            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_99" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_99" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_99"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 99</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_99" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_99" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an on-premises application that collects data and stores it to an on-premises
                            NFS server. The company recently set up a 10 Gbps AWS Direct Connect connection. The company
                            is running out of storage capacity on premises. The company needs to migrate the application
                            data from on premises to the AWS Cloud while maintaining low-latency access to the data from
                            the on-premises application.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to meet these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Deploy AWS Storage Gateway for the application data, and use the file gateway to
                                    store the data in Amazon S3. Connect the on-premises application servers to the file
                                    gateway using NFS.</li>
                                <li> Attach an Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) file system to the NFS server,
                                    and copy the application data to the EFS file system. Then connect the on-premises
                                    application to Amazon EFS.</li>
                                <li> Configure AWS Storage Gateway as a volume gateway. Make the application data
                                    available to the on- premises application from the NFS server and with Amazon
                                    Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) snapshots.</li>
                                <li> Create an AWS DataSync agent with the NFS server as the source location and an
                                    Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) file system as the destination for
                                    application data transfer. Connect the on-premises application to the EFS file
                                    system.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ99">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer99" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ99" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_99" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_99" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_100" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_100" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_100"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 100</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_100" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_100" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is planning on deploying a newly built application on AWS in a default VPC. The
                            application will consist of a web layer and database layer. The web server was created in
                            public subnets, and the MySQL database was created in private subnets. All subnets are
                            created with the default network ACL settings, and the default security group in the VPC
                            will be replaced with new custom security groups.<br /><br />The following are the key
                            requirements:<br />The web servers must be accessible only to users on an SSL
                            connection.<br />The database should be accessible to the web layer, which is created in a
                            public subnet only. <br />All traffic to and from the IP range 182.20.0.0/16 subnet should
                            be blocked.<br /><br />Which combination of steps meets these requirements? (Select two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create a database server security group with inbound and outbound rules for MySQL
                                    port 3306 traffic to and from anywhere (0 0.0.0/0).</li>
                                <li> Create a database server security group with an inbound rule for MySQL port 3306
                                    and specify the source as a web server security group.</li>
                                <li> Create a web server security group with an inbound allow rule for HTTPS port 443
                                    traffic from anywhere (0.0.0.0/0) and an inbound deny rule for IP range
                                    182.20.0.0/16.</li>
                                <li> Create a web server security group with an inbound rule for HTTPS port 443 traffic
                                    from anywhere (0.0.0.0/0). Create network ACL inbound and outbound deny rules for IP
                                    range 182.20.0.0/16.</li>
                                <li> Create a web server security group with inbound and outbound rules for HTTPS port
                                    443 traffic to and from anywhere (0.0.0.0/0). Create a network ACL inbound deny rule
                                    for IP range 182.20.0.0/16.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ100">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer100" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B,D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ100" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_100" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_100" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>

<div class="product-info-box questions">
    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_101" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_101" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_101"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 101</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_101" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_101" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company recently migrated a message processing system to AWS. The system receives messages
                            into an ActiveMQ queue running on an Amazon EC2 instance. Messages are processed by a
                            consumer application running on Amazon EC2. The consumer application processes the messages
                            and writes results to a MySQL database running on Amazon EC2. The company wants this
                            application to be highly available with low operational complexity.<br /><br />Which
                            architecture offers the HIGHEST availability?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Add a second ActiveMQ server to another Availability Zone. Add an additional
                                    consumer EC2 instance in another Availability Zone Replicate the MySQL database to
                                    another Availability Zone.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon MQ with active/standby brokers configured across two Availability Zones.
                                    Add an additional consumer EC2 instance in another Availability Zone. Replicate the
                                    MySQL database to another Availability Zone.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon MQ with active/standby brokers configured across two Availability Zones.
                                    Add an additional consumer EC2 instance in another Availability Zone. Use Amazon RDS
                                    for MySQL with Multi-AZ enabled.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon MQ with active/standby brokers configured across two Availability Zones.
                                    Add an Auto Scaling group for the consumer EC2 instances across two Availability
                                    Zones. Use Amazon RDS for MySQL with Multi-AZ enabled.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ101">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer101" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ101" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_101" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_101" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_102" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_102" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_102"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 102</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_102" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_102" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is moving its on-premises Oracle database to Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL. The
                            database has several applications that write to the same tables. The applications need to be
                            migrated one by one with a month in between each migration Management has expressed concerns
                            that the database has a high number of reads and writes. The data must be kept in sync
                            across both databases throughout tie migration.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect
                            recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use AWS DataSync for the initial migration. Use AWS Database Migration Service (AWS
                                    DMS) to create a change data capture (CDC) replication task and a table mapping to
                                    select all cables.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS DataSync for the initial migration. Use AWS Database Migration Service (AWS
                                    DMS) to create a full load plus change data capture (CDC) replication task and a
                                    table mapping to select all tables.</li>
                                <li> Use the AWS Schema Conversion Tool with AWS DataBase Migration Service (AWS DMS)
                                    using a memory optimized replication instance. Create a full load plus change data
                                    capture (CDC) replication task and a table mapping to select all tables.</li>
                                <li> Use the AWS Schema Conversion Tool with AWS Database Migration Service (AWS DMS)
                                    using a compute optimized replication instance. Create a full load plus change data
                                    capture (CDC) replication task and a table mapping to select the largest tables.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ102">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer102" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ102" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_102" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_102" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_103" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_103" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_103"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 103</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_103" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_103" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has developed a new video game as a web application. The application is in a
                            three-tier architecture in a VPC with Amazon RDS for MySQL. In the database layer several
                            players will compete concurrently online. The game’s developers want to display a top-10
                            scoreboard in near-real time and offer the ability to stop and restore the game while
                            preserving the current scores.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to meet these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Set up an Amazon ElastiCache for Memcached cluster to cache the scores for the web
                                    application to display.</li>
                                <li> Set up an Amazon ElastiCache for Redis cluster to compute and cache the scores for
                                    the web application to display.</li>
                                <li> Place an Amazon CloudFront distribution in front of the web application to cache
                                    the scoreboard in a section of the application.</li>
                                <li> Create a read replica on Amazon RDS for MySQL to run queries to compute the
                                    scoreboard and serve the read traffic to the web application.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ103">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer103" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_104" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_104" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_104"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 104</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_104" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_104" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company hosts its multi-tier public web application in the AWS Cloud. The web application
                            runs on Amazon EC2 instances and its database runs on Amazon RDS. The company is
                            anticipating a large increase in sales during an upcoming holiday weekend. A solutions
                            architect needs to build a solution to analyze the performance of the web application with a
                            granularity of no more than 2 minutes.<br /><br />What should the solutions architect do to
                            meet this requirement?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Send Amazon CloudWatch logs to Amazon Redshift. Use Amazon QuickSight to perform
                                    further analysis.</li>
                                <li> Enable detailed monitoring on all EC2 instances. Use Amazon CloudWatch metrics to
                                    perform further analysis.</li>
                                <li> Create an AWS Lambda function to fetch EC2 logs from Amazon CloudWatch Logs. Use
                                    Amazon CloudWatch metrics to perform further analysis.</li>
                                <li> Send EC2 logs to Amazon S3. Use Amazon Redshift to fetch logs from the S3 bucket to
                                    process raw data for further analysis with Amazon QuickSight.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ104">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer104" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_105" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_105" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_105"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 105</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_105" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_105" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company’s website hosted on Amazon EC2 instances processes classified data stored in
                            Amazon S3. Due to security concerns, the company requires a private and secure connection
                            between its EC2 resources and Amazon S3.<br /><br />Which solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Set up S3 bucket policies to allow access from a VPC endpoint.</li>
                                <li> Set up an IAM policy to grant read-write access to the S3 bucket.</li>
                                <li> Set up a NAT gateway to access resources outside the private subnet.</li>
                                <li> Set up an access key ID and a secret access key to access the S3 bucket.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ105">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer105" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>

        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_106" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_106" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_106"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 106</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_106" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_106" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has two applications: a sender application that sends messages with payloads to be
                            processed and a processing application intended to receive messages with payloads. The
                            company wants to implement an AWS service to handle messages between the two applications.
                            The sender application can send about 1,000 messages each hour. The messages may take up to
                            2 days to be processed. If the messages fail to process, they must be retained so that they
                            do not impact the processing of any remaining messages.<br /><br />Which solution meets
                            these requirements and is the MOST operationally efficient?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Set up an Amazon EC2 instance running a Redis database. Configure both applications
                                    to use the instance. Store, process, and delete the messages, respectively.</li>
                                <li> Use an Amazon Kinesis data stream to receive the messages from the sender
                                    application. Integrate the processing application with the Kinesis Client Library
                                    (KCL).</li>
                                <li> Integrate the sender and processor applications with an Amazon Simple Queue Service
                                    (Amazon SQS) queue. Configure a dead-letter queue to collect the messages that
                                    failed to process.</li>
                                <li> Subscribe the processing application to an Amazon Simple Notification Service
                                    (Amazon SNS) topic to receive notifications to process. Integrate the sender
                                    application to write to the SNS topic.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ106">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer106" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>

                    <a aria-controls="collapse_107" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_107"

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 107</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_107" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_107" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an application that is hosted on Amazon EC2 instances in two private subnets.
                            A solutions architect must make the application available on the public internet with the
                            least amount of administrative effort. What should the solutions architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create a load balancer and associate two public subnets from the same Availability
                                    Zones as the private instances. Add the private instances to the load balancer.</li>
                                <li> Create a load balancer and associate two private subnets from the same Availability
                                    Zones as the private instances. Add the private instances to the load balancer.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Machine Image (AMI) of the instances in the private subnet and
                                    restore in the public subnet. Create a load balancer and associate two public
                                    subnets from the same Availability Zones as the public instances.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Machine Image (AMI) of the instances in the private subnet and
                                    restore in the public subnet. Create a load balancer and associate two private
                                    subnets from the same Availability Zones as the public instances.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ107">

                    <a aria-controls="collapse_108" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_108"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 108</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_108" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_108" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A user wants to list the IAM role that is attached to their Amazon EC2 instance. The user
                            has login access to the EC2 instance but does not have IAM permissions.<br /><br />What
                            should a solutions architect do to retrieve this information?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Run the following EC2 command:<br />curl
                                    http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/info</li>
                                <li> Run the following EC2 command:<br />curl
                                    http://169.254.169.254/latest/user-data/iam/info</li>
                                <li> Run the following EC2
                                    command:<br />http://169.254.169.254/latest/dynamic/instance-identity/</li>
                                <li> Run the following AWS CLI command:<br />aws iam get-instance-profile
                                    --instance-profile-name ExampleInstanceProfile</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ108">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer108" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>

                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">

                                <p>
                                    https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/iam-roles-for-amazon-ec2.html

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_109" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_109" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_109"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 109</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_109" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_109" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect is designing the architecture of a new application being deployed to
                            the AWS Cloud. The application will run on Amazon EC2 On-Demand Instances and will
                            automatically scale across multiple Availability Zones. The EC2 instances will scale up and
                            down frequently throughout the day. An Application Load Balancer (ALB) will handle the load
                            distribution. The architecture needs to support distributed session data management. The
                            company is willing to make changes to code if needed.<br /><br />What should the solutions
                            architect do to ensure that the architecture supports distributed session data management?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon ElastiCache to manage and store session data.</li>
                                <li> Use session affinity (sticky sessions) of the ALB to manage session data.</li>
                                <li> Use Session Manager from AWS Systems Manager to manage the session.</li>
                                <li> Use the GetSessionToken API operation in AWS Security Token Service (AWS STS) to
                                    manage the session.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ109">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer109" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_110" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_110" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_110"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 110</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_110" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_110" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A software vendor is deploying a new software-as-a-service (SaaS) solution that will be
                            utilized by many AWS users. The service is hosted in a VPC behind a Network Load Balancer.
                            The software vendor wants to provide access to this service to users with the least amount
                            of administrative overhead and without exposing the service to the public internet.<br />
                            <br />What should a solutions architect do to accomplish this goal?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create a peering VPC connection from each user’s VPC to the software vendor’s VPC.
                                </li>
                                <li> Deploy a transit VPC in the software vendor’s AWS account. Create a VPN connection
                                    with each user account.</li>
                                <li> Connect the service in the VPC with an AWS Private Link endpoint. Have users
                                    subscribe to the endpoint.</li>
                                <li> Deploy a transit VPC in the software vendor’s AWS account. Create an AWS Direct
                                    Connect connection with each user account.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ110">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer110" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>

<div class="product-info-box questions">
    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_111" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_111" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_111"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 111</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_111" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_111" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company wants to move a multi-tiered application from on premises to the AWS Cloud to
                            improve the application’s performance. The application consists of application tiers that
                            communicate with each other by way of RESTful services. Transactions are dropped when one
                            tier becomes overloaded. A solutions architect must design a solution that resolves these
                            issues and modernizes the application.<br /><br />Which solution meets these requirements
                            and is the MOST operationally efficient?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon API Gateway and direct transactions to the AWS Lambda functions as the
                                    application layer. Use Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) as the communication
                                    layer between application services.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon CloudWatch metrics to analyze the application performance history to
                                    determine the server’s peak utilization during the performance failures. Increase
                                    the size of the application server’s Amazon EC2 instances to meet the peak
                                    requirements.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS) to handle the messaging between
                                    application servers running on Amazon EC2 in an Auto Scaling group. Use Amazon
                                    CloudWatch to monitor the SNS queue length and scale up and down as required.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) to handle the messaging between
                                    application servers running on Amazon EC2 in an Auto Scaling group. Use Amazon
                                    CloudWatch to monitor the SQS queue length and scale up when communication failures
                                    are detected.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ111">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer111" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ111" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_111" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_111" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_112" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_112" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_112"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 112</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_112" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_112" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect needs to design a resilient solution for Windows users’ home
                            directories. The solution must provide fault tolerance, file-level backup and recovery, and
                            access control, based upon the company’s Active Directory.<br /><br />Which storage solution
                            meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure Amazon S3 to store the users’ home directories. Join Amazon S3 to Active
                                    Directory.</li>
                                <li> Configure a Multi-AZ file system with Amazon FSx for Windows File Server. Join
                                    Amazon FSx to Active Directory.</li>
                                <li> Configure Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) for the users’ home directories.
                                    Configure AWS Single Sign-On with Active Directory.</li>
                                <li> Configure Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EFS) to store the users’ home
                                    directories. Configure AWS Single Sign-On with Active Directory.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ112">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer112" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ112" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_112" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_112" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_113" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_113" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_113"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 113</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_113" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_113" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is building an application on Amazon EC2 instances that generates temporary
                            transactional data. The application requires access to data storage that can provide
                            configurable and consistent IOPS.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Provision an EC2 instance with a Throughput Optimized HDD (st1) root volume and a
                                    Cold HDD (sc1) data volume.</li>
                                <li> Provision an EC2 instance with a Throughput Optimized HDD (st1) volume that will
                                    serve as the root and data volume.</li>
                                <li> Provision an EC2 instance with a General Purpose SSD (gp2) root volume and
                                    Provisioned IOPS SSD (io1) data volume.</li>
                                <li> Provision an EC2 instance with a General Purpose SSD (gp2) root volume. Configure
                                    the application to store its data in an Amazon S3 bucket.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ113">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer113" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_114" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_114" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_114"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 114</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_114" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_114" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is launching a new application deployed on an Amazon Elastic Container Service
                            (Amazon ECS) cluster and is using the Fargate launch type for ECS tasks. The company is
                            monitoring CPU and memory usage because it is expecting high traffic to the application upon
                            its launch. However, the company wants to reduce costs when utilization
                            decreases.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling to scale at certain periods based on previous traffic
                                    patterns.</li>
                                <li> Use an AWS Lambda function to scale Amazon ECS based on metric breaches that
                                    trigger an Amazon CloudWatch alarm.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling with simple scaling policies to scale when ECS metric
                                    breaches trigger an Amazon CloudWatch alarm.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS Application Auto Scaling with target tracking policies to scale when ECS
                                    metric breaches trigger an Amazon CloudWatch alarm.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ114">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer114" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>

                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is moving its on-premises applications to Amazon EC2 instances. However, as a
                            result of fluctuating compute requirements, the EC2 instances must always be ready to use
                            between 8 AM and 5 PM in specific Availability Zones.<br /><br />Which EC2 instances should
                            the company choose to run the applications?
                        </p>
                        <div>

                                <li> Scheduled Reserved Instances</li>
                                <li> On-Demand Instances</li>
                                <li> Spot Instances as part of a Spot Fleet</li>
                                <li> EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling group</li>
                            </ol>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_116" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_116" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_116"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 116</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_116" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_116" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company owns an asynchronous API that is used to ingest user requests and, based on the
                            request type, dispatch requests to the appropriate microservice for processing. The company
                            is using Amazon API Gateway to deploy the API front end, and an AWS Lambda function that
                            invokes Amazon DynamoDB to store user requests before dispatching them to the processing
                            microservices.<br /><br />The company provisioned as much DynamoDB throughput as its budget
                            allows, but the company is still experiencing availability issues and is losing user
                            requests.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to address this issue without
                            impacting existing users?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Add throttling on the API Gateway with server-side throttling limits.</li>
                                <li> Use DynamoDB Accelerator (DAX) and Lambda to buffer writes to DynamoD</li>
                                <li> Create a secondary index in DynamoDB for the table with the user requests.</li>
                                <li> Use the Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) queue and Lambda to buffer writes
                                    to DynamoDB.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ116">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer116" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_117" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_117" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_117"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 117</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_117" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_117" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company hosts historical weather records in Amazon S3. The records are downloaded from the
                            company’s website by a way of a URL that resolves to a domain name. Users all over the world
                            access this content through subscriptions. A third-party provider hosts the company’s root
                            domain name, but the company recently migrated some of its services to Amazon Route 53. The
                            company wants to consolidate contracts, reduce latency for users, and reduce costs related
                            to serving the application to subscribers.<br /><br />Which solution meets these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create a web distribution on Amazon CloudFront to serve the S3 content for the
                                    application. Create a CNAME record in a Route 53 hosted zone that points to the
                                    CloudFront distribution, resolving to the application’s URL domain name.</li>
                                <li> Create a web distribution on Amazon CloudFront to serve the S3 content for the
                                    application. Create an ALIAS record in the Amazon Route 53 hosted zone that points
                                    to the CloudFront distribution, resolving to the application’s URL domain name.</li>
                                <li> Create an A record in a Route 53 hosted zone for the application. Create a Route 53
                                    traffic policy for the web application, and configure a geolocation rule. Configure
                                    health checks to check the health of the endpoint and route DNS queries to other
                                    endpoints if an endpoint is unhealthy.</li>
                                <li> Create an A record in a Route 53 hosted zone for the application. Create a Route 53
                                    traffic policy for the web application, and configure a geoproximity rule. Configure
                                    health checks to check the health of the endpoint and route DNS queries to other
                                    endpoints if an endpoint is unhealthy.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ117">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer117" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_118" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_118" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_118"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 118</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_118" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_118" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect is creating a new VPC design. There are two public subnets for the
                            load balancer, two private subnets for web servers, and two private subnets for MySQL. The
                            web servers use only HTTPS. The solutions architect has already created a security group for
                            the load balancer allowing port 443 from 0.0.0.0/0. Company policy requires that each
                            resource has the least access required to still be able to perform its
                            tasks.<br /><br />Which additional configuration strategy should the solutions architect use
                            to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create a security group for the web servers and allow port 443 from 0.0.0.0/0.
                                    Create a security group for the MySQL servers and allow port 3306 from the web
                                    servers security group.</li>
                                <li> Create a network ACL for the web servers and allow port 443 from 0.0.0.0/0. Create
                                    a network ACL for the MySQL servers and allow port 3306 from the web servers
                                    security group.</li>
                                <li> Create a security group for the web servers and allow port 443 from the load
                                    balancer. Create a security group for the MySQL servers and allow port 3306 from the
                                    web servers security group.</li>
                                <li> Create a network ACL for the web servers and allow port 443 from the load balancer.
                                    Create a network ACL for the MySQL servers and allow port 3306 from the web servers
                                    security group.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ118">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer118" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_119" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_119" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_119"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 119</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_119" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_119" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company runs an application on an Amazon EC2 instance backed by Amazon Elastic Block Store
                            (Amazon EBS). The instance needs to be available for 12 hours daily. The company wants to
                            save costs by making the instance unavailable outside the window required for the
                            application. However, the contents of the instance’s memory must be preserved whenever the
                            instance is unavailable.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to meet this
                            requirement?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Stop the instance outside the application’s availability window. Start up the
                                    instance again when required.</li>
                                <li> Hibernate the instance outside the application’s availability window. Start up the
                                    instance again when required.</li>
                                <li> Use Auto Scaling to scale down the instance outside the application’s availability
                                    window. Scale up the instance when required.</li>
                                <li> Terminate the instance outside the application’s availability window. Launch the
                                    instance by using a preconfigured Amazon Machine Image (AMI) when required.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ119">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer119" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_120" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_120" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_120"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 120</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_120" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_120" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect is designing a solution that requires frequent updates to a website
                            that is hosted on Amazon S3 with versioning enabled. For compliance reasons, the older
                            versions of the objects will not be accessed frequently and will need to be deleted after 2
                            years.<br /><br />What should the solutions architect recommend to meet these requirements
                            at the LOWEST cost?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use S3 batch operations to replace object tags. Expire the objects based on the
                                    modified tags.</li>
                                <li> Configure an S3 Lifecycle policy to transition older versions of objects to S3
                                    Glacier. Expire the objects after 2 years.</li>
                                <li> Enable S3 Event Notifications on the bucket that sends older objects to the Amazon
                                    Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) queue for further processing.</li>
                                <li> Replicate older object versions to a new bucket. Use an S3 Lifecycle policy to
                                    expire the objects in the new bucket after 2 years.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ120">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer120" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ120" role="button">

                <div aria-labelledby="heading_121" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_121" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A business application is hosted on Amazon EC2 and uses Amazon S3 for encrypted object
                            storage. The chief information security officer has directed that no application traffic
                            between the two services should traverse the public internet.<br /><br />Which capability
                            should the solutions architect use to meet the compliance requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS)</li>
                                <li> VPC endpoint</li>
                                <li> Private subnet</li>
                                <li> Virtual private gateway</li>
                            </ol>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_122" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_122" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_122"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 122</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_122" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_122" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company hosts its application in the AWS Cloud. The application runs on Amazon EC2
                            instances behind an Elastic Load Balancer in an Auto Scaling group and with an Amazon
                            DynamoDB table. The company wants to ensure the application can be made available in another
                            AWS Region with minimal downtime.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to meet
                            these requirements with the LEAST amount of downtime?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an Auto Scaling group and a load balancer in the disaster recovery Region.
                                    Configure the DynamoDB table as a global table. Configure DNS failover to point to
                                    the new disaster recovery Region’s load balancer.</li>
                                <li> Create an AWS CloudFormation template to create EC2 instances, load balancers, and
                                    DynamoDB tables to be executed when needed. Configure DNS failover to point to the
                                    new disaster recovery Region’s load balancer.</li>
                                <li> Create an AWS CloudFormation template to create EC2 instances and a load balancer
                                    to be executed when needed. Configure the DynamoDB table as a global table.
                                    Configure DNS failover to point to the new disaster recovery Region’s load balancer.
                                </li>
                                <li> Create an Auto Scaling group and load balancer in the disaster recovery Region.
                                    Configure the DynamoDB table as a global table. Create an Amazon CloudWatch alarm to
                                    trigger and AWS Lambda function that updates Amazon Route 53 pointing to the
                                    disaster recovery load balancer.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ122">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer122" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_123" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_123" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_123"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 123</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_123" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_123" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect is designing a new API using Amazon API Gateway that will receive
                            requests from users. The volume of requests is highly variable; several hours can pass
                            without receiving a single request. The data processing will take place asynchronously, but
                            should be completed within a few seconds after a request is made.<br /><br />Which compute
                            service should the solutions architect have the API invoke to deliver the requirements at
                            the lowest cost?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> An AWS Glue job</li>
                                <li> An AWS Lambda function</li>
                                <li> A containerized service hosted in Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS)
                                </li>
                                <li> A containerized service hosted in Amazon ECS with Amazon EC2</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ123">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer123" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ123" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_123" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_123" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_124" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_124" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_124"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 124</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_124" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_124" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company serves a multilingual website from a fleet of Amazon EC2 instances behind an
                            Application Load Balancer (ALB). This architecture is currently running in the us-west-1
                            Region but is exhibiting high request latency for users located in other parts of the
                            world.<br /><br />The website needs to serve requests quickly and efficiently regardless of
                            a user’s location. However, the company does not want to recreate the existing architecture
                            across multiple Regions.<br /><br />How should a solutions architect accomplish this?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Replace the existing architecture with a website served from an Amazon S3 bucket.
                                    Configure an Amazon CloudFront distribution with the S3 bucket as the origin.</li>
                                <li> Configure an Amazon CloudFront distribution with the ALB as the origin. Set the
                                    cache behavior settings to only cache based on the Accept-Language request header.
                                </li>
                                <li> Set up Amazon API Gateway with the ALB as an integration. Configure API Gateway to
                                    use an HTTP integration type. Set up an API Gateway stage to enable the API cache.
                                </li>
                                <li> Launch an EC2 instance in each additional Region and configure NGINX to act as a
                                    cache server for that Region. Put all the instances plus the ALB behind an Amazon
                                    Route 53 record set with a geolocation routing policy.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ124">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer124" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ124" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_124" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_124" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_125" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_125" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_125"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 125</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_125" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_125" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has a custom application with embedded credentials that retrieves information from
                            an Amazon RDS MySQL DB instance. Management says the application must be made more secure
                            with the least amount of programming effort.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do
                            to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) customer master keys (CMKs) to create
                                    keys. Configure the application to load the database credentials from AWS KMS.
                                    Enable automatic key rotation.</li>
                                <li> Create credentials on the RDS for MySQL database for the application user and store
                                    the credentials in AWS Secrets Manager. Configure the application to load the
                                    database credentials from Secrets Manager. Create an AWS Lambda function that
                                    rotates the credentials in Secret Manager.</li>
                                <li> Create credentials on the RDS for MySQL database for the application user and store
                                    the credentials in AWS Secrets Manager. Configure the application to load the
                                    database credentials from Secrets Manager. Set up a credentials rotation schedule
                                    for the application user in the RDS for MySQL database using Secrets Manager.</li>
                                <li> Create credentials on the RDS for MySQL database for the application user and store
                                    the credentials in AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store. Configure the application to
                                    load the database credentials from Parameter Store. Set up a credentials rotation
                                    schedule for the application user in the RDS for MySQL database using Parameter
                                    Store.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ125">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer125" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ125" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_125" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_125" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
