            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_202" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_202" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_202"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 202</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_202" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_202" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company runs an online marketplace web application on AWS. The application serves hundreds
                            of thousands of users during peak hours. The company needs a scalable, near-real-time
                            solution to share the details of millions of financial transactions with several other
                            internal applications. Transactions also need to be processed to remove sensitive data
                            before being stored in a document database for low-latency retrieval.<br /><br />What should
                            a solutions architect recommend to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Store the transactions data into Amazon DynamoDB. Set up a rule in DynamoDB to
                                    remove sensitive data from every transaction upon write. Use DynamoDB Streams to
                                    share the transactions data with other applications.</li>
                                <li> Stream the transactions data into Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose to store data in
                                    Amazon DynamoDB and Amazon S3. Use AWS Lambda integration with Kinesis Data Firehose
                                    to remove sensitive data. Other applications can consume the data stored in Amazon
                                    S3.</li>
                                <li> Stream the transactions data into Amazon Kinesis Data Streams. Use AWS Lambda
                                    integration to remove sensitive data from every transaction and then store the
                                    transactions data in AmazonDynamoDB. Other applications can consume the transactions
                                    data off the Kinesis data stream.</li>
                                <li> Store the batched transactions data in Amazon S3 as files. Use AWS Lambda to
                                    process every file and remove sensitive data before updating the files in Amazon S3.
                                    The Lambda function then stores the data in Amazon DynamoDB. Other applications can
                                    consume transaction files stored in Amazon S3.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ202">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer202" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 203</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>

                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_203" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_203" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has a three-tier environment on AWS that ingests sensor data from its users’
                            devices. The traffic flows through a Network Load Balancer (NLB) then to Amazon EC2
                            instances for the web tier, and finally toEC2 instances for the application tier that makes
                            database calls.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to improve the security of
                            data in transit to the web tier?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure a TLS listener and add the server certificate on the NLB.</li>
                                <li> Configure AWS Shield Advanced and enable AWS WAF on the NL</li>
                                <li> Change the load balancer to an Application Load Balancer and attach AWS WAF to it.
                                </li>
                                <li> Encrypt the Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) volume on the EC2 instances
                                    using AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS).</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">

                    <a aria-controls="collapse_204" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_204"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 204</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_204" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_204" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has several Amazon EC2 instances set up in a private subnet for security reasons.
                            These instances host applications that read and write large amounts of data to and from
                            Amazon S3 regularly. Currently, subnet routing directs all the traffic destined for the
                            internet through a NAT gateway. The company wants to optimize the overall cost without
                            impacting the ability of the application to communicate with Amazon S3 or the outside
                            internet.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to optimize costs?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an additional NAT gateway. Update the route table to route to the NAT
                                    gateway. Update the network ACL to allow S3 traffic.</li>
                                <li> Create an internet gateway. Update the route table to route traffic to the internet
                                    gateway. Update the network ACL to allow S3 traffic.</li>
                                <li> Create a VPC endpoint for Amazon S3. Attach an endpoint policy to the endpoint.
                                    Update the route table to direct traffic to the VPC endpoint.</li>
                                <li> Create an AWS Lambda function outside of the VPC to handle S3 requests. Attach an
                                    IAM policy to the EC2 instances, allowing them to invoke the Lambda function.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>

                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an API-based inventory reporting application running on Amazon EC2 instances.
                            The application stores information in an Amazon DynamoDB table. The company’s distribution
                            centers have an on- premises shipping application that calls an API to update the inventory
                            before printing shipping labels. The company has been experiencing application interruptions
                            several times each day, resulting in lost transactions.<br /><br />What should a solutions
                            architect recommend to improve application resiliency?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Modify the shipping application to write to a local database.</li>
                                <li> Modify the application APIs to run serverless using AWS Lambda</li>
                                <li> Configure Amazon API Gateway to call the EC2 inventory application APIs.</li>
                                <li> Modify the application to send inventory updates using Amazon Simple Queue Service
                                    (Amazon SQS).</li>

                    <a aria-controls="collapse_206" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_206"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 206</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_206" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_206" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An ecommerce website is deploying its web application as Amazon Elastic Container Service
                            (Amazon ECS) container instances behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB). During periods
                            of high activity, the website slows down and availability is reduced. A solutions architect
                            uses Amazon CloudWatch alarms to receive notifications whenever there is an availability
                            issue so they can scale out resources. Company management wants a solution that
                            automatically responds to such events.<br /><br />Which solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Set up AWS Auto Scaling to scale out the ECS service when there are timeouts on the
                                    ALB. Set up AWS Auto Scaling to scale out the ECS cluster when the CPU or memory
                                    reservation is too high.</li>
                                <li> Set up AWS Auto Scaling to scale out the ECS service when the ALB CPU utilization
                                    is too high. Setup AWS Auto Scaling to scale out the ECS cluster when the CPU or
                                    memory reservation is too high.</li>
                                <li> Set up AWS Auto Scaling to scale out the ECS service when the service’s CPU
                                    utilization is too high. Set up AWS Auto Scaling to scale out the ECS cluster when
                                    the CPU or memory reservation is too high.</li>
                                <li> Set up AWS Auto Scaling to scale out the ECS service when the ALB target group CPU
                                    utilization is too high. Set up AWS Auto Scaling to scale out the ECS cluster when
                                    the CPU or memory reservation is too high.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ206">

                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_207" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_207" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An application uses an Amazon RDS MySQL DB instance. The RDS database is becoming low on
                            disk space. A solutions architect wants to increase the disk space without downtime. Which
                            solution meets these requirements with the LEAST amount of effort?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Enable storage auto scaling in RDS.</li>
                                <li> Increase the RDS database instance size.</li>
                                <li> Change the RDS database instance storage type to Provisioned IOPS.</li>
                                <li> Back up the RDS database, increase the storage capacity, restore the database and
                                    stop the previous instance.</li>
                            </ol>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_208" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_208" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_208"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 208</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_208" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_208" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company hosts a website on premises and wants to migrate it to the AWS Cloud. The website
                            exposes a single hostname to the internet but it routes its functions to different
                            on-premises server groups based on the path of the URL. The server groups are scaled
                            independently depending on the needs of the functions they support. The company has an AWS
                            Direct Connect connection configured to its on-premises network.<br /><br />What should a
                            solutions architect do to provide path-based routing to send the traffic to the correct
                            group of servers?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Route all traffic to an internet gateway. Configure pattern matching rules at the
                                    internet gateway to route traffic to the group of servers supporting that path.</li>
                                <li> Route all traffic to a Network Load Balancer (NLB) with target groups for each
                                    group of servers. Use pattern matching rules at the NLB to route traffic to the
                                    correct target group.</li>
                                <li> Route all traffic to an Application Load Balancer (ALB). Configure path-based
                                    routing at the ALB to route traffic to the correct target group for the servers
                                    supporting that path.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Route 53 as the DNS server. Configure Route 53 path-based alias records
                                    to route traffic to the correct Elastic Load Balancer for the group of servers
                                    supporting that path.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ208">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer208" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>

                <div aria-labelledby="heading_209" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_209" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an application that runs on Amazon EC2 instances within a private subnet in a
                            VPC. The instances access data in an Amazon S3 bucket in the same AWS Region. The VPC
                            contains a NAT gateway in a public subnet to access the S3 bucket. The company wants to
                            reduce costs by replacing the NAT gateway without compromising security or
                            redundancy.<br /><br />Which solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Replace the NAT gateway with a NAT instance.</li>
                                <li> Replace the NAT gateway with an internet gateway.</li>
                                <li> Replace the NAT gateway with a gateway VPC endpoint.</li>
                                <li> Replace the NAT gateway with an AWS Direct Connect connection.</li>
                            </ol>

            <div class="panel panel-default">

                    <a aria-controls="collapse_210" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_210"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 210</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_210" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_210" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A mobile gaming company runs application servers on Amazon EC2 instances. The servers
                            receive updates from players every 15 minutes. The mobile game creates a JSON object of the
                            progress made in the game since the last update, and sends the JSON object to an Application
                            Load Balancer. As the mobile game is played, game updates are being lost. The company wants
                            to create a durable way to get the updates in older.<br /><br />What should a solutions
                            architect recommend to decouple the system?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon Kinesis Data Streams to capture the data and store the JSON object in
                                    Amazon S3.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose to capture the data and store the JSON object in
                                    Amazon S3.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) FIFO queues to capture the data and
                                    EC2 instances to process the messages in the queue.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS) to capture the data and EC2
                                    instances to process the messages sent to the Application Load Balancer.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ210">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer210" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C

<div class="product-info-box questions">
    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_211" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_211" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_211"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 211</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_211" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_211" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company previously migrated its data warehouse solution to AWS. The company also has an
                            AWS Direct Connect connection. Corporate office users query the data warehouse using a
                            visualization tool. The average size of a query returned by the data warehouse is 50 MB and
                            each webpage sent by the visualization tool is approximately 500 KB. Result sets returned by
                            the data warehouse are not cached.<br /><br />Which solution provides the LOWEST data
                            transfer egress cost for the company?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Host the visualization tool on premises and query the data warehouse directly over
                                    the internet.</li>
                                <li> Host the visualization tool in the same AWS Region as the data warehouse. Access it
                                    over the internet.</li>
                                <li> Host the visualization tool on premises and query the data warehouse directly over
                                    a Direct Connect connection at a location in the same AWS Region.</li>
                                <li> Host the visualization tool in the same AWS Region as the data warehouse and access
                                    it over a DirectConnect connection at a location in the same Region.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ211">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer211" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ211" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_211" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_211" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_212" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_212" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_212"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 212</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_212" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_212" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an application that generates a large number of files, each approximately 5 MB
                            in size. The files are stored in Amazon S3. Company policy requires the files to be stored
                            for 4 years before they can be deleted. Immediate accessibility is always required as the
                            files contain critical business data that is not easy to reproduce. The files are frequently
                            accessed in the first 30 days of the object creation but are rarely accessed after the first
                            30 days.<br /><br />Which storage solution is MOST cost-effective?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an S3 bucket lifecycle policy to move files from S3 Standard to S3 Glacier
                                    30 days from object creation. Delete the files 4 years after object creation.</li>
                                <li> Create an S3 bucket lifecycle policy to move files from S3 Standard to S3 One
                                    Zone-Infrequent Access (S3 One Zone-IA) 30 days from object creation. Delete the
                                    files 4 years after object creation.</li>
                                <li> Create an S3 bucket lifecycle policy to move files from S3 Standard to S3
                                    Standard-Infrequent Access (S3 Standard-IA) 30 days from object creation. Delete the
                                    files 4 years after object creation.</li>
                                <li> Create an S3 bucket lifecycle policy to move files from S3 Standard to S3
                                    Standard-Infrequent Access (S3 Standard-IA) 30 days from object creation. Move the
                                    files to S3 Glacier 4 years after object creation.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ212">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer212" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ212" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_212" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_212" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_213" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_213" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_213"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 213</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_213" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_213" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is preparing to deploy a data lake on AWS. A solutions architect must define the
                            encryption strategy tor data at rest m Amazon S3/ The company’s security policy
                            states:<br /><br />Keys must be rotated every 90 days.<br />Strict separation of duties
                            between key users and key administrators must be implemented.<br />Auditing key usage must
                            be possible.<br /><br />What should the solutions architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Server-side encryption with AWS KMS managed keys (SSE-KMS) with customer managed
                                    customer master keys (CMKs)</li>
                                <li> Server-side encryption with AWS KMS managed keys (SSE-KMS) with AWS managed
                                    customer master keys (CMKs)</li>
                                <li> Server-side encryption with Amazon S3 managed keys (SSE-S3) with customer managed
                                    customer master keys (CMKs)</li>
                                <li> Server-side encryption with Amazon S3 managed keys (SSE-S3) with AWS managed
                                    customer master keys (CMKs)</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ213">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer213" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_214" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_214" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_214"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 214</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_214" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_214" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has 700 TB of backup data stored in network attached storage (NAS) in its data
                            center This backup data need to be accessible for infrequent regulatory requests and must be
                            retained 7 years. The company has decided to migrate this backup data from its data center
                            to AWS. The migration must be complete within 1 month. The company has 500 Mbps of dedicated
                            bandwidth on its public internet connection available for data transfer.<br /><br />What
                            should a solutions architect do to migrate and store the data at the LOWEST cost?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Order AWS Snowball devices to transfer the data. Use a lifecycle policy to
                                    transition the files to Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Archive.</li>
                                <li> Deploy a VPN connection between the data center and Amazon VPC. Use the AWS CLI to
                                    copy the data from on premises to Amazon S3 Glacier.</li>
                                <li> Provision a 500 Mbps AWS Direct Connect connection and transfer the data to Amazon
                                    S3. Use a lifecycle policy to transition the files to Amazon S3 Glacier Deep
                                    Archive.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS DataSync to transfer the data and deploy a DataSync agent on premises. Use
                                    the DataSync task to copy files from the on-premises NAS storage to Amazon S3
                                    Glacier.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ214">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer214" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ214" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_214" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_214" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 215</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_215" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_215" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company hosts its web application on AWS using seven Amazon EC2 instances. The company
                            requires that the IP addresses of all healthy EC2 instances be returned in response to DNS
                            queries.<br /><br />Which policy should be used to meet this requirement?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Simple routing policy</li>
                                <li> Latency routing policy</li>
                                <li> Multi-value routing policy</li>
                                <li> Geolocation routing policy</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_216" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_216" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_216"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 216</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_216" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_216" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is selling up an application to use an Amazon RDS MySQL DB instance. The database
                            must be architected for high availability across Availability Zones and AWS Regions with
                            minimal downtime.<br /><br />How should a solutions architect meet this requirement?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Set up an RDS MySQL Multi-AZ DB instance. Configure an appropriate backup window.
                                </li>
                                <li> Set up an RDS MySQL Multi-AZ DB instance. Configure a read replica in a different
                                    Region.</li>
                                <li> Set up an RDS MySQL Single-AZ DB instance. Configure a read replica in a different
                                    Region.</li>
                                <li> Set up an RDS MySQL Single-AZ DB instance. Copy automated snapshots to at least one
                                    other Region.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ216">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer216" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_217" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_217" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_217"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 217</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_217" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_217" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is running an online transaction processing (OLTP) workload on AWS. This workload
                            uses an unencrypted Amazon RDS DB instance in a Multi-AZ deployment. Daily database
                            snapshots are taken from this instance.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to
                            ensure the database and snapshots are always encrypted moving forward?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Encrypt a copy of the latest DB snapshot. Replace existing DB instance by restoring
                                    the encrypted snapshot.</li>
                                <li> Create a new encrypted Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) volume and copy the
                                    snapshots to it. Enable encryption on the DB instance.</li>
                                <li> Copy the snapshots and enable encryption using AWS Key Management Service (AWS
                                    KMS). Restore encrypted snapshot to an existing DB instance.</li>
                                <li> Copy the snapshots to an Amazon S3 bucket that is encrypted using server-side
                                    encryption with AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) managed keys (SSE-KMS).</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ217">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer217" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ217" role="button">

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_218" role="tab">

                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 218</strong>

                <div aria-labelledby="heading_218" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_218" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is planning to transfer multiple terabytes of data to AWS. The data is collected
                            offline from ships. The company want to run complex transformation before transferring the
                            data.<br /> <br />Which AWS service should a solutions architect recommend for this
                            migration?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> AWS Snowball</li>
                                <li> AWS Snowmobile</li>
                                <li> AWS Snowball Edge Storage Optimize</li>
                                <li> AWS Snowball Edge Compute Optimize</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ218">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer218" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_219" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_219" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_219"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 219</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_219" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_219" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has a website deployed on AWS. The database backend is hosted on Amazon RDS for
                            MySQL with a primary instance and five read replicas to support scaling needs. The read
                            replicas should lag no more than 1 second behind the primary instance to support the user
                            experience.<br /><br />As traffic on the website continues to increase, the replicas are
                            falling further behind during periods of peak load, resulting in complaints from users when
                            searches yield inconsistent results. A solutions architect needs to reduce the replication
                            lag as much as possible, with minimal changes to the application code or operational
                            requirements.<br /><br />Which solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Migrate the database to Amazon Aurora MySQL. Replace the MySQL read replicas with
                                    Aurora Replicas and enable Aurora Auto Scaling</li>
                                <li> Deploy an Amazon ElastiCache for Redis cluster in front of the database. Modify the
                                    website to check the cache before querying the database read endpoints.</li>
                                <li> Migrate the database from Amazon RDS to MySQL running on Amazon EC2 compute
                                    instances. Choose very large compute optimized instances for all replica nodes.</li>
                                <li> Migrate the database to Amazon DynamoDB. Initially provision a large number of read
                                    capacity units (RCUs) to support the required throughput with on-demand capacity
                                    scaling enabled.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ219">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer219" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ219" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_219" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_219" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_220" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_220" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_220"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 220</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_220" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_220" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An application is running on an Amazon EC2 instance and must have millisecond latency when
                            running the workload. The application makes many small reads and writes to the file system,
                            but the file system itself is small.<br /><br />Which Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon
                            EBS) volume type should a solutions architect attach to their EC2 instance?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Cold HDD (sc1)</li>
                                <li> General Purpose SSD (gp2)</li>
                                <li> Provisioned IOPS SSD (io1)</li>
                                <li> Throughput Optimized HDD (st1)</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ220">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer220" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>

        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_221" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_221" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_221"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 221</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_221" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_221" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is deploying an application in three AWS Regions using an Application Load
                            Balancer Amazon Route 53 will be used to distribute traffic between these
                            Regions.<br /><br />Which Route 53 configuration should a solutions architect use to provide
                            the MOST high-performing experience?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an A record with a latency policy.</li>
                                <li> Create an A record with a geolocation policy.</li>
                                <li> Create a CNAME record with a failover policy.</li>
                                <li> Create a CNAME record with a geoproximity policy.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ221">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer221" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>

                        </div>

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_221" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_222" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_222" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_222"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 222</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_222" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_222" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is migrating a Linux-based web server group to AWS. The web servers must access
                            files in a shared file store for some content. To meet the migration date, minimal changes
                            can be made.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an Amazon S3 Standard bucket with access to the web server.</li>
                                <li> Configure an Amazon CloudFront distribution with an Amazon S3 bucket as the origin.
                                </li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) volume and mount it on all web
                                    servers.</li>
                                <li> Configure Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) Provisioned IOPS SSD (io1)
                                    volumes and mount them on all web servers.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ222">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer222" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ222" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_222" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_222" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_223" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_223" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_223"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 223</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_223" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_223" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is using a centralized AWS account to store log data in various Amazon S3 buckets.
                            A solutions architect needs to ensure that the data is encrypted at rest before the data is
                            uploaded to the S3 buckets. The data also must be encrypted in transit.<br /><br />Which
                            solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use client-side encryption to encrypt the data that is being uploaded to the S3
                                    buckets.</li>
                                <li> Use server-side encryption to encrypt the data that is being uploaded to the S3
                                    buckets.</li>
                                <li> Create bucket policies that require the use of server-side encryption with S3
                                    managed encryption keys (SSE-S3) for S3 uploads.</li>
                                <li> Enable the security option to encrypt the S3 buckets through the use of a default
                                    AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) key.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ223">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer223" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/UsingEncryption.html
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ223" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_223" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_223" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_224" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_224" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_224"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 224</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_224" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_224" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is using an Amazon S3 bucket to store data uploaded by different departments from
                            multiple locations. During an AWS Well-Architected review, the financial manager notices
                            that 10 TB of S3 Standard storage data has been charged each month. However, in the AWS
                            Management Console for Amazon S3, using the command to select all files and folders shows a
                            total size of 5 TB.<br />What are the possible causes for this difference? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Some files are stored with deduplication.</li>
                                <li> The S3 bucket has versioning enabled.</li>
                                <li> There are incomplete S3 multipart uploads.</li>
                                <li> The S3 bucker has AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) enabled.</li>
                                <li> The S3 bucket has Intelligent-Tiering enabled.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ224">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer224" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A,B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ224" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_224" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_224" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_225" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_225" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_225"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 225</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_225" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_225" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has two AWS accounts: Production and Development. There are code changes ready in
                            the<br />Development account to push to the Production account. In the alpha phase, only two
                            senior developers on the development team need access to the Production account. In the beta
                            phase, more developers might need access to perform testing as well.<br />What should a
                            solutions architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create two policy documents using the AWS Management Console in each account.
                                    Assign the policy to developers who need access.</li>
                                <li> Create an IAM role in the Development account. Give one IAM role access to the
                                    Production account. Allow developers to assume the role.</li>
                                <li> Create an IAM role in the Production account with the trust policy that specifies
                                    the Development account.<br />Allow developers to assume the role.</li>
                                <li> Create an IAM group in the Production account and add it as a principal in the
                                    trust policy that specifies the Production account. Add developers to the group.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ225">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer225" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ225" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_225" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_225" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
        </div>

<div class="product-info-box questions">
    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_226" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_226" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_226"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 226</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_226" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_226" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has thousands of edge devices that collectively generate 1 TB of status alerts
                            each day. Each alert is approximately 2 KB in size. A solutions architect needs to implement
                            a solution to ingest and store the alerts for future analysis.<br />The company wants a
                            highly available solution. However, the company needs to minimize costs and does not want to
                            manage additional infrastructure. Additionally, the company wants to keep 14 days of data
                            available for immediate analysis and archive any data older than 14 days.<br />What is the
                            MOST operationally efficient solution that meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose delivery stream to ingest the alerts.
                                    Configure the Kinesis Data Firehose stream to deliver the alerts to an Amazon S3
                                    bucket. Set up an S3 Lifecycle configuration to transition data to Amazon S3 Glacier
                                    after 14 days.</li>
                                <li> Launch Amazon EC2 instances across two Availability Zones and place them behind an
                                    Elastic Load Balancer to ingest the alerts. Create a script on the EC2 instances
                                    that will store the alerts in an Amazon S3 bucket. Set up an S3 Lifecycle
                                    configuration to transition data to Amazon S3 Glacier after 14 days.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose delivery stream to ingest the alerts.
                                    Configure the Kinesis Data Firehose stream to deliver the alerts to an Amazon
                                    Elasticsearch Service (Amazon ES) cluster. Set up the Amazon ES cluster to take
                                    manual snapshots every day and delete data from the cluster that is older than 14
                                    days.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) standard queue to ingest the
                                    alerts, and set the message retention period to 14 days. Configure consumers to poll
                                    the SQS queue, check the age of the message, and analyze the message data as needed.
                                    If the message is 14 days old, the consumer should copy the message to an Amazon S3
                                    bucket and delete the message from the SQS queue.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ226">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer226" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ226" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_226" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_226" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_227" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_227" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_227"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 227</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_227" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_227" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company manages its own Amazon EC2 instances that run MySQL databases. The company is
                            manually managing replication and scaling as demand increases or decreases. The company
                            needs a new solution that simplifies the process of adding or removing compute capacity to
                            or from its database tier as needed. The solution also must offer improved performance,
                            scaling, and durability with minimal effort from operations.<br />Which solution meets these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Migrate the databases to Amazon Aurora Serverless for Aurora MySQL.</li>
                                <li> Migrate the databases to Amazon Aurora Serverless for Aurora PostgreSQL.</li>
                                <li> Combine the databases into one larger MySQL database. Run the larger database on
                                    larger EC2 instances.</li>
                                <li> Create an EC2 Auto Scaling group for the database tier. Migrate the existing
                                    databases to the new environment.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ227">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer227" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://aws-quickstart.s3.amazonaws.com/quickstart-drupal/doc/drupal-on-the-aws-cloud.pdf
                                    (p.6)
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ227" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_227" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_227" role="button">
