            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_228" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_228" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_228"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 228</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_228" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_228" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is using Amazon Route 53 latency-based routing to route requests to its UDP-based
                            application for users around the world. The application is hosted on redundant servers in
                            the company’s on-premises data centers in the United States, Asia, and Europe. The company’s
                            compliance requirements state that the application must be hosted on premises. The company
                            wants to improve the performance and availability of the application.<br />What should a
                            solutions architect do to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure three Network Load Balancers (NLBs) in the three AWS Regions to address
                                    the on-premises endpoints. Create an accelerator by using AWS Global Accelerator,
                                    and register the NLBs as its endpoints.<br />Provide access to the application by
                                    using a CNAME that points to the accelerator DNS.</li>
                                <li> Configure three Application Load Balancers (ALBs) in the three AWS Regions to
                                    address the on-premises endpoints. Create an accelerator by using AWS Global
                                    Accelerator, and register the ALBs as its endpoints.<br />Provide access to the
                                    application by using a CNAME that points to the accelerator DNS.</li>
                                <li> Configure three Network Load Balancers (NLBs) in the three AWS Regions to address
                                    the on-premises endpoints. In Route 53, create a latency-based record that points to
                                    the three NLBs, and use it as an origin for an Amazon CloudFront distribution.
                                    Provide access to the application by using a CNAME that points to the CloudFront
                                    DNS.</li>
                                <li> Configure three Application Load Balancers (ALBs) in the three AWS Regions to
                                    address the on-premises endpoints. In Route 53, create a latency-based record that
                                    points to the three ALBs, and use it as an origin for an Amazon CloudFront
                                    distribution. Provide access to the application by using a CNAME that points to the
                                    CloudFront DNS.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ228">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer228" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ228" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_228" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_228" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_229" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_229" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_229"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 229</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_229" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_229" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect needs to host a high performance computing (HPC) workload in the AWS
                            Cloud. The workload will run on hundreds of Amazon EC2 instances and will require parallel
                            access to a shared file system to enable distributed processing of large datasets. Datasets
                            will be accessed across multiple instances simultaneously. The workload requires access
                            latency within 1 ms. After processing has completed, engineers will need access to the
                            dataset for manual postprocessing.<br /><br />Which solution will meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) as a shared file system. Access the
                                    dataset from Amazon EFS.</li>
                                <li> Mount an Amazon S3 bucket to serve as the shared file system. Perform
                                    postprocessing directly from the S3 bucket.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon FSx for Lustre as a shared file system. Link the file system to an
                                    Amazon S3 bucket for<br />postprocessing.</li>
                                <li> Configure AWS Resource Access Manager to share an Amazon S3 bucket so that it can
                                    be mounted to all instances for processing and postprocessing.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ229">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer229" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://jayendrapatil.com/aws-fsx-for-lustre/
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ229" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_229" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_229" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_230" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_230" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_230"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 230</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_230" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_230" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an application that uses overnight digital images of products on store shelves
                            to analyze inventory data. The application runs on Amazon EC2 instances behind an
                            Application Load Balancer (ALB) and obtains the images from an Amazon S3 bucket for its
                            metadata to be processed by worker nodes for analysis.<br /><br />A solutions architect
                            needs to ensure that every image is processed by the worker nodes.<br />What should the
                            solutions architect do to meet this requirement in the MOST cost-efficient way?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Send the image metadata from the application directly to a second ALB for the
                                    worker nodes that use an Auto Scaling group of EC2 Spot Instances as the target
                                    group.</li>
                                <li> Process the image metadata by sending it directly to EC2 Reserved Instances in an
                                    Auto Scaling group.<br />With a dynamic scaling policy, use an Amazon CloudWatch
                                    metric for average CPU utilization of the Auto Scaling group as soon as the
                                    front-end application obtains the images.</li>
                                <li> Write messages to Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) when the front-end
                                    application obtains an image. Process the images with EC2 On-Demand instances in an
                                    Auto Scaling group with instance scale-in protection and a fixed number of instances
                                    with periodic health checks.</li>
                                <li> Write messages to Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) when the application
                                    obtains an image.<br />Process the images with EC2 Spot Instances in an Auto Scaling
                                    group with instance scale-in protection and a dynamic scaling policy using a custom
                                    Amazon CloudWatch metric for the current number of messages in the queue.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ230">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer230" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ230" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_230" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_230" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_231" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_231" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_231"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 231</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_231" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_231" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company designs a mobile app for its customers to upload photos to a website. The app
                            needs a secure login with multi-factor authentication (MFA). The company wants to limit the
                            initial build time and the maintenance of the solution.<br />Which solution should a
                            solutions architect recommend to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon Cognito Identity with SMS-based MF</li>
                                <li> Edit IAM policies to require MFA for all users.</li>
                                <li> Federate IAM against the corporate Active Directory that requires MFA.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon API Gateway and require server-side encryption (SSE) for photos.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ231">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer231" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://aws.amazon.com/cognito/
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ231" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_231" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_231" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_232" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_232" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_232"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 232</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_232" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_232" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A user owns a MySQL database that is accessed by various clients who expect, at most, 100 ms
                            latency on requests. Once a record is stored in the database, it is rarely changed. Clients
                            only access one record at a time.<br />Database access has been increasing exponentially due
                            to increased client demand. The resultant load will soon exceed the capacity of the most
                            expensive hardware available for purchase. The user wants to migrate to AWS, and is willing
                            to change database systems.<br />Which service would alleviate the database load issue and
                            offer virtually unlimited scalability for the future?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Amazon RDS</li>
                                <li> Amazon DynamoDB</li>
                                <li> Amazon Redshift</li>
                                <li> AWS Data Pipeline</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ232">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer232" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/big-data/near-zero-downtime-migration-from-mysql-to-dynamodb/
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ232" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_232" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_232" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_233" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_233" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_233"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 233</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_233" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_233" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company recently launched Linux-based application instances on Amazon EC2 in a private
                            subnet and launched a Linux-based bastion host on an Amazon EC2 instance in a public subnet
                            of a VPC. A solutions architect needs to connect from the on-premises network, through the
                            company’s internet connection, to the bastion host, and to the application servers. The
                            solutions architect must make sure that the security groups of all the EC2 instances will
                            allow that access.<br /><br />Which combination of steps should the solutions architect take
                            to meet these requirements? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Replace the current security group of the bastion host with one that only allows
                                    inbound access from the application instances.</li>
                                <li> Replace the current security group of the bastion host with one that only allows
                                    inbound access from the internal IP range for the company.</li>
                                <li> Replace the current security group of the bastion host with one that only allows
                                    inbound access from the external IP range for the company.</li>
                                <li> Replace the current security group of the application instances with one that
                                    allows inbound SSH access from only the private IP address of the bastion host.</li>
                                <li> Replace the current security group of the application instances with one that
                                    allows inbound SSH access from only the public IP address of the bastion host.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ233">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer233" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A,C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ233" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_233" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_233" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_234" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_234" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_234"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 234</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_234" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_234" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A development team is deploying a new product on AWS and is using AWS Lambda as part of the
                            deployment.<br /><br />The team allocates 512 MB of memory for one of the Lambda functions.
                            With this memory allocation, the function is completed in 2 minutes. The function runs
                            millions of times monthly, and the development team is concerned about cost. The team
                            conducts tests to see how different Lambda memory allocations affect the cost of the
                            function.<br />Which steps will reduce the Lambda costs for the product? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Increase the memory allocation for this Lambda function to 1,024 MB if this change
                                    causes the execution time of each function to be less than 1 minute.</li>
                                <li> Increase the memory allocation for this Lambda function to 1,024 MB if this change
                                    causes the execution time of each function to be less than 90 seconds.</li>
                                <li> Reduce the memory allocation for this Lambda function to 256 MB if this change
                                    causes the execution time of each function to be less than 4 minutes.</li>
                                <li> Increase the memory allocation for this Lambda function to 2,048 MB if this change
                                    causes the execution time of each function to be less than 1 minute.</li>
                                <li> Reduce the memory allocation for this Lambda function to 256 MB if this change
                                    causes the execution time of each function to be less than 5 minutes.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ234">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer234" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A,E
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ234" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_234" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_234" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_235" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_235" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_235"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 235</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_235" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_235" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company hosts multiple production applications. One of the applications consists of
                            resources from Amazon EC2, AWS Lambda, Amazon RDS, Amazon Simple Notification Service
                            (Amazon SNS), and Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) across multiple AWS Regions. All
                            company resources are tagged with a tag name of “application” and a value that corresponds
                            to each application. A solutions architect must provide the quickest solution for
                            identifying all of the tagged components.<br />Which solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use AWS CloudTrail to generate a list of resources with the application tag.</li>
                                <li> Use the AWS CLI to query each service across all Regions to report the tagged
                                    components.</li>
                                <li> Run a query in Amazon CloudWatch Logs Insights to report on the components with the
                                    application tag.</li>
                                <li> Run a query with the AWS Resource Groups Tag Editor to report on the resources
                                    globally with the application tag.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ235">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer235" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />

        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_236" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_236" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_236"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 236</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_236" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_236" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an application workflow that uses an AWS Lambda function to download and
                            decrypt files from Amazon S3. These files are encrypted using AWS Key Management Service
                            Customer Master Keys (AWS KMS CMKs). A solutions architect needs to design a solution that
                            will ensure the required permissions are set correctly.<br /><br />Which combination of
                            actions accomplish this? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Attach the kms:decrypt permission to the Lambda function’s resource policy.</li>
                                <li> Grant the decrypt permission for the Lambda IAM role in the KMS key’s policy.</li>
                                <li> Grant the decrypt permission for the Lambda resource policy in the KMS key’s
                                    policy.</li>
                                <li> Create a new IAM policy with the kms:decrypt permission and attach the policy to
                                    the Lambda function.</li>
                                <li> Create a new IAM role with the kms:decrypt permission and attach the execution role
                                    to the Lambda function.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ236">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer236" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B,E
                            </div>
                            </p>

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 237</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_237" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_237" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is building a web-based application running on Amazon EC2 instances in multiple
                            Availability<br />Zones. The web application will provide access to a repository of text
                            documents totaling about 900 TB in size.<br /><br />The company anticipates that the web
                            application will experience periods of high demand. A solutions architect must ensure that
                            the storage component for the text documents can scale to meet the demand of the application
                            at all times. The company is concerned about the overall cost of the solution.<br />Which
                            storage solution meets these requirements MOST cost-effectively?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS)</li>
                                <li> Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS)</li>
                                <li> Amazon Elasticsearch Service (Amazon ES)</li>
                                <li> Amazon S3</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ237">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer237" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_238" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_238" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_238"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 238</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_238" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_238" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An application calls a service run by a vendor. The vendor charges based on the number of
                            calls. The finance department needs to know the number of calls that are made to the service
                            to validate the billing statements.<br />How can a solutions architect design a system to
                            durably store the number of calls without requiring changes to the application?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Call the service through an internet gateway.</li>
                                <li> Decouple the application from the service with an Amazon Simple Queue Service
                                    (Amazon SQS) queue.</li>
                                <li> Publish a custom Amazon CloudWatch metric that counts calls to the service.</li>
                                <li> Call the service through a VPC peering connection.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ238">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer238" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Explanation:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    There are 2 main types of monitoring you can do on AWS EC2 Instances as
                                    follows:<br />Basic Monitoring for Amazon EC2 instances: Seven pre-selected metrics
                                    at five-minute frequency and three status check metrics at one-minute frequency, for
                                    no additional charge.<br />Detailed Monitoring for Amazon EC2 instances: All metrics
                                    available to Basic Monitoring at one-minute<br />frequency, for an additional
                                    charge. Instances with Detailed Monitoring enabled allows data aggregation by Amazon
                                    EC2 AMI ID and instance type.
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://datanextsolutions.com/blog/how-to-collect-custom-metrics-from-aws-ec2-instances/
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>

                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is planning to migrate a legacy application to AWS. The application currently uses
                            NFS to communicate to an on-premises storage solution to store application data. The
                            application cannot be modified to use any other communication protocols other than NFS for
                            this purpose.<br />Which storage solution should a solutions architect recommend for use
                            after the migration?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> AWS DataSync</li>
                                <li> Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS)</li>
                                <li> Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS)</li>
                                <li> Amazon EMR File System (Amazon EMRFS)</li>

                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 240</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_240" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_240" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A team has an application that detects new objects being uploaded into an Amazon S3 bucket.
                            The uploads trigger AWS Lambda function to write object metadata into an Amazon DynamoDB
                            table and an Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL database.<br />Which action should the team take to
                            ensure high availability?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Enable Cross-Region Replication in the S3 bucket.</li>
                                <li> Create a Lambda function for each Availability Zone the application is deployed in.
                                </li>
                                <li> Enable Multi-AZ on the RDS for PostgreSQL database.</li>
                                <li> Create a DynamoDB stream for the DynamoDB table.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ240">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer240" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>

        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_241" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_241" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_241"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 241</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_241" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_241" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect plans to convert a company’s monolithic web application into a
                            multi-tier application. The company wants to avoid managing its own infrastructure. The
                            minimum requirements for the web application are high availability, scalability, and
                            regional low latency during peak hours. The solution should also store and retrieve data
                            with millisecond latency using the application’s API.<br /><br />Which solution meets these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use AWS Fargate to host the web application with backend Amazon RDS Multi-AZ DB
                                    instances.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon API Gateway with an edge-optimized API endpoint, AWS Lambda for compute,
                                    and Amazon DynamoDB as the data store.</li>
                                <li> Use an Amazon Route 53 routing policy with geolocation that points to an Amazon S3
                                    bucket with static website hosting and Amazon DynamoDB as the data store.</li>
                                <li> Use an Amazon CloudFront distribution that points to an Elastic Load Balancer with
                                    an Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling group, along with Amazon RDS Multi-AZ DB instances.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ241">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer241" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_242" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_242" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_242"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 242</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_242" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_242" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is storing sensitive user information in an Amazon S3 bucket. The company wants to
                            provide secure access to this bucket from the application tier running on Amazon EC2
                            instances inside a VPC.<br /><br />Which combination of steps should a solutions architect
                            take to accomplish this? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure a VPC gateway endpoint for Amazon S3 within the VPC.</li>
                                <li> Create a bucket policy to make the objects in the S3 bucket public.</li>
                                <li> Create a bucket policy that limits access to only the application tier running in
                                    the VP</li>
                                <li> Create an IAM user with an S3 access policy and copy the IAM credentials to the EC2
                                    instance.</li>
                                <li> Create a NAT instance and have the EC2 instances use the NAT instance to access the
                                    S3 bucket.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ242">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer242" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A,C
                            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">

                    <a aria-controls="collapse_243" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_243"

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 243</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_243" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_243" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an on-premises business application that generates hundreds of files each day.
                            These files are stored on an SMB file share and require a low-latency connection to the
                            application servers. A new company policy states all application-generated files must be
                            copied to AWS. There is already a VPN connection to AWS.<br /><br />The application
                            development team does not have time to make the necessary code modifications to move the
                            application to AWS.<br /><br />Which service should a solutions architect recommend to allow
                            the application to copy files to AWS?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS)</li>
                                <li> Amazon FSx for Windows File Server</li>
                                <li> AWS Snowball</li>
                                <li> AWS Storage Gateway</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ243">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer243" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_243" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_243" role="button">

                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_244" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_244" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_244"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 244</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_244" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_244" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an Amazon S3 bucket that contains mission-critical data. The company wants to
                            ensure this data is protected from accidental deletion. The data should still be accessible,
                            and a user should be able to delete the data intentionally.<br /> <br />Which combination of
                            steps should a solutions architect take to accomplish this? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Enable versioning on the S3 bucket.</li>
                                <li> Enable MFA Delete on the S3 bucket.</li>
                                <li> Create a bucket policy on the S3 bucket.</li>
                                <li> Enable default encryption on the S3 bucket.</li>
                                <li> Create a lifecycle policy for the objects in the S3 bucket.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ244">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer244" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A,B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://acloud.guru/forums/aws-certified-solutions-architect-associate/discussion/-LNMknp7BP01IYVSlee8/Final%20practice%20exam
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ244" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_244" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_244" role="button">
                        </a>

                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_245" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_245" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_245"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 245</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_245" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_245" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company maintains a searchable repository of items on its website. The data is stored in
                            an Amazon RDS for MySQL database table that contains over 10 million rows. The database has
                            2 TB of General Purpose SSD (gp2) storage. There are millions of updates against this data
                            every day through the company’s website. The company has noticed some operations are taking
                            10 seconds or longer and has determined that the database storage performance is the
                            bottleneck.<br /><br />Which solution addresses the performance issue?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Change the storage type to Provisioned IOPS SSD (io1).</li>
                                <li> Change the instance to a memory-optimized instance class.</li>
                                <li> Change the instance to a burstable performance DB instance class.</li>
                                <li> Enable Multi-AZ RDS read replicas with MySQL native asynchronous replication.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ245">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer245" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ245" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_245" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_245" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

<div class="product-info-box questions">
    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_246" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_246" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_246"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 246</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_246" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_246" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An engineering team is developing and deploying AWS Lambda functions. The team needs to
                            create roles and manage policies in AWS IAM to configure the permissions of the Lambda
                            functions.<br /><br />How should the permissions for the team be configured so they also
                            adhere to the concept of least privilege?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an IAM role with a managed policy attached. Allow the engineering team and
                                    the Lambda functions to assume this role.</li>
                                <li> Create an IAM group for the engineering team with an IAMFullAccess policy attached.
                                    Add all the users from the team to this IAM group.</li>
                                <li> Create an execution role for the Lambda functions. Attach a managed policy that has
                                    permission boundaries specific to these Lambda functions.</li>
                                <li> Create an IAM role with a managed policy attached that has permission boundaries
                                    specific to the Lambda functions. Allow the engineering team to assume this role.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ246">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer246" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_247" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_247" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_247"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 247</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_247" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_247" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has a multi-tier application deployed on several Amazon EC2 instances in an Auto
                            Scaling group. An Amazon RDS for Oracle instance is the application, data layer that uses
                            Oracle-specific PSQL functions. Traffic to the application has been steadily increasing.
                            This is causing the EC2 instances to become overloaded and RDS instance to run out of
                            storage. The Auto Scaling group does not have any scaling metrics and defines the minimum
                            healthy instance count only. The company predicts that traffic will continue to increase at
                            a steady but unpredictable rate before leveling off.<br /><br />What should a solutions
                            architect do to ensure the system can automatically scale for the increased traffic? (Choose
                            two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure storage Auto Scaling on the RDS for Oracle instance.</li>
                                <li> Migrate the database to Amazon Aurora to use Auto Scaling storage.</li>
                                <li> Configure an alarm on the RDS for Oracle instance for low free storage space.</li>
                                <li> Configure the Auto Scaling group to use the average CPU as the scaling metric.</li>
                                <li> Configure the Auto Scaling group to use the average free memory as the scaling
                                    metric.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ247">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer247" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A,C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ247" role="button">

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_247" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_247" role="button">

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_248" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_248" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_248"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 248</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_248" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_248" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A disaster response team is using drones to collect images of recent storm damage. The
                            response team’s laptops lack the storage and compute capacity to transfer the images and
                            process the data. While the team has Amazon EC2 instances for processing and Amazon S3
                            buckets for storage, network connectivity is intermittent and unreliable. The images need to
                            be processed to evaluate the damage.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use AWS Snowball Edge devices to process and store the images.</li>
                                <li> Upload the images to Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) during intermittent
                                    connectivity to EC2 instances.</li>
                                <li> Configure Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose to create multiple delivery streams aimed
                                    separately at the S3 buckets for storage and the EC2 instances for processing the
                                    images.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS Storage Gateway pre-installed on a hardware appliance to cache the images
                                    locally for Amazon S3 to process the images when connectivity becomes available.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ248">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer248" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_248" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_249" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_249" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_249"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 249</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_249" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_249" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect is developing a multiple-subnet VPC architecture. The solution will
                            consist of six subnets in two Availability Zones. The subnets are defined as public, private
                            and dedicated for databases. Only the Amazon EC2 instances running in the private subnets
                            should be able to access a database. Which solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create a now route table that excludes the route to the public subnets’ CIDR
                                    blocks. Associate the route table to the database subnets.</li>
                                <li> Create a security group that denies ingress from the security group used by
                                    instances in the public subnets. Attach the security group to an Amazon RDS DB
                                    instance.</li>
                                <li> Create a security group that allows ingress from the security group used by
                                    instances in the private subnets. Attach the security group to an Amazon RDS DB
                                    instance.</li>
                                <li> Create a new peering connection between the public subnets and the private subnets.
                                    Create a different peering connection between the private subnets and the database
                                    subnets.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ249">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer249" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ249" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_249" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_249" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_250" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_250" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_250"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 250</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_250" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_250" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company that operates a web application on premises is preparing to launch a newer version
                            of the application on AWS. The company needs to route requests to either the AWS-hosted or
                            the on-premises- hosted application based on the URL query string. The on-premises
                            application is not available from the internet, and a VPN connection is established between
                            Amazon VPC and the company’s data center. The company wants to use an Application Load
                            Balancer (ALB) for this launch.<br /><br />Which solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use two ALBs: one for on-premises and one for the AWS resource. Add hosts to each
                                    target group of each ALB. Route with Amazon Route 53 based on the URL query string.
                                </li>
                                <li> Use two ALBs: one for on-premises and one for the AWS resource. Add hosts to the
                                    target group of each AL Create a software router on an EC2 instance based on the URL
                                    query string.</li>
                                <li> Use one ALB with two target groups: one for the AWS resource and one for on
                                    premises. Add hosts to each target group of the ALB. Configure listener rules based
                                    on the URL query string.</li>
                                <li> Use one ALB with two AWS Auto Scaling groups: one for the AWS resource and one for
                                    on premises. Add hosts to each Auto Scaling group. Route with Amazon Route 53 based
                                    on the URL query string.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ250">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer250" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
