<div class="product-info-box questions">
    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_251" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_251" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_251"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 251</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_251" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_251" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company wants to reduce its Amazon S3 storage costs in its production environment without
                            impacting durability or performance of the stored objects.<br />What is the FIRST step the
                            company should take to meet these objectives?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Enable Amazon Macie on the business-critical S3 buckets to classify the sensitivity
                                    of the objects.</li>
                                <li> Enable S3 analytics to identify S3 buckets that are candidates for transitioning to
                                    S3 Standard-Infrequent<br />Access (S3 Standard-IA).</li>
                                <li> Enable versioning on all business-critical S3 buckets.</li>
                                <li> Migrate the objects in all S3 buckets to S3 Intelligent-Tiering.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ251">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer251" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ251" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_251" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_251" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_252" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_252" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_252"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 252</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_252" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_252" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A financial company hosts a web application on AWS. The application uses an Amazon API
                            Gateway Regional API endpoint to give users the ability to retrieve current stock prices.
                            The company's security team has noticed an increase in the number of API requests. The
                            security team is concerned that HTTP flood attacks might take the application
                            offline.<br /><br />A solutions architect must design a solution to protect the application
                            from this type of attack.<br />Which solution meets these requirements with the LEAST
                            operational overhead?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an Amazon CloudFront distribution in front of the API Gateway Regional API
                                    endpoint with a maximum TTL of 24 hours.</li>
                                <li> Create a Regional AWS WAF web ACL with a rate-based rule. Associate the web ACL
                                    with the API Gateway stage.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon CloudWatch metrics to monitor the Count metric and alert the security
                                    team when the predefined rate is reached.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon CloudFront distribution with Lambda@Edge in front of the API
                                    Gateway Regional API endpoint. Create an AWS Lambda function to block requests from
                                    IP addresses that exceed the predefined rate.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ252">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer252" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ252" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_252" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_252" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_253" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_253" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_253"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 253</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_253" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_253" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company provides an API to its users that automates inquiries for tax computations based
                            on item prices. The company experiences a larger number of inquiries during the holiday
                            season only that cause slower response times. A solutions architect needs to design a
                            solution that is scalable and elastic.<br /><br />What should the solutions architect do to
                            accomplish this?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Provide an API hosted on an Amazon EC2 instance. The EC2 instance performs the
                                    required computations when the API request is made.</li>
                                <li> Design a REST API using Amazon API Gateway that accepts the item names. API Gateway
                                    passes item names to AWS Lambda for tax computations.</li>
                                <li> Create an Application Load Balancer that has two Amazon EC2 instances behind it.
                                    The EC2 instances will compute the tax on the received item names.</li>
                                <li> Design a REST API using Amazon API Gateway that connects with an API hosted on an
                                    Amazon EC2 instance. API Gateway accepts and passes the item names to the EC2
                                    instance for tax computations.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ253">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer253" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ253" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_253" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_253" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_254" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_254" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_254"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 254</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_254" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_254" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an automobile sales website that stores its listings in a database on Amazon
                            RDS. When an automobile is sold, the listing needs to be removed from the website and the
                            data must be sent to multiple target systems.<br /><br />Which design should a solutions
                            architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an AWS Lambda function triggered when the database on Amazon RDS is updated
                                    to send the information to an Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) queue for the
                                    targets to consume.</li>
                                <li> Create an AWS Lambda function triggered when the database on Amazon RDS is updated
                                    to send the information to an Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) FIFO queue
                                    for the targets to consume.</li>
                                <li> Subscribe to an RDS event notification and send an Amazon Simple Queue Service
                                    (Amazon SQS) queue fanned out to multiple Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon
                                    SNS) topics. Use AWS Lambda functions to update the targets.</li>
                                <li> Subscribe to an RDS event notification and send an Amazon Simple Notification
                                    Service (Amazon SNS) topic fanned out to multiple Amazon Simple Queue Service
                                    (Amazon SQS) queues. Use AWS Lambda functions to update the targets.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ254">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer254" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ254" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_254" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_254" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_255" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_255" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_255"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 255</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_255" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_255" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is seeing access requests by some suspicious IP addresses. The security team
                            discovers the requests are from different IP addresses under the same CIDR range.<br />What
                            should a solutions architect recommend to the team?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Add a rule in the inbound table of the security to deny the traffic from that CIDR
                                    range.</li>
                                <li> Add a rule in the outbound table of the security group to deny the traffic from
                                    that CIDR range.</li>
                                <li> Add a deny rule in the inbound table of the network ACL with a lower number than
                                    other rules.</li>
                                <li> Add a deny rule in the outbound table of the network ACL with a lower rule number
                                    than other rules.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ255">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer255" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ255" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_255" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_255" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>

            <br />

    </div>

                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_256" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_256" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_256"

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 256</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_256" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_256" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A public-facing web application queries a database hosted on an Amazon EC2 instance in a
                            private subnet. A large number of queries involve multiple table joins, and the application
                            performance has been degrading due to an increase in complex queries. The application team
                            will be performing updates to improve performance.<br /><br />What should a solutions
                            architect recommend to the application team? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Cache query data in Amazon SQS</li>
                                <li> Create a read replica to offload queries</li>
                                <li> Migrate the database to Amazon Athena</li>
                                <li> Implement Amazon DynamoDB Accelerator to cache data.</li>
                                <li> Migrate the database to Amazon RDS</li>
                            </ol>

                <div aria-labelledby="heading_257" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_257" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has 150 TB of archived image data stored on-premises that needs to be moved to the
                            AWS Cloud within the next month. The company's current network connection allows up to 100
                            Mbps uploads for this purpose during the night only.<br /><br />What is the MOST
                            cost-effective mechanism to move this data and meet the migration deadline?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use AWS Snowmobile to ship the data to AWS.</li>
                                <li> Order multiple AWS Snowball devices to ship the data to AWS.</li>
                                <li> Enable Amazon S3 Transfer Acceleration and securely upload the data.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon S3 VPC endpoint and establish a VPN to upload the data.</li>
                            </ol>

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 258</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_258" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_258" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company recently implemented hybrid cloud connectivity using AWS Direct Connect and is
                            migrating data to Amazon S3. The company is looking for a fully managed solution that will
                            automate and accelerate the replication of data between the on-premises storage systems and
                            AWS storage services.<br /><br />Which solution should a solutions architect recommend to
                            keep the data private?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Deploy an AWS DataSync agent for the on-premises environment. Configure a sync job
                                    to replicate the data and connect it with an AWS service endpoint.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an AWS DataSync agent for the on-premises environment. Schedule a batch job
                                    to replicate point- in-time snapshots to AWS.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an AWS Storage Gateway volume gateway for the on-premises environment.
                                    Configure it to store data locally, and asynchronously back up point-in-time
                                    snapshots to AWS.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an AWS Storage Gateway file gateway for the on-premises environment.
                                    Configure it to store data locally, and asynchronously back up point-in-time
                                    snapshots to AWS.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>

                <div aria-labelledby="heading_259" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_259" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company recently deployed a new auditing system to centralize information about operating
                            system versions, patching, and installed software for Amazon EC2 instances. A solutions
                            architect must ensure all instances provisioned through EC2 Auto Scaling groups successfully
                            send reports to the auditing system as soon as they are launched and
                            terminated.<br /><br />Which solution achieves these goals MOST efficiently?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use a scheduled AWS Lambda function and execute a script remotely on all EC2
                                    instances to send data to the audit system.</li>
                                <li> Use EC2 Auto Scaling lifecycle hooks to execute a custom script to send data to the
                                    audit system when instances are launched and terminated.</li>
                                <li> Use an EC2 Auto Scaling launch configuration to execute a custom script through
                                    user data to send data to the audit system when instances are launched and
                                    terminated.</li>
                                <li> Execute a custom script on the instance operating system to send data to the audit
                                    system. Configure the script to be executed by the EC2 Auto Scaling group when the
                                    instance starts and is terminated.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>

                            <p>
                            <div id="answer259" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 260</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_260" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_260" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A healthcare company stores highly sensitive patient records. Compliance requires that
                            multiple copies be stored in different locations. Each record must be stored for 7 years.
                            The company has a service level agreement (SLA) to provide records to government agencies
                            immediately for the first 30 days and then within 4 hours of a request
                            thereafter.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon S3 with cross-Region replication enabled. After 30 days, transition the
                                    data to Amazon S3 Glacier using lifecycle policy.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon S3 with cross-origin resource sharing (CORS) enabled. After 30 days,
                                    transition the data to Amazon S3 Glacier using a lifecycle policy.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon S3 with cross-Region replication enabled. After 30 days, transition the
                                    data to Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Achieve using a lifecycle policy.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon S3 with cross-origin resource sharing (CORS) enabled. After 30 days,
                                    transition the data to Amazon S3 Glacier Deep Archive using a lifecycle policy.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ260">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer260" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_261" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_261" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_261"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 261</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_261" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_261" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has created a VPC with multiple private subnets in multiple Availability Zones
                            (AZs) and one public subnet in one of the AZs. The public subnet is used to launch a NAT
                            gateway. There are instances in the private subnets that use a NAT gateway to connect to the
                            internet. In case of an AZ failure, the company wants to ensure that the instances are not
                            all experiencing internet connectivity issues and that there is a backup plan
                            ready.<br /><br />Which solution should a solutions architect recommend that is MOST highly
                            available?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create a new public subnet with a NAT gateway in the same AZ. Distribute the
                                    traffic between the two NAT gateways.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon EC2 NAT instance in a new public subnet. Distribute the traffic
                                    between the NAT gateway and the NAT instance.</li>
                                <li> Create public subnets in each AZ and launch a NAT gateway in each subnet. Configure
                                    the traffic from the private subnets in each AZ to the respective NAT gateway.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon EC2 NAT instance in the same public subnet. Replace the NAT
                                    gateway with the NAT instance and associate the instance with an Auto Scaling group
                                    with an appropriate scaling policy.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ261">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer261" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>

                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_262" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_262" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is looking for a solution that can store video archives in AWS from old news
                            footage. The company needs to minimize costs and will rarely need to restore these files.
                            When the files are needed, they must be available in a maximum of five
                            minutes.<br /><br />What is the MOST cost-effective solution?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Store the video archives in Amazon S3 Glacier and use Expedited retrievals.</li>
                                <li> Store the video archives in Amazon S3 Glacier and use Standard retrievals.</li>
                                <li> Store the video archives in Amazon S3 Standard-Infrequent Access (S3 Standard-IA).
                                </li>
                                <li> Store the video archives in Amazon S3 One Zone-Infrequent Access (S3 One Zone-IA).
                                </li>
                            </ol>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_263" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_263" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_263"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 263</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_263" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_263" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company built an application that lets users check in to places they visit, rank the
                            places, and add reviews about their experiences. The application is successful with a rapid
                            increase in the number of users every month.<br /> <br />The chief technology officer fears
                            the database supporting the current Infrastructure may not handle the new load the following
                            month because the single Amazon RDS for MySQL instance has triggered alarms related to
                            resource exhaustion due to read requests.<br /><br />What can a solutions architect
                            recommend to prevent service Interruptions at the database layer with minimal changes to
                            code?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create RDS read replicas and redirect read-only traffic to the read replica
                                    endpoints. Enable a Multi-AZ deployment.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon EMR cluster and migrate the data to a Hadoop Distributed File
                                    System (HDFS) with a replication factor of 3.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon ElastiCache cluster and redirect all read-only traffic to the
                                    cluster. Set up the cluster to be deployed in three Availability Zones.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon DynamoDB table to replace the RDS instance and redirect all
                                    read-only traffic to the DynamoDB table. Enable DynamoDB Accelerator to offload
                                    traffic from the main table.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ263">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer263" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 264</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_264" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_264" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An application runs on Amazon EC2 instances in private subnets. The application needs to
                            access an Amazon DynamoDB table. What is the MOST secure way to access the table while
                            ensuring that the traffic does not leave the AWS network?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use a VPC endpoint for DynamoDB.</li>
                                <li> Use a NAT gateway in a public subnet.</li>
                                <li> Use a NAT instance in a private subnet.</li>
                                <li> Use the internet gateway attached to the VPC.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ264">

                            <div id="answer264" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A

                </div>

            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_265" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_265" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_265"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 265</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_265" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_265" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company's operations team has an existing Amazon S3 bucket configured to notify an Amazon
                            SQS queue when new objects are created within the bucket. The development team also wants to
                            receive events when new objects are created. The existing operations team workflow must
                            remain intact.<br /><br />Which solution would satisfy these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create another SQS queue. Update the S3 events in the bucket to also update the new
                                    queue when a new object is created.</li>
                                <li> Create a new SQS queue that only allows Amazon S3 to access the queue. Update
                                    Amazon S3 to update this queue when a new object is created.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon SNS topic and SQS queue for the bucket updates. Update the bucket
                                    to send events to the new topic. Updates both queues to poll Amazon SNS.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon SNS topic and SQS queue for the bucket updates. Update the bucket
                                    to send events to the new topic. Add subscriptions for both queues in the topic.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ265">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer265" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_266" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_266" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_266"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 266</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_266" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_266" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company wants to use Amazon S3 for the secondary copy of its on-premises dataset. The
                            company would rarely need to access this copy. The storage solution's cost should be
                            minimal.<br />Which storage solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> S3 Standard</li>
                                <li> S3 Intelligent-Tiering</li>
                                <li> S3 Standard-Infrequent Access (S3 Standard-IA)</li>
                                <li> S3 One Zone-Infrequent Access (S3 One Zone-IA)</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ266">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer266" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>

                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_266" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_266" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_267" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_267" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_267"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 267</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_267" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_267" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is managing health records on-premises. The company must keep these records
                            indefinitely, disable any modifications to the records once they are stored, and granularly
                            audit access at all levels. The chief technology officer (CTO) is concerned because there
                            are already millions of records not being used by any application, and the current
                            infrastructure is running out of space. The CTO has requested a solutions architect design a
                            solution to move existing data and support future records.<br /><br />Which services can the
                            solutions architect recommend to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use AWS DataSync to move existing data to AWS. Use Amazon S3 to store existing and
                                    new data. Enable Amazon S3 object lock and enable AWS CloudTrail with data events.
                                </li>
                                <li> Use AWS Storage Gateway to move existing data to AWS. Use Amazon S3 to store
                                    existing and new data. Enable Amazon S3 object lock and enable AWS CloudTrail with
                                    management events.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS DataSync to move existing data to AWS. Use Amazon S3 to store existing and
                                    new data. Enable Amazon S3 object lock and enable AWS CloudTrail with management
                                    events.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS Storage Gateway to move existing data to AWS. Use Amazon Elastic Block
                                    Store (Amazon EBS) to store existing and new data. Enable Amazon S3 object lock and
                                    enable Amazon S3 server access logging.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ267">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer267" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ267" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_267" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_267" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_268" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_268" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_268"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 268</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_268" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_268" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an application that calls AWS Lambda functions. A recent code review found
                            database credentials stored in the source code. The database credentials need to be removed
                            from the Lambda source code. The credentials must then be securely stored and rotated on an
                            ongoing basis to meet security policy requirements.<br /><br />What should a solutions
                            architect recommend to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Store the password in AWS CloudHSM. Associate the Lambda function with a role that
                                    can retrieve the password from CloudHSM given its key ID.</li>
                                <li> Store the password in AWS Secrets Manager. Associate the Lambda function with a
                                    role that can retrieve the password from Secrets Manager given its secret ID.</li>
                                <li> Move the database password to an environment variable associated with the Lambda
                                    function. Retrieve the password from the environment variable upon execution.</li>
                                <li> Store the password in AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS). Associate the Lambda
                                    function with a role that can retrieve the password from AWS KMS given its key I
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ268">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer268" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/security/how-to-use-aws-secrets-manager-rotate-credentials-amazon-rds-database-types-oracle/
                                </p>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_269" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_269" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_269"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 269</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_269" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_269" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect is designing a web application that will run on Amazon EC2 instances
                            behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB). The company strictly requires that the
                            application be resilient against malicious internet activity and attacks, and protect
                            against new common vulnerabilities and exposures.<br /><br />What should the solutions
                            architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Leverage Amazon CloudFront with the ALB endpoint as the origin.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an appropriate managed rule for AWS WAF and associate it with the AL</li>
                                <li> Subscribe to AWS Shield Advanced and ensure common vulnerabilities and exposures
                                    are blocked.</li>
                                <li> Configure network ACLs and security groups to allow only ports 80 and 443 to access
                                    the EC2 instances.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ269">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer269" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_270" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_270" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_270"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 270</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_270" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_270" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A bicycle sharing company is developing a multi-tier architecture to track the location of
                            its bicycles during peak operating hours. The company wants to use these data points in its
                            existing analytics platform. A solutions architect must determine the most viable multi-tier
                            option to support this architecture. The data points must be accessible from the REST
                            API.<br /><br />Which action meets these requirements for storing and retrieving location
                            data?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon Athena with Amazon S3.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon API Gateway with AWS Lambda.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon QuickSight with Amazon Redshift.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon API Gateway with Amazon Kinesis Data Analytics.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ270">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer270" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_271" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_271" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_271"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 271</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_271" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_271" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect needs to design a managed storage solution for a company’s application
                            that includes high-performance machine learning. This application runs on AWS Fargate, and
                            the connected storage needs to have concurrent access to files and deliver high
                            performance.<br /><br />Which storage option should the solutions architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an Amazon S3 bucket for the application and establish an IAM role for
                                    Fargate to communicate with Amazon S3.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon FSx for Lustre file share and establish an IAM role that allows
                                    Fargate to communicate with FSx for Lustre.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) file share and establish an IAM
                                    role that allows Fargate to communicate with Amazon EFS.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) volume for the application and
                                    establish an IAM role that allows Fargate to communicate with Amazon EBS.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ271">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer271" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_272" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_272" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_272"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 272</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_272" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_272" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company built a food ordering application that captures user data and stores it for future
                            analysis. The application’s static front end is deployed on an Amazon EC2 instance. The
                            front-end application sends the requests to the backend application running on separate EC2
                            instance. The backend application then stores the data in Amazon RDS.<br /><br />What should
                            a solutions architect do to decouple the architecture and make it scalable?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon S3 to serve the front-end application, which sends requests to Amazon
                                    EC2 to execute the backend application. The backend application will process and
                                    store the data in Amazon RDS.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon S3 to serve the front-end application and write requests to an Amazon
                                    Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS) topic. Subscribe Amazon EC2 instances to
                                    the HTTP/HTTPS endpoint of the topic, and process and store the data in Amazon RDS.
                                </li>
                                <li> Use an EC2 instance to serve the front end and write requests to an Amazon SQS
                                    queue. Place the backend instance in an Auto Scaling group, and scale based on the
                                    queue depth to process and store the data in Amazon RDS.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon S3 to serve the static front-end application and send requests to Amazon
                                    API Gateway, which writes the requests to an Amazon SQS queue. Place the backend
                                    instances in an Auto Scaling group, and scale based on the queue depth to process
                                    and store the data in Amazon RDS.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ272">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer272" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 273</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_273" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_273" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect is designing a system to analyze the performance of financial markets
                            while the markets are closed. The system will run a series of compute-intensive jobs for 4
                            hours every night. The time to complete the compute jobs is expected to remain constant, and
                            jobs cannot be interrupted once started. Once completed, the system is expected to run for a
                            minimum of 1 year.<br /><br />Which type of Amazon EC2 instances should be used to reduce
                            the cost of the system?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Spot Instances</li>
                                <li> On-Demand Instances</li>
                                <li> Standard Reserved Instances</li>
                                <li> Scheduled Reserved Instances</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ273">

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_274" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_274" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_274"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 274</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_274" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_274" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has a three-tier image-sharing application. It uses an Amazon EC2 instance for the
                            front-end layer, another for the backend tier, and a third for the MySQL database. A
                            solutions architect has been tasked with designing a solution that is highly available, and
                            requires the least amount of changes to the application<br /><br />Which solution meets
                            these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon S3 to host the front-end layer and AWS Lambda functions for the backend
                                    layer. Move the database to an Amazon DynamoDB table and use Amazon S3 to store and
                                    serve users’ images.</li>
                                <li> Use load-balanced Multi-AZ AWS Elastic Beanstalk environments for the front-end and
                                    backend layers. Move the database to an Amazon RDS instance with multiple read
                                    replicas to store and serve users’ images.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon S3 to host the front-end layer and a fleet of Amazon EC2 instances in an
                                    Auto Scaling group for the backend layer. Move the database to a memory optimized
                                    instance type to store and serve users’ images.</li>
                                <li> Use load-balanced Multi-AZ AWS Elastic Beanstalk environments for the front-end and
                                    backend layers. Move the database to an Amazon RDS instance with a Multi-AZ
                                    deployment. Use Amazon S3 to store and serve users’ images.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ274">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer274" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>

        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_276" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_276" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_276"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 276</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_276" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_276" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An Amazon EC2 administrator created the following policy associated with an IAM group
                            containing several users:<br /><img id="img14" imageviewer=""
                                src="data:image/png;base64," /><br /><br />What
                            is the effect of this policy?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Users can terminate an EC2 instance in any AWS Region except us-east-1.</li>
                                <li> Users can terminate an EC2 instance with the IP address 10.100.100.1 in the
                                    us-east-1 Region.</li>
                                <li> Users can terminate an EC2 instance in the us-east-1 Region when the user’s source
                                    IP is 10.100.100.254.</li>
                                <li> Users cannot terminate an EC2 instance in the us-east-1 Region when the user’s
                                    source IP is 10.100.100.254.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ276">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer276" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_276" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_277" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_277" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_277"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 277</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_277" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_277" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company hosts an application on multiple Amazon EC2 instances. The application processes
                            messages from an Amazon SQS queue, writes for an Amazon RDS table, and deletes the message
                            from the queue. Occasional duplicate records are found in the RDS table. The SQS queue does
                            not contain any duplicate messages.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to
                            ensure messages are being processed once only?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use the CreateQueue API call to create a new queue.</li>
                                <li> Use the AddPermission API call to add appropriate permissions.</li>
                                <li> Use the ReceiveMessage API call to set an appropriate wait time.</li>
                                <li> Use the ChangeMessageVisibility API call to increase the visibility timeout.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ277">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer277" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ277" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_277" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_277" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_278" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_278" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_278"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 278</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_278" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_278" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company’s application is running on Amazon EC2 instances within an Auto Scaling group
                            behind an Elastic Load Balancer. Based on the application’s history the company anticipates
                            a spike in traffic during a holiday each year. A solutions architect must design a strategy
                            to ensure that the Auto Scaling group proactively increases capacity to minimize any
                            performance impact on application users.<br /><br />Which solution will meet these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an Amazon CloudWatch alarm to scale up the EC2 instances when CPU
                                    utilization exceeds 90%.</li>
                                <li> Create a recurring scheduled action to scale up the Auto Scaling group before the
                                    expected period of peak demand.</li>
                                <li> Increase the minimum and maximum number of EC2 instances in the Auto Scaling group
                                    during the peak demand period.</li>
                                <li> Configure an Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS) notification to send
                                    alerts when there are autoscaling EC2_INSTANCE_LAUNCH events.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ278">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer278" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ278" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_278" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_278" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_279" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_279" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_279"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 279</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_279" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_279" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has on-premises servers running a relational database. The current database serves
                            high read traffic for users in different locations. The company wants to migrate to AWS with
                            the least amount of effort. The database solution should support disaster recovery and not
                            affect the company’s current traffic flow.<br /><br />Which solution meets these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use a database in Amazon RDS with Multi-AZ and at least one read replica.</li>
                                <li> Use a database in Amazon RDS with Multi-AZ and at least one standby replica.</li>
                                <li> Use databases hosted on multiple Amazon EC2 instances in different AWS Regions.
                                </li>
                                <li> Use databases hosted on Amazon EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer in
                                    different Availability Zones.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ279">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer279" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/database/implementing-a-disaster-recovery-strategy-with-amazon-rds/
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_279" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_279" role="button">
                        </a>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_280" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_280" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_280"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 280</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_280" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_280" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A marketing company is storing CSV files in an Amazon S3 bucket for statistical analysis. An
                            application on an Amazon EC2 instance needs permission to efficiently process the CSV data
                            stored in the S3 bucket. <br />Which action will MOST securely grant the EC2 instance access
                            to the S3 bucket?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Attach a resource-based policy to the S3 bucket.</li>
                                <li> Create an IAM user for the application with specific permissions to the S3 bucket.
                                </li>
                                <li> Associate an IAM role with least privilege permissions to the EC2 instance profile.
                                </li>
                                <li> Store AWS credentials directly on the EC2 instance for applications on the instance
                                    to use for API calls.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ280">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer280" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ280" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_280" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
