<div class="product-info-box questions">
    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_281" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_281" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_281"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 281</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_281" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_281" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect is designing the cloud architecture for a new application being
                            deployed on AWS. The process should run in parallel while adding and removing application
                            nodes as needed based on the number of jobs to be processed. The processor application is
                            stateless. The solutions architect must ensure that the application is loosely coupled and
                            the job items are durably stored.<br /><br />Which design should the solutions architect
                            use?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an Amazon SNS topic to send the jobs that need to be processed. Create an
                                    Amazon Machine Image (AMI) that consists of the processor application. Create a
                                    launch configuration that uses the AMI. Create an Auto Scaling group using the
                                    launch configuration. Set the scaling policy for the Auto Scaling group to add and
                                    remove nodes based on CPU usage.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon SQS queue to hold the jobs that need to be processed. Create an
                                    Amazon Machine Image (AMI) that consists of the processor application. Create a
                                    launch configuration that uses the AMI. Create an Auto Scaling group using the
                                    launch configuration. Set the scaling policy for the Auto Scaling group to add and
                                    remove nodes based on network usage.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon SQS queue to hold the jobs that need to be processed. Create an
                                    Amazon Machine Image (AMI) that consists of the processor application. Create a
                                    launch template that uses the AMI. Create an Auto Scaling group using the launch
                                    template. Set the scaling policy for the Auto Scaling group to add and remove nodes
                                    based on the number of items in the SQS queue.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon SNS topic to send the jobs that need to be processed. Create an
                                    Amazon Machine Image (AMI) that consists of the processor application. Create a
                                    launch template that uses the AMI. Create an Auto Scaling group using the launch
                                    template. Set the scaling policy for the Auto Scaling group to add and remove nodes
                                    based on the number of messages published to the SNS topic.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ281">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer281" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Explanation:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    Amazon Simple Queue Service<br /><br />Amazon Simple Queue Service (SQS) is a fully
                                    managed message queuing service that enables you to decouple and scale
                                    microservices, distributed systems, and serverless applications. SQS eliminates the
                                    complexity and overhead associated with managing and operating message oriented
                                    middleware, and empowers developers to focus on differentiating work. Using SQS, you
                                    can send, store, and receive messages between software components at any volume,
                                    without losing messages or requiring other services to be available. Get started
                                    with SQS in minutes using the AWS console, Command Line Interface or SDK of your
                                    choice, and three simple commands.<br /><br />SQS offers two types of message
                                    queues. Standard queues offer maximum throughput, best-effort ordering, and
                                    at-least-once delivery. SQS FIFO queues are designed to guarantee that messages are
                                    processed exactly once, in the exact order that they are sent.<br /><br />Scaling
                                    Based on Amazon SQS<br /><br />There are some scenarios where you might think about
                                    scaling in response to activity in an Amazon SQS queue. For example, suppose that
                                    you have a web app that lets users upload images and use them online. In this
                                    scenario, each image requires resizing and encoding before it can be published. The
                                    app runs on EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling group, and it's configured to handle
                                    your typical upload rates. Unhealthy instances are terminated and replaced to
                                    maintain current instance levels at all times. The app places the raw bitmap data of
                                    the images in an SQS queue for processing. It processes the images and then
                                    publishes the processed images where they can be viewed by users. The architecture
                                    for this scenario works well if the number of image uploads doesn't vary over time.
                                    But if the number of uploads changes over time, you might consider using dynamic
                                    scaling to scale the capacity of your Auto Scaling group.
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://aws.amazon.com/sqs/#:~:text=Amazon%20SQS%20leverages%20the%20AWS,queues%20provide%20nearly%20unlimited%20throughput<br />https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/as-using-sqs-queue.html
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ281" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_281" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_281" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_282" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_282" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_282"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 282</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_282" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_282" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company recently expanded globally and wants to make its application accessible to users
                            in those geographic locations. The application is deployed on Amazon EC2 instances behind an
                            Application Load Balancer in an Auto Scaling group. The company needs the ability shift
                            traffic from resources in one region to another.<br /><br />What should a solutions
                            architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure an Amazon Route 53 latency routing policy.</li>
                                <li> Configure an Amazon Route 53 geolocation routing policy.</li>
                                <li> Configure an Amazon Route 53 geoproximity routing policy.</li>
                                <li> Configure an Amazon Route 53 multivalue answer routing policy.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ282">

                            <div id="answer282" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_283" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_283" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_283"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 283</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_283" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_283" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company wants to replicate its data to AWS to recover in the event of a disaster. Today, a
                            system administrator has scripts that copy data to a NFS share Individual backup files need
                            to be accessed with low latency by application administrators to deal with errors in
                            processing.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect recommend to meet these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Modify the script to copy data to an Amazon S3 bucket instead of the on-premises
                                    NFS share.</li>
                                <li> Modify the script to copy data to an Amazon S3 Glacier Archive instead of the
                                    on-premises NFS share.</li>
                                <li> Modify the script to copy data to an Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) volume
                                    instead of the on- premises NFS share.</li>
                                <li> Modify the script to copy data to an AWS Storage Gateway for File Gateway virtual
                                    appliance instead of the on-premises NFS share.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ283">

                            <div id="answer283" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 284</strong>

                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_284" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_284" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An application requires a development environment (DEV) and production environment (PROD)
                            for several years. The DEV instances will run for 10 hours each day during normal business
                            hours, while the PROD instances will run 24 hours each day. A solutions architect needs to
                            determine a compute instance purchase strategy to minimize costs.<br /><br />Which solution
                            is the MOST cost-effective?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> DEV with Spot Instances and PROD with On-Demand Instances</li>
                                <li> DEV with On-Demand Instances and PROD with Spot Instances</li>
                                <li> DEV with Scheduled Reserved Instances and PROD with Reserved Instances</li>
                                <li> DEV with On-Demand Instances and PROD with Scheduled Reserved Instances</li>
                            </ol>

                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 285</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_285" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_285" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company runs multiple Amazon EC2 Linux instances in a VPC with applications that use a
                            hierarchical directory structure. The applications need to rapidly and concurrently read and
                            write to shared storage.<br />How can this be achieved?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an Amazon EFS file system and mount it from each EC2 instance.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon S3 bucket and permit access from all the EC2 instances in the VPC.
                                </li>
                                <li> Create a file system on an Amazon EBS Provisioned IOPS SSD (io1) volume. Attach the
                                    volume to all the EC2 instances.</li>
                                <li> Create file systems on Amazon EBS volumes attached to each EC2 instance.
                                    Synchronize the Amazon EBS volumes across the different EC2 instances.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ285">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer285" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>

                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 286</strong>

                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_286" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_286" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has several business systems that require access to data stored in a file share.
                            The business systems will access the file share using the Server Message Block (SMB)
                            protocol. The file share solution should be accessible from both of the company's legacy
                            on-premises environments and with AWS.<br /><br />Which services meet the business
                            requirements? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Amazon EBS</li>
                                <li> Amazon EFS</li>
                                <li> Amazon FSx for Windows</li>
                                <li> Amazon S3</li>
                                <li> AWS Storage Gateway file gateway</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ286">

                            <div id="answer286" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C,E

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_287" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_287" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_287"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 287</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_287" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_287" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has enabled AWS CloudTrail logs to deliver log files to an Amazon S3 bucket for
                            each of its developer accounts. The company has created a central AWS account for
                            streamlining management and audit reviews. An internal auditor needs to access the
                            CloudTrail logs, yet access needs to be restricted for all developer account users. The
                            solution must be secure and optimized.<br /><br />How should a solutions architect meet
                            these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure an AWS Lambda function in each developer account to copy the log files to
                                    the central account. Create an IAM role in the central account for the auditor.
                                    Attach an IAM policy providing read-only permissions to the bucket.</li>
                                <li> Configure CloudTrail from each developer account to deliver the log files to an S3
                                    bucket in the central account. Create an IAM user in the central account for the
                                    auditor. Attach an IAM policy providing full permissions to the bucket.</li>
                                <li> Configure CloudTrail from each developer account to deliver the log files to an S3
                                    bucket in the central account. Create an IAM role in the central account for the
                                    auditor. Attach an IAM policy providing read-only permissions to the bucket.</li>
                                <li> Configure an AWS Lambda function in the central account to copy the log files from
                                    the S3 bucket in each developer account. Create an IAM user in the central account
                                    for the auditor. Attach an IAM policy providing full permissions to the bucket.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ287">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer287" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ287" role="button">

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_287" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_287" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_288" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_288" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_288"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 288</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_288" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_288" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company running an on-premises application is migrating the application to AWS to increase
                            its elasticity and availability. The current architecture uses a Microsoft SQL Server
                            database with heavy read activity. The company wants to explore alternate database options
                            and migrate database engines, if needed. Every 4 hours, the development team does a full
                            copy of the production database to populate a test database. During this period, users
                            experience latency.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect recommend as replacement
                            database?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon Aurora with Multi-AZ Aurora Replicas and restore from mysqldump for the
                                    test database.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Aurora with Multi-AZ Aurora Replicas and restore snapshots from Amazon
                                    RDS for the test database.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon RDS for MySQL with a Multi-AZ deployment and read replicas, and use the
                                    standby instance for the test database.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon RDS for SQL Server with a Multi-AZ deployment and read replicas, and
                                    restore snapshots from RDS for the test database.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ288">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer288" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>

                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_289" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_289" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_289"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 289</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_289" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_289" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is running a highly sensitive application on Amazon EC2 backed by an Amazon RDS
                            database. Compliance regulations mandate that all personally identifiable information (PII)
                            be encrypted at rest.<br /><br />Which solution should a solutions architect recommend to
                            meet this requirement with the LEAST amount of changes to the infrastructure?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Deploy AWS Certificate Manager to generate certificates. Use the certificates to
                                    encrypt the database volume.</li>
                                <li> Deploy AWS CloudHSM, generate encryption keys, and use the customer master key
                                    (CMK) to encrypt database volumes.</li>
                                <li> Configure SSL encryption using AWS Key Management Service customer master keys (AWS
                                    KMS CMKs) to encrypt database volumes.</li>
                                <li> Configure Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) encryption and Amazon RDS
                                    encryption with AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) keys to encrypt instance and
                                    database volumes.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ289">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer289" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ289" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_289" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_289" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_290" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_290" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_290"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 290</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_290" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_290" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An ecommerce company has noticed performance degradation of its Amazon RDS based web
                            application. The performance degradation is attributed to an increase in the number of
                            read-only SQL queries triggered by business analysts. A solutions architect needs to solve
                            the problem with minimal changes to the existing web application.<br /><br />What should the
                            solutions architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Export the data to Amazon DynamoDB and have the business analysts run their
                                    queries.</li>
                                <li> Load the data into Amazon ElastiCache and have the business analysts run their
                                    queries.</li>
                                <li> Create a read replica of the primary database and have the business analysts run
                                    their queries.</li>
                                <li> Copy the data into an Amazon Redshift cluster and have the business analysts run
                                    their queries.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ290">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer290" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ290" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_290" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"

                <div aria-labelledby="heading_291" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_291" role="tabpanel">

                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has two applications it wants to migrate to AWS. Both applications process a large
                            set of files by accessing the same files at the same time. Both applications need to read
                            the files with low latency.<br />Which architecture should a solutions architect recommend
                            for this situation?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure two AWS Lambda functions to run the applications. Create an Amazon EC2
                                    instance with an instance store volume to store the data.</li>
                                <li> Configure two AWS Lambda functions to run the applications. Create an Amazon EC2
                                    instance with an Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) volume to store the data.
                                </li>
                                <li> Configure one memory optimized Amazon EC2 instance to run both applications
                                    simultaneously. Create an Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) volume with
                                    Provisioned IOPS to store the data.</li>
                                <li> Configure two Amazon EC2 instances to run both applications. Configure Amazon
                                    Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) with General Purpose performance mode and Bursting
                                    Throughput mode to store the data.</li>

                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_296" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_296" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An application running on an Amazon EC2 instance in VPC-A needs to access files in another
                            EC2 instance in VPC-B. Both are in separate. AWS accounts. The network administrator needs
                            to design a solution to enable secure access to EC2 instance in VPC-B from VPC-A. The
                            connectivity should not have a single point of failure or bandwidth
                            concerns.<br /><br />Which solution will meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Set up a VPC peering connection between VPC-A and VPC-B.</li>
                                <li> Set up VPC gateway endpoints for the EC2 instance running in VPC-</li>
                                <li> Attach a virtual private gateway to VPC-B and enable routing from VPC-A.</li>
                                <li> Create a private virtual interface (VIF) for the EC2 instance running in VPC-B and
                                    add appropriate routes from VPC-B.</li>
                            </ol>

                                <li> Configure another EC2 instance in a different Availability Zone as part of the
                                    origin group.</li>
                                <li> Configure another EC2 instance as part of the origin server cluster in the same
                                    Availability Zone.</li>

                <div aria-labelledby="heading_298" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_298" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is investigating potential solutions that would collect, process, and store users'
                            service usage data. The business objective is to create an analytics capability that will
                            enable the company to gather operational insights quickly using standard SQL queries. The
                            solution should be highly available and ensure Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, and

                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon DynamoDB transactions.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Neptune database in a Multi-AZ design</li>
                                <li> Use a fully managed Amazon RDS for MySQL database in a Multi-AZ design.</li>
                                <li> Deploy PostgreSQL on an Amazon EC2 instance that uses Amazon EBS Throughput
                                    Optimized HDD (st1) storage.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ298">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer298" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ298" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_298" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_298" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>

            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_299" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_299" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_299"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 299</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_299" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_299" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company hosts its product information webpages on AWS. The existing solution uses multiple
                            Amazon C2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer in an Auto Scaling group. The
                            website also uses a custom DNS name and communicates with HTTPS only using a dedicated SSL
                            certificate. The company is planning a new product launch and wants to be sure that users
                            from around the world have the best possible experience on the new website.<br /><br />What
                            should a solutions architect do to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Redesign the application to use Amazon CloudFront.</li>
                                <li> Redesign the application to use AWS Elastic Beanstalk.</li>
                                <li> Redesign the application to use a Network Load Balancer.</li>
                                <li> Redesign the application to use Amazon S3 static website hosting.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ299">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer299" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Explanation:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    What Is Amazon CloudFront?<br /><br />Amazon CloudFront is a web service that speeds
                                    up distribution of your static and dynamic web content, such as .html, .css, .js,
                                    and image files, to your users. CloudFront delivers your content through a worldwide
                                    network of data centers called edge locations. When a user requests content that
                                    you're serving with CloudFront, the user is routed to the edge location that
                                    provides the lowest latency (time delay), so that content is delivered with the best
                                    possible performance.<br /><br />If the content is already in the edge location with
                                    the lowest latency, CloudFront delivers it immediately.<br /><br />If the content is
                                    not in that edge location, CloudFront retrieves it from an origin that you've
                                    defined – such as an Amazon S3 bucket, a MediaPackage channel, or an HTTP server
                                    (for example, a web server) that you have identified as the source for the
                                    definitive version of your content.<br /><br />As an example, suppose that you're
                                    serving an image from a traditional web server, not from CloudFront. For example,
                                    you might serve an image, sunsetphoto.png, using the URL
                                    http://example.com/sunsetphoto.png.<br /><br />Your users can easily navigate to
                                    this URL and see the image. But they probably don't know that their request was
                                    routed from one network to another – through the complex collection of
                                    interconnected networks that comprise the internet – until the image was
                                    found.<br /><br />CloudFront speeds up the distribution of your content by routing
                                    each user request through the AWS backbone network to the edge location that can
                                    best serve your content. Typically, this is a CloudFront edge server that provides
                                    the fastest delivery to the viewer. Using the AWS network dramatically reduces the
                                    number of networks that your users' requests must pass through, which improves
                                    performance. Users get lower latency – the time it takes to load the first byte of
                                    the file – and higher data transfer rates.<br /><br />You also get increased
                                    reliability and availability because copies of your files (also known as objects)
                                    are now held (or cached) in multiple edge locations around the world.
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudFront/latest/DeveloperGuide/Introduction.html
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ299" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_299" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_299" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_300" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_300" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_300"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 300</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_300" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_300" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect is moving the static content from a public website hosted on Amazon
                            EC2 instances to an Amazon S3 bucket. An Amazon CloudFront distribution will be used to
                            deliver the static assets. The security group used by the EC2 instances restricts access to
                            a limited set of IP ranges. Access to the static content should be similarly
                            restricted.<br /><br />Which combination of steps will meet these requirements? (Choose
                            two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an origin access identity (OAI) and associate it with the distribution.
                                    Change the permissions in the bucket policy so that only the OAI can read the
                                    objects.</li>
                                <li> Create an AWS WAF web ACL that includes the same IP restrictions that exist in the
                                    EC2 security group. Associate this new web ACL with the CloudFront distribution.
                                </li>
                                <li> Create a new security group that includes the same IP restrictions that exist in
                                    the current EC2 security group. Associate this new security group with the
                                    CloudFront distribution.</li>
                                <li> Create a new security group that includes the same IP restrictions that exist in
                                    the current EC2 security group. Associate this new security group with the S3 bucket
                                    hosting the static content.</li>
                                <li> Create a new IAM role and associate the role with the distribution. Change the
                                    permissions either on the S3 bucket or on the files within the S3 bucket so that
                                    only the newly created IAM role has read and download permissions.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ300">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer300" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A,B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ300" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_300" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_300" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="product-info-box questions">
    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_301" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_301" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_301"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 301</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_301" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_301" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company wants to run a hybrid workload for data processing. The data needs to be accessed
                            by on-premises applications for local data processing using an NFS protocol, and must also
                            be accessible from the AWS Cloud for further analytics and batch
                            processing.<br /><br />Which solution will meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use an AWS Storage Gateway file gateway to provide file storage to AWS, then
                                    perform analytics on this data in the AWS Cloud.</li>
                                <li> Use an AWS storage Gateway tape gateway to copy the backup of the local data to
                                    AWS, then perform analytics on this data in the AWS cloud.</li>
                                <li> Use an AWS Storage Gateway volume gateway in a stored volume configuration to
                                    regularly take snapshots of the local data, then copy the data to AWS.</li>
                                <li> Use an AWS Storage Gateway volume gateway in a cached volume configuration to back
                                    up all the local storage in the AWS cloud, then perform analytics on this data in
                                    the cloud.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ301">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer301" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_302" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_302" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_302"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 302</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_302" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_302" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company delivers files in Amazon S3 to certain users who do not have AWS credentials.
                            These users must be given access for a limited time. What should a solutions architect do to
                            securely meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Enable public access on an Amazon S3 bucket.</li>
                                <li> Generate a presigned URL to share with the users.</li>
                                <li> Encrypt files using AWS KMS and provide keys to the users.</li>
                                <li> Create and assign IAM roles that will grant GetObject permissions to the users.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ302">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer302" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_303" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_303" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_303"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 303</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_303" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_303" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is processing data on a daily basis. The results of the operations are stored in
                            an Amazon S3 bucket, analyzed daily for one week, and then must remain immediately
                            accessible for occasional analysis. What is the MOST cost-effective storage solution
                            alternative to the current configuration?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure a lifecycle policy to delete the objects after 30 days.</li>
                                <li> Configure a lifecycle policy to transition the objects to Amazon S3 Glacier after
                                    30 days.</li>
                                <li> Configure a lifecycle policy to transition the objects to Amazon S3
                                    Standard-Infrequent Access (S3 Standard-IA) after 30 days.</li>
                                <li> Configure a lifecycle policy to transition the objects to Amazon S3 One
                                    Zone-Infrequent Access (S3 One Zone-IA) after 30 days.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ303">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer303" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_304" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_304" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_304"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 304</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_304" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_304" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an on-premises data center that is running out of storage capacity. The
                            company wants to migrate its storage infrastructure to AWS while minimizing bandwidth costs.
                            The solution must allow for immediate retrieval of data at no additional
                            cost.<br /><br />How can these requirements be met?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Deploy Amazon S3 Glacier Vault and enable expedited retrieval. Enable provisioned
                                    retrieval capacity for the workload.</li>
                                <li> Deploy AWS Storage Gateway using cached volumes. Use Storage Gateway to store data
                                    in Amazon S3 while retaining copies of frequently accessed data subsets locally.
                                </li>
                                <li> Deploy AWS Storage Gateway using stored volumes to store data locally. Use Storage
                                    Gateway to asynchronously back up point-in-time snapshots of the data to Amazon S3.
                                </li>
                                <li> Deploy AWS Direct Connect to connect with the on-premises data center. Configure
                                    AWS Storage Gateway to store data locally. Use Storage Gateway to asynchronously
                                    back up point-in-time snapshots of the data to Amazon S3.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ304">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer304" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ304" role="button">

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_304" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_304" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_305" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_305" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_305"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 305</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_305" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_305" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An ecommerce company is running a multi-tier application on AWS. The front-end and backend
                            tiers both run on Amazon EC2, and the database runs on Amazon RDS for MySQL. The backend
                            tier communicates with the RDS instance. There are frequent calls to return identical
                            datasets from the database that are causing performance slowdowns.<br /><br />Which action
                            should be taken to improve the performance of the backend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Implement Amazon SNS to store the database calls.</li>
                                <li> Implement Amazon ElastiCache to cache the large datasets.</li>
                                <li> Implement an RDS for MySQL read replica to cache database calls.</li>
                                <li> Implement Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose to stream the calls to the database.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ305">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer305" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B

                            A company must migrate 20 TB of data from a data center to the AWS Cloud within 30 days. The

                            should a solutions architect do to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>

                                <li> Use AWS DataSync.</li>
                                <li> Use a secure VPN connection.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon S3 Transfer Acceleration.</li>

                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 308</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_308" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_308" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an Amazon EC2 instance running on a private subnet that needs to access a
                            public website to download patches and updates. The company does not want external websites
                            to see the EC2 instance IP address or initiate connections to it.<br /><br />How can a
                            solutions architect achieve this objective?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create a site-to-site VPN connection between the private subnet and the network in
                                    which the public site is deployed.</li>
                                <li> Create a NAT gateway in a public subnet. Route outbound traffic from the private
                                    subnet through the NAT gateway.</li>
                                <li> Create a network ACL for the private subnet where the EC2 instance deployed only
                                    allows access from the IP address range of the public website.</li>
                                <li> Create a security group that only allows connections from the IP address range of
                                    the public website. Attach the security group to the EC2 instance.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ308">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer308" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>

                <div aria-labelledby="heading_310" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_310" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company's web application is running on Amazon EC2 instances behind an Application Load
                            Balancer. The company recently changed its policy, which now requires the application to be
                            accessed from one specific country only.<br /><br />Which configuration will meet this
                            requirement?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure the security group for the EC2 instances.</li>
                                <li> Configure the security group on the Application Load Balancer.</li>
                                <li> Configure AWS WAF on the Application Load Balancer in a VP</li>
                                <li> Configure the network ACL for the subnet that contains the EC2 instances.</li>
                            </ol>

    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_311" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_311" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_311"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 311</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_311" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_311" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect is designing a mission-critical web application. It will consist of
                            Amazon EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer and a relational database. The
                            database should be highly available and fault tolerant.<br /><br />Which database
                            implementations will meet these requirements? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Amazon Redshift</li>
                                <li> Amazon DynamoDB</li>
                                <li> Amazon RDS for MySQL</li>
                                <li> MySQL-compatible Amazon Aurora Multi-AZ</li>
                                <li> Amazon RDS for SQL Server Standard Edition Multi-AZ</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ311">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer311" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D,E
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ311" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_311" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_311" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_312" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_312" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_312"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 312</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_312" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_312" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A Solutions Architect must design a web application that will be hosted on AWS, allowing
                            users to purchase access to premium, shared content that is stored in an S3 bucket. Upon
                            payment, content will be available for download for 14 days before the user is denied
                            access.<br /><br />Which of the following would be the LEAST complicated implementation?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use an Amazon CloudFront distribution with an origin access identity (OAI).
                                    Configure the distribution with an Amazon S3 origin to provide access to the file
                                    through signed URLs. Design a Lambda function to remove data that is older than 14
                                    days.</li>
                                <li> Use an S3 bucket and provide direct access to the file. Design the application to
                                    track purchases in a DynamoDB table. Configure a Lambda function to remove data that
                                    is older than 14 days based on a query to Amazon DynamoD</li>
                                <li> Use an Amazon CloudFront distribution with an OAI. Configure the distribution with
                                    an Amazon S3 origin to provide access to the file through signed URLs. Design the
                                    application to set an expiration of 14 days for the URL.</li>
                                <li> Use an Amazon CloudFront distribution with an OAI. Configure the distribution with
                                    an Amazon S3 origin to provide access to the file through signed URLs. Design the
                                    application to set an expiration of 60 minutes for the URL and recreate the URL as
                                    necessary.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ312">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer312" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ312" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_312" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_312" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_313" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_313" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_313"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 313</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_313" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_313" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect observes that a nightly batch processing job is automatically scaled
                            up for 1 hour before the desired Amazon EC2 capacity is reached. The peak capacity is the
                            same every night and the batch jobs always start at 1 AM. The solutions architect needs to
                            find a cost-effective solution that will allow for the desired EC2 capacity to be reached
                            quickly and allow the Auto Scaling group to scale down after the batch jobs are
                            complete.<br /> <br />What should the solutions architect do to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Increase the minimum capacity for the Auto Scaling group.</li>
                                <li> Increase the maximum capacity for the Auto Scaling group.</li>
                                <li> Configure scheduled scaling to scale up to the desired compute level.</li>
                                <li> Change the scaling policy to add more EC2 instances during each scaling operation.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ313">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer313" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ313" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_313" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_313" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">

                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company plans to store sensitive user data on Amazon S3. Internal security compliance
                            requirement mandate encryption of data before sending it to Amazon S3.<br /><br />What
                            should a solutions architect recommend to satisfy these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Server-side encryption with customer-provided encryption keys</li>
                                <li> Client-side encryption with Amazon S3 managed encryption keys</li>
                                <li> Server-side encryption with keys stored in AWS key Management Service (AWS KMS)
                                </li>
                                <li> Client-side encryption with a master key stored in AWS Key Management Service (AWS
                                    KMS)</li>
                            </ol>

                            A media streaming company collects real-time data and stores it in a disk-optimized database
                            system. The company is not getting the expected throughput and wants an in-memory database
                            storage solution that performs faster and provides high availability using data
                            replication.<br /><br />Which database should a solutions architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Amazon RDS for MySQL</li>
                                <li> Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL.</li>
                                <li> Amazon ElastiCache for Redis</li>
                                <li> Amazon ElastiCache for Memcached</li>
                            </ol>

                            <div id="answer316" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Explanation:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    In-memory databases on AWS Amazon Elasticache for Redis.<br /><br />Amazon
                                    ElastiCache for Redis is a blazing fast in-memory data store that provides
                                    submillisecond latency to power internet-scale, real-time applications. Developers
                                    can use ElastiCache for Redis as an in-memory nonrelational database. The
                                    ElastiCache for Redis cluster configuration supports up to 15 shards and enables
                                    customers to run Redis workloads with up to 6.1 TB of in-memory capacity in a single
                                    cluster. ElastiCache for Redis also provides the ability to add and remove shards
                                    from a running cluster. You can dynamically scaleout and even scale in your Redis
                                    cluster workloads to adapt to changes in demand.
