            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_24" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_24" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_24"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 24</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_24" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_24" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is running a multi-tier ecommerce web application in the AWS Cloud. The
                            application runs on Amazon EC2 Instances with an Amazon RDS MySQL Multi-AZ DB instance.
                            Amazon RDS is configured with the latest generation instance with 2,000 GB of storage in an
                            Amazon EBS General Purpose SSD (gp2) volume. The database performance impacts the
                            application during periods of high demand.<br /><br />After analyzing the logs in Amazon
                            CloudWatch Logs, a database administrator finds that the application performance always
                            degrades when the number of read and write IOPS is higher than 6.000.<br /><br />What should
                            a solutions architect do to improve the application performance?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Replace the volume with a Magnetic volume.</li>
                                <li> Increase the number of IOPS on the gp2 volume.</li>
                                <li> Replace the volume with a Provisioned IOPS (PIOPS) volume.</li>
                                <li> Replace the 2,000 GB gp2 volume with two 1,000 GBgp2 volumes.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ24">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer24" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ24" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_24" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_24" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_25" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_25" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_25"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 25</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_25" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_25" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company wants to build an online marketplace application on AWS as a set of loosely
                            coupled microservices. For this application, when a customer submits a new order, two
                            microservices should handle the event simultaneously. The Email microservice will send a
                            confirmation email, and the OrderProcessing microservice will start the order delivery
                            process. If a customer cancels an order, the OrderCancelation and Email microservices should
                            handle the event simultaneously.<br /><br />A solutions architect wants to use Amazon Simple
                            Queue Service (Amazon SQS) and Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS) to design the
                            messaging between the microservices.<br /><br />How should the solutions architect design
                            the solution?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create a single SQS queue and publish order events to it. The Email OrderProcessing
                                    and Order Cancellation microservices can then consume messages of the queue.</li>
                                <li> Create three SNS topics for each microservice. Publish order events to the three
                                    topics. Subscribe each of the Email OrderProcessing and Order Cancellation
                                    microservices to its own topic.</li>
                                <li> Create an SNS topic and publish order events to it. Create three SQS queues for the
                                    Email OrderProcessing and Order Cancellation microservices. Subscribe all SQS queues
                                    to the SNS topic with message filtering.</li>
                                <li> Create two SQS queues and publish order events to both queues simultaneously. One
                                    queue is for the Email and OrderProcessing microservices. The second queue is for
                                    the Email and Order Cancellation microservices.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ25">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer25" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ25" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_25" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_25" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />

    </div>

                        <h4 class="panel-title">

                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_26" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_26" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company hosts more than 300 global websites and applications. The company requires a
                            platform to analyze more than 30 TB of clickstream data each day. What should a solutions
                            architect do to transmit and process the clickstream data?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Design an AWS Data Pipeline to archive the data to an Amazon S3 bucket and run an
                                    Amazon EMR cluster with the data to generate analytics.</li>
                                <li> Create an Auto Scaling group of Amazon EC2 instances to process the data and send
                                    it to an Amazon S3 data lake for Amazon Redshift to use for analysis.</li>
                                <li> Cache the data to Amazon CloudFront. Store the data in an Amazon S3 bucket. When an
                                    object is added to the S3 bucket, run an AWS Lambda function to process the data for
                                    analysis.</li>
                                <li> Collect the data from Amazon Kinesis Data Streams. Use Amazon Kinesis Data firehose
                                    to transmit the data to an Amazon S3 data lake. Load the data in Amazon Redshift for
                                    analysis.</li>
                            </ol>

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 27</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_27" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_27" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is creating a web application that will store a large number of images in Amazon
                            S3. The images will be accessed by users over variable periods of time. The company wants
                            to:<br />Retain all the images <br />Incur no cost for retrieval.<br />Have minimal
                            management overhead.<br />Have the images available with no impact on retrieval
                            time.<br /><br />Which solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Implement S3 Intelligent-Tiering</li>
                                <li> Implement S3 storage class analysis</li>
                                <li> Implement an S3 Lifecycle policy to move data to S3 Standard-Infrequent Access (S3
                                    Standard-IA).</li>
                                <li> Implement an S3 Lifecycle policy to move data to S3 One Zone-Infrequent Access (S3
                                    One Zone-IA).</li>

                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company receives 10 TB of instrumentation data each day from several machines located at a
                            single factory. The data consists of JSON files stored on a storage area network (SAN) in an
                            on-premises data center located within the factory. The company wants to send this data to
                            Amazon S3 where it can be accessed by several additional systems that provide critical
                            near-real-lime analytics. A secure transfer is important because the data is considered
                            sensitive.<br /><br />Which solution offers the MOST reliable data transfer?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> AWS DataSync over public internet</li>
                                <li> AWS DataSync over AWS Direct Connect</li>
                                <li> AWS Database Migration Service (AWS DMS) over public internet</li>
                                <li> AWS Database Migration Service (AWS DMS) over AWS Direct Connect</li>
                            </ol>

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 29</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_29" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_29" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is preparing to deploy a new serverless workload. A solutions architect needs to
                            configure permissions for invoking an AWS Lambda function. The function will be triggered by
                            an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule. Permissions should be configured
                            using the principle of least privilege.<br /><br />Which solution will meet these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Add an execution role to the function with lambda:InvokeFunction as the action and
                                    * as the principal.</li>
                                <li> Add an execution rote to the function with lambda:InvokeFunction as the action and
                                    Service:eventsamazonaws.com as the principal.</li>
                                <li> Add a resource-based policy to the function with lambda:’ as the action and
                                    Service:events.amazonaws.com as the principal.</li>
                                <li> Add a resource-based policy to the function with lambda:InvokeFunction as the
                                    action and Service:events.amazonaws.com as the principal.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ29">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer29" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_30" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_30" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_30"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 30</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_30" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_30" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is building its web application using containers on AWS. The company requires
                            three instances of the web application to run at all times. The application must be able to
                            scale to meet increases in demand.<br /><br />Management is extremely sensitive to cost but
                            agrees that the application should be highly available. What should a solutions architect
                            recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) cluster using the Fargate
                                    launch type. Create a task definition for the web application. Create an ECS service
                                    with a desired count of three tasks.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) cluster using the Amazon
                                    EC2 launch type with three container instances in one Availability Zone. Create a
                                    task definition for the web application. Place one task for each container instance.
                                </li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) cluster using the Fargate
                                    launch type with one container instance in three different Availability Zones.
                                    Create a task definition for the web application. Create an ECS service with a
                                    desired count of three tasks.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) cluster using the Amazon
                                    EC2 launch type with one container instance in two different Availability Zones.
                                    Create a task definition for the web application. Place two tasks on one container
                                    instance and one task on the remaining container instance.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ30">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer30" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>

    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_31" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_31" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_31"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 31</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_31" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_31" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is Re-architecting a strongly coupled application to be loosely coupled.
                            Previously the application used a request/response pattern to communicate between tiers. The
                            company plans to use Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) to achieve decoupling
                            requirements. The initial design contains one queue for requests and one for responses.
                            However, this approach is not processing all the messages as the application
                            scales.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to resolve this issue?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure a dead-letter queue on the ReceiveMessage API action of the SQS queue.
                                </li>
                                <li> Configure a FIFO queue, and use the message deduplication ID and message group ID.
                                </li>
                                <li> Create a temporary queue, with the Temporary Queue Client to receive each response
                                    message.</li>
                                <li> Create a queue for each request and response on startup for each producer, and use
                                    a correlation ID message attribute.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ31">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer31" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_32" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_32" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_32"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 32</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_32" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_32" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is launching an ecommerce website on AWS. This website is built with a three-tier
                            architecture that includes a MySQL database in a Multi-AZ deployment of Amazon Aurora MySQL.
                            The website application must be highly available and will initially be launched in an AWS
                            Region with three Availability Zones The application produces a metric that describes the
                            load the application experiences.<br /><br />Which solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure an Application Load Balancer (ALB) with Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling behind
                                    the ALB with scheduled scaling</li>
                                <li> Configure an Application Load Balancer (ALB) and Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling behind the
                                    ALB with a simple scaling policy.</li>
                                <li> Configure a Network Load Balancer (NLB) and launch a Spot Fleet with Amazon EC2
                                    Auto Scaling behind the NLB.</li>
                                <li> Configure an Application Load Balancer (ALB) and Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling behind the
                                    ALB with a target tracking scaling policy.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>

                    <a aria-controls="collapse_33" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_33"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 33</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_33" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_33" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has no existing file share services. A new project requires access to file storage
                            that is mountable as a drive for on-premises desktops. The file server must authenticate
                            users to an Active Directory domain before they are able to access the
                            storage.<br /><br />Which service will allow Active Directory users to mount storage as a
                            drive on their desktops?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Amazon S3 Glacier</li>
                                <li> AWS DataSync</li>
                                <li> AWS Snowball Edge</li>
                                <li> AWS Storage Gateway</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ33">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer33" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ33" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_33" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_33" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_34" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_34" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_34"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 34</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_34" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_34" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is developing a new machine learning model solution in AWS. The models are
                            developed as independent microservices that fetch about 1 GB of model data from Amazon S3 at
                            startup and load the data into memory. Users access the models through an asynchronous API.
                            Users can send a request or a batch of requests and specify where the results should be
                            sent.<br /><br />The company provides models to hundreds of users. The usage patterns for
                            the models are irregular Some models could be unused for days or weeks. Other models could
                            receive batches of thousands of requests at a time.<br /><br />Which solution meets these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> The requests from the API are sent to an Application Load Balancer (ALB). Models
                                    are deployed as AWS Lambda functions invoked by the ALB.</li>
                                <li> The requests from the API are sent to the models Amazon Simple Queue Service
                                    (Amazon SQS) queue. Models are deployed as AWS Lambda functions triggered by SQS
                                    events AWS Auto Scaling is enabled on Lambda to increase the number of vCPUs based
                                    on the SQS queue size.</li>
                                <li> The requests from the API are sent to the model’s Amazon Simple Queue Service
                                    (Amazon SQS) queue. Models are deployed as Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon
                                    ECS) services reading from the queue AWS App Mesh scales the instances of the ECS
                                    cluster based on the SQS queue size.</li>
                                <li> The requests from the API are sent to the models Amazon Simple Queue Service
                                    (Amazon SQS) queue. Models are deployed as Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon
                                    ECS) services reading from the queue AWS Auto Scaling is enabled on Amazon ECS for
                                    both the cluster and copies of the service based on the queue size.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ34">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer34" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ34" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_34" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_34" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_35" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_35" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_35"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 35</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_35" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_35" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company stores call recordings on a monthly basis. Statistically, the recorded data may be
                            referenced randomly within a year but accessed rarely after 1 year. Files that are newer
                            than 1 year old must be queried and retrieved as quickly as possible. A delay in retrieving
                            older files is acceptable. A solutions architect needs to store the recorded data at a
                            minimal cost.<br /><br />Which solution is MOST cost-effective?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Store individual files in Amazon S3 Glacier and store search metadata in object
                                    tags created in S3 Glacier Query S3 Glacier tags and retrieve the files from S3
                                    Glacier.</li>
                                <li> Store individual files in Amazon S3. Use lifecycle policies to move the files to
                                    Amazon S3 Glacier after1 year. Query and retrieve the files from Amazon S3 or S3
                                    Glacier.</li>
                                <li> Archive individual files and store search metadata for each archive in Amazon S3.
                                    Use lifecycle policies to move the files to Amazon S3 Glacier after 1 year. Query
                                    and retrieve the files by searching for metadata from Amazon S3.</li>
                                <li> Archive individual files in Amazon S3. Use lifecycle policies to move the files to
                                    Amazon S3 Glacier after 1 year. Store search metadata in Amazon DynamoDB. Query the
                                    files from DynamoDB and retrieve them from Amazon S3 or S3 Glacier.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ35">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer35" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ35" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_35" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_35" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>

                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_36" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_36" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is building a payment application that must be highly available even during
                            regional service disruptions. A solutions architect must design a data storage solution that
                            can be easily replicated and used in other AWS Regions. The application also requires
                            low-latency atomicity, consistency, isolation, and durability (ACID) transactions that need
                            to be immediately available to generate reports The development team also needs to use
                            SQL.<br /><br />Which data storage solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Amazon Aurora Global Database</li>
                                <li> Amazon DynamoDB global tables</li>
                                <li> Amazon S3 with cross-Region replication and Amazon Athena</li>
                                <li> MySQL on Amazon EC2 instances with Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) snapshot
                                    replication</li>

                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_37" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_37" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A recently created startup built a three-tier web application. The front end has static
                            content. The application layer is based on microservices. User data is stored as JSON
                            documents that need to be accessed with low latency. The company expects regular traffic to
                            be low during the first year, with peaks in traffic when it publicizes new features every
                            month. The startup team needs to minimize operational overhead costs.<br /><br />What should
                            a solutions architect recommend to accomplish this?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon S3 static website hosting to store and serve the front end. Use AWS
                                    Elastic Beanstalk for the application layer. Use Amazon DynamoDB to store user data.
                                </li>
                                <li> Use Amazon S3 static website hosting to store and serve the front end. Use Amazon
                                    Elastic KubernetesService (Amazon EKS) for the application layer. Use Amazon
                                    DynamoDB to store user data.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon S3 static website hosting to store and serve the front end. Use Amazon
                                    API Gateway and AWS Lambda functions for the application layer. Use Amazon DynamoDB
                                    to store user data.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon S3 static website hosting to store and serve the front end. Use Amazon
                                    API Gateway and AWS Lambda functions for the application layer. Use Amazon RDS with
                                    read replicas to store user data.</li>
                            </ol>

                            minimize costs and provide at least 99% availability. Which solution meets these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>

                                    disabled.</li>
                                <li> Deploy the application to Amazon EC2 instances that run in two AWS Regions and two
                                    Availability Zones.</li>
                                <li> Deploy the application to an Amazon S3 bucket that has versioning and cross-Region
                                    replication enabled.</li>

                                    one Availability Zone.</li>

                            across different AWS Regions. Since the application content will be specific to each

                                <li> Configure Amazon Route 53 with a weighted routing policy.</li>
                                <li> Configure Amazon Route 53 with a geolocation routing policy.</li>
                                <li> Configure Amazon Route 53 with a multivalue answer routing policy</li>

                        </h4>

                <div aria-labelledby="heading_40" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_40" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company provides an online service for posting video content and transcoding it for use by
                            any mobile platform. The application architecture uses Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon
                            EFS) Standard to collect and store the videos so that multiple Amazon EC2 Linux instances
                            can access the video content for processing. As the popularity of the service has grown over
                            time, the storage costs have become too expensive.<br /><br />Which storage solution is MOST
                            cost-effective?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use AWS Storage Gateway for files to store and process the video content.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS Storage Gateway for volumes to store and process the video content.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon EFS for storing the video content. Once processing is complete, transfer
                                    the files to Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS).</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon S3 for storing the video content. Move the files temporarily over to an
                                    Amazon ElasticBlock Store (Amazon EBS) volume attached to the server for processing.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>

                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 41</strong>

                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_41" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_41" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has applications hosted on Amazon EC2 instances with IPv6 addresses. The
                            applications must initiate communications with other external applications using the
                            internet. However, the company’'s security policy states that any external service cannot
                            initiate a connection to the EC2 instances. What should a solutions architect recommend to
                            resolve this issue?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create a NAT gateway and make it the destination of the subnet’s route table.</li>
                                <li> Create an internet gateway and make it the destination of the subnet’s route table.
                                </li>
                                <li> Create a virtual private gateway and make it the destination of the subnet’s route
                                    table.</li>
                                <li> Create an egress-only internet gateway and make it the destination of the subnet’s
                                    route table.</li>
                            </ol>

                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_43" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_43" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is developing a video conversion application hosted on AWS. The application will
                            be available in two tiers: a free tier and a paid tier. Users in the paid tier will have
                            their videos converted first and then the tree tier users will have their videos
                            converted.<br /><br />Which solution meets these requirements and is MOST cost-effective?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> One FIFO queue for the paid tier and one standard queue for the free tier.</li>
                                <li> A single FIFO Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) queue for all file types.
                                </li>
                                <li> A single standard Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) queue for all file
                                    types.</li>
                                <li> Two standard Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) queues with one for the paid
                                    tier and one for the free tier.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ43">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer43" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">

                    <a aria-controls="collapse_44" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_44"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 44</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_44" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_44" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A development team is collaborating with another company to create an integrated product.
                            The other company needs to access an Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) queue that is
                            contained in the development team's account. The other company wants to poll the queue
                            without giving up its own account permissions to do so.<br /><br />How should a solutions
                            architect provide access to the SQS queue?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an instance profile that provides the other company access to the SQS queue.
                                </li>
                                <li> Create an IAM policy that provides the other company access to the SQS queue.</li>
                                <li> Create an SQS access policy that provides the other company access to the SQS
                                    queue.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS) access policy that
                                    provides the other company access to the SQS queue.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ44">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer44" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ44" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_44" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_44" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_45" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_45" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_45"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 45</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_45" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_45" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company requires that all versions of objects in its Amazon S3 bucket be retained. Current
                            object versions will be frequently accessed during the first 30 days, after which they will
                            be rarely accessed and must be retrievable within 5 minutes. Previous object versions need
                            to be kept forever, will be rarely accessed, and can be retrieved within 1 week. All storage
                            solutions must be highly available and highly durable.<br /><br />What should a solutions
                            architect recommend to meet these requirements in the MOST cost-effective manner?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an S3 lifecycle policy for the bucket that moves current object versions
                                    from S3 Standard storage to S3 Glacier after 30 days and moves previous object
                                    versions to S3 Glacier after 1 day.</li>
                                <li> Create an S3 lifecycle policy for the bucket that moves current object versions
                                    from S3 Standard storage to S3 Glacier after 30 days and moves previous object
                                    versions to S3 Glacier Deep Archive after 1 day.</li>
                                <li> Create an S3 lifecycle policy for the bucket that moves current object versions
                                    from S3 Standard storage to S3 Standard-infrequent Access (S3 Standard-IA) after 30
                                    days and moves previous object versions toS3 Glacier Deep Archive after 1 day.</li>
                                <li> Create an S3 lifecycle policy for the bucket that moves current object versions
                                    from S3 Standard storage to S3 One Zone-Infrequent Access (S3 One Zone-IA) after 30
                                    days and moves previous object versions to S3 Glacier Deep Archive after 1 day.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ45">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer45" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ45" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_45" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_45" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

<div class="product-info-box questions">
    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_46" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_46" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_46"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 46</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_46" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_46" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect is designing an architecture to run a third-party database server. The
                            database software is memory intensive and has a CPU-based licensing model where the cost
                            increases with the number of vCPU cores within the operating system. The solutions architect
                            must select an Amazon EC2 instance with sufficient memory to run the database software, but
                            the selected instance has a large number of vCPUs. The solutions architect must ensure that
                            the vCPUs will not be underutilized and must minimize costs.<br /><br />Which solution meets
                            these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Select and launch a smaller EC2 instance with an appropriate number of vCPUs.</li>
                                <li> Configure the CPU cores and threads on the selected EC2 instance during instance
                                    launch.</li>
                                <li> Create a new EC2 instance and ensure multithreading is enabled when configuring the
                                    instance details.</li>
                                <li> Create a new Capacity Reservation and select the appropriate instance type. Launch
                                    the instance into this new Capacity Reservation.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ46">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer46" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ46" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_46" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_46" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_47" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_47" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_47"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 47</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_47" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_47" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is reviewing a recent migration of a three-tier application to a VPC. The security
                            team discovers that the principle of least privilege is not being applied to Amazon EC2
                            security group ingress and egress rules between the application tiers.<br /><br />What
                            should a solutions architect do to correct this issue?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create security group rules using the instance ID as the source or destination.
                                </li>
                                <li> Create security group rules using the security group ID as the source or
                                    destination.</li>
                                <li> Create security group rules using the VPC CIDR blocks as the source or destination.
                                </li>
                                <li> Create security group rules using the subnet CIDR blocks as the source or
                                    destination.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ47">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer47" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ47" role="button">

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_47" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_48" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_48" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_48"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 48</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_48" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_48" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An application allows users at a company’s headquarters to access product data. The product
                            data is stored in an Amazon RDS MySQL DB instance. The operations team has isolated an
                            application performance slowdown and wants to separate read traffic from write traffic. A
                            solutions architect needs to optimize the application’s performance quickly.<br /><br />What
                            should the solutions architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Change the existing database to a Multi-AZ deployment. Serve the read requests from
                                    the primary Availability Zone.</li>
                                <li> Change the existing database to a Multi-AZ deployment. Serve the read requests from
                                    the secondary Availability Zone.</li>
                                <li> Create read replicas for the database. Configure the read replicas with half of the
                                    compute and storage resources as the source database.</li>
                                <li> Create read replicas for the database. Configure the read replicas with the same
                                    compute and storage resources as the source database.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ48">

                            <div id="answer48" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D

            <div class="panel panel-default">

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 49</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_49" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_49" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is running a multi-tier web application on premises. The web application is
                            containerized and runs on a number of Linux hosts connected to a PostgreSQL database that
                            contains user records. The operational overhead of maintaining the infrastructure and
                            capacity planning is limiting the company’s growth. A solutions architect must improve the
                            application’s infrastructure.<br /><br />Which combination of actions should the solutions
                            architect take to accomplish this? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Migrate the PostgreSQL database to Amazon Aurora.</li>
                                <li> Migrate the web application to be hosted on Amazon EC2 instances.</li>
                                <li> Set up an Amazon CloudFront distribution for the web application content.</li>
                                <li> Set up Amazon ElastiCache between the web application and the PostgreSQL database.
                                </li>
                                <li> Migrate the web application to be hosted on AWS Fargate with Amazon Elastic
                                    Container Service (Amazon ECS).</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>

                                <li> Users will be allowed all actions except s3:PutObject if multi-factor
                                    authentication (MFA) is enabled.</li>
                                <li> Users will be allowed all actions except s3:PutObject if multi-factor
                                    authentication (MFA) is not enabled.</li>
                                <li> Users will be denied all actions except s3:PutObject if multi-factor authentication
                                    (MFA) is enabled.</li>

                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 51</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>

                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_51" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_51" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company that recently started using AWS establishes a Site-to-Site VPN between its
                            on-premises datacenter and AWS. The company's security mandate states that traffic
                            originating from on premises should stay within the company’s private IP space when
                            communicating with an Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) cluster that is hosting
                            a sample web application. Which solution meets this requirement?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure a gateway endpoint for Amazon ECS. Modify the route table to include an
                                    entry pointing to the ECS cluster.</li>
                                <li> Create a Network Load Balancer and AWS PrivateLink endpoint for Amazon ECS in the
                                    same VPC that is hosting the ECS cluster.</li>
                                <li> Create a Network Load Balancer in one VPC and an AWS PrivateLink endpoint for
                                    Amazon ECS in another VP Connect the two VPCs by using VPC peering.</li>
                                <li> Configure an Amazon Route 53 record with Amazon ECS as the target. Apply a server
                                    certificate to Route 53 from AWS Certificate Manager (ACM) for SSL offloading.</li>
                            </ol>

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 52</strong>

                <div aria-labelledby="heading_52" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_52" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company plans to host a survey website on AWS. The company anticipates an unpredictable
                            amount of traffic. This traffic results in asynchronous updates to the database. The company
                            wants to ensure that writes to the database hosted on AWS do not get dropped.<br /><br />How
                            should the company write its application to handle these database requests?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure the application to publish to an Amazon Simple Notification Service
                                    (Amazon SNS) topic. Subscribe the database to the SNS topic.</li>
                                <li> Configure the application to subscribe to an Amazon Simple Notification Service
                                    (Amazon SNS) topic. Publish the database updates to the SNS topic.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) FIFO queues to queue the database
                                    connection until the database has resources to write the data.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) FIFO queues for capturing the writes
                                    and draining the queue as each write is made to the database.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>

                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 53</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_53" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_53" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company wants to move its on-premises network, attached storage (NAS) to AWS. The company
                            wants to make the data available to any Linux instances within its VPC and ensure changes
                            are automatically synchronized across all instances accessing the data store. The majority
                            of the data is accessed very rarely, and some files are accessed by multiple users at the
                            same time.<br /><br />Which solution meets these requirements and is MOST cost-effective?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) snapshot containing the data.
                                    Share it with users within the VPC.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon S3 bucket that has a lifecycle policy set to transition the data
                                    to S3 Standard-Infrequent Access (S3 Standard-IA) after the appropriate number of
                                    days.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) file system within the VP Set the
                                    throughput mode to Provisioned and to the required amount of IOPS to support
                                    concurrent usage.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) file system within the VPC. Set
                                    the lifecycle policy to transition the data to EFS Infrequent Access (EFS IA) after
                                    the appropriate number of days.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ53">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer53" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D

                            A company stores 200 GB of data each month in Amazon S3. The company needs to perform
                            analytics on this data at the end of each month to determine the number of items sold in
                            each sales region for the previous month.<br /><br />Which analytics strategy is MOST
                            cost-effective for the company to use?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an Amazon Elasticsearch Service (Amazon ES) cluster. Query the data in
                                    Amazon ES. Visualize the data by using Kibana.</li>
                                <li> Create a table in the AWS Glue Data Catalog. Query the data in Amazon S3 by using
                                    Amazon Athena. Visualize the data in Amazon QuickSight.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon EMR cluster. Query the data by using Amazon EMR, and store the
                                    results in Amazon S3. Visualize the data in Amazon QuickSight.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Redshift cluster. Query the data in Amazon Redshift, and upload
                                    the results to Amazon S3. Visualize the data in Amazon QuickSight.</li>

                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company wants to automate the security assessment of its Amazon EC2 instances. The company
                            needs to validate and demonstrate that security and compliance standards are being followed
                            throughout the development process.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to meet
                            these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon Macie to automatically discover, classify and protect the EC2 instances.
                                </li>
                                <li> Use Amazon GuardDuty to publish Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS)
                                    notifications.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Inspector with Amazon CloudWatch to publish Amazon Simple Notification
                                    Service (Amazon SNS) notifications</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) to detect and react to changes in
                                    the status of AWS Trusted Advisor checks.</li>

                            six Aurora Replicas. The company wants near-real-lime reporting queries from one of its

                                <li> Use any of the instance endpoints for the selected three nodes.</li>

                        <h4 class="panel-title">

                <div aria-labelledby="heading_59" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_59" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect is redesigning a monolithic application to be a loosely coupled
                            application composed of two microservices: Microservice A and Microservice
                            B.<br /><br />Microservice A places messages in a main Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon
                            SQS) queue for Microservice B to consume. When Microservice B fails to process a message
                            after four retries, the message needs to be removed from the queue and stored for further
                            investigation.<br /> <br />What should the solutions architect do to meet these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an SQS dead-letter queue. Microservice B adds failed messages to that queue
                                    after it receives and fails to process the message four times.</li>
                                <li> Create an SQS dead-letter queue. Configure the main SQS queue to deliver messages
                                    to the dead-letter queue after the message has been received four times.</li>
                                <li> Create an SQS queue for failed messages. Microservice A adds failed messages to
                                    that queue after Microservice B receives and fails to process the message four
                                    times.</li>
                                <li> Create an SQS queue for failed messages. Configure the SQS queue for failed
                                    messages to pull messages from the main SQS queue after the original message has
                                    been received four times.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ59">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer59" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ59" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_59" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_59" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_60" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_60" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_60"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 60</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_60" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_60" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect is creating a new Amazon CloudFront distribution for an application.
                            Some of the information submitted by users is sensitive. The application uses HTTPS but
                            needs another layer of security. The sensitive information should be protected throughout
                            the entire application stack, and access to the information should be restricted to certain
                            applications.<br /><br />Which action should the solutions architect take?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure a CloudFront signed URL</li>
                                <li> Configure a CloudFront signed cookie.</li>
                                <li> Configure a CloudFront field-level encryption profile.</li>
                                <li> Configure a CloudFront and set the Origin Protocol Policy setting to HTTPS. Only
                                    for the Viewer Protocol Pokey.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ60">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer60" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ60" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_60" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_60" role="button">
                        </a>

                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_61" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_61" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_61"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 61</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_61" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_61" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is using Amazon DynamoDB with provisioned throughput for the database tier of its
                            ecommerce website. During flash sales, customers experience periods of time when the
                            database cannot handle the high number of transactions taking place. This causes the company
                            to lose transactions. During normal periods, the database performs
                            appropriately.<br /><br />Which solution solves the performance problem the company faces?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Switch DynamoDB to on-demand mode during flash sales.</li>
                                <li> Implement DynamoDB Accelerator for fast in memory performance.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Kinesis to queue transactions for processing to DynamoDB.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) to queue transactions to DynamoDB.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ61">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer61" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 62</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_62" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_62" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is preparing to launch a public-facing web application in the AWS Cloud. The
                            architecture consists of Amazon EC2 instances within a VPC behind an Elastic Load Balancer
                            (ELB). A third party service is used for the DNS. The company’s solutions architect must
                            recommend a solution to detect and protect against largescale DDoS attacks.<br /><br />Which
                            solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Enable Amazon GuardDuty on the account.</li>
                                <li> Enable Amazon Inspector on the EC2 instances.</li>
                                <li> Enable AWS Shield and assign Amazon Route 53 to it.</li>
                                <li> Enable AWS Shield Advanced and assign the ELB to it.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 63</strong>
