                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_63" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_63" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an ecommerce application running in a single VPC. The application stack has a
                            single web server and an Amazon RDS Multi-AZ DB instance.<br /><br />The company launches
                            new products twice a month. This increases website traffic by approximately 400% for a
                            minimum of 72 hours. During product launches, users experience slow response times and
                            frequent timeout errors in their browsers.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do
                            to mitigate the slow response times and timeout errors while minimizing operational
                            overhead?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Increase the instance size of the web server.</li>
                                <li> Add an Application Load Balancer and an additional web server.</li>
                                <li> Add Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling and an Application Load Balancer.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an Amazon ElastiCache cluster to store frequently accessed data.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ63">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer63" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>

                    <a aria-controls="collapse_64" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_64"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 64</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_64" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_64" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company wants to improve the availability and performance of its hybrid application. The
                            application consists of a stateful TCP-based workload hosted on Amazon EC2 instances in
                            different AWS Regions and a stateless UOP-based workload hosted on premises.<br />Which
                            combination of actions should a solutions architect take to improve availability and
                            performance? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an accelerator using AWS Global Accelerator. Add the load balancers as
                                    endpoints.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon CloudFront distribution with an origin that uses Amazon Route 53
                                    latency-based routing to route requests to the load balancers.</li>
                                <li> Configure two Application Load Balancers in each Region. The first will route to
                                    the EC2 endpoints and the second will route to the on-premises endpoints.</li>
                                <li> Configure a Network Load Balancer in each Region to address the EC2 endpoints.
                                    Configure a Network Load Balancer in each Region that routes to the on-premises
                                    endpoints.</li>
                                <li> Configure a Network Load Balancer in each Region to address the EC2 endpoints.
                                    Configure an Application Load Balancer in each Region that routes to the on-premises
                                    endpoints</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ64">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer64" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A,D
                            </div>
                            </p>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_65" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_65" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_65"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 65</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_65" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_65" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has created a multi-tier application for its ecommerce website. The website uses
                            an Application Load Balancer that resides in the public subnets, a web tier in the public
                            subnets, and a MySQL cluster hosted on Amazon EC2 instances in the private subnets. The
                            MySQL database needs to retrieve product catalog and pricing information that is hosted on
                            the internet by a third-party provider. A solutions architect must devices a strategy that
                            maximizes security without increasing operational overhead.<br /><br />What should the
                            solutions architect do to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Deploy a NAT instance in the VPC. Route all the internet-based traffic through the
                                    NAT instance.</li>
                                <li> Deploy a NAT gateway in the public subnets. Modify the private subnet route table
                                    to direct all internet- bound traffic to the NAT gateway.</li>
                                <li> Configure an internet gateway and attach it to the VP Modify the private subnet
                                    route table to direct internet-bound traffic to the internet gateway.</li>
                                <li> Configure a virtual private gateway and attach it to the VPC. Modify the private
                                    subnet route table to direct internet-bound traffic to the virtual private gateway.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ65">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer65" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>

                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_66" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_66" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_66"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 66</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_66" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_66" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect is designing the cloud architecture for a company that needs to host
                            hundreds of machine learning models for its users. During startup, the models need to load
                            up to 10 GB of data from Amazon S3 into memory, but they do not need disk access. Most of
                            the models are used sporadically, but the users expect all of them to be highly available
                            and accessible with low latency.<br /><br />Which solution meets the requirements and is
                            MOST cost-effective?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Deploy models as AWS Lambda functions behind an Amazon API Gateway for each model.
                                </li>
                                <li> Deploy models as Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) services behind an
                                    Application Load Balancer for each model.</li>
                                <li> Deploy models as AWS Lambda functions behind a single Amazon API Gateway with
                                    path-based routing where one path corresponds to each model.</li>
                                <li> Deploy models as Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) services behind a
                                    single Application Load Balancer with path-based routing where one path corresponds
                                    to each model.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ66">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer66" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_66" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_66" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>

            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_67" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_67" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_67"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 67</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_67" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_67" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an application that ingests incoming messages. These messages are then quickly
                            consumed by dozens of other applications and microservices. The number of messages varies
                            drastically and sometimes spikes as high as 100,000 each second. The company wants to
                            decouple the solution and increase scalability.<br /><br />Which solution meets these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Persist the messages to Amazon Kinesis Data Analytics. All the applications will
                                    read and process the messages.</li>
                                <li> Deploy the application on Amazon EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling group, which
                                    scales the number of EC2 instances based on CPU metrics.</li>
                                <li> Write the messages to Amazon Kinesis Data Streams with a single shard. All
                                    applications will read from the stream and process the messages.</li>
                                <li> Publish the messages to an Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS) topic
                                    with one or more Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) subscriptions. All
                                    applications then process the messages from the queues.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ67">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer67" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://aws.amazon.com/kinesis/data-streams/faqs/
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ67" role="button">

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_67" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_67" role="button">

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_68" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_68" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_68"

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 68</strong>

                <div aria-labelledby="heading_68" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_68" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an ecommerce application that stores data in an on-premises SQL database. The
                            company has decided to migrate this database to AWS. However, as part of the migration, the
                            company wants to find a way to attain sub-millisecond responses to common read
                            requests.<br /><br />A solutions architect knows that the increase in speed is paramount and
                            that a small percentage of stale data returned in the database reads is
                            acceptable.<br /><br />What should the solutions architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Build Amazon RDS read replicas.</li>
                                <li> Build the database as a larger instance type.</li>
                                <li> Build a database cache using Amazon ElastiCache.</li>
                                <li> Build a database cache using Amazon Elasticsearch Service (Amazon ES).</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ68">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer68" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>

                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_68" role="button">

                </div>

            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_69" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_69" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_69"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 69</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_69" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_69" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is developing an ecommerce application that will consist of a load-balanced front
                            end, a container- based application, and a relational database. A solutions architect needs
                            to create a highly available solution that operates with as little manual intervention as
                            possible.<br /><br />Which solutions meet these requirements? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an Amazon RDS DB instance in Multi-AZ mode.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon RDS DB instance and one or more replicas in another Availability
                                    Zone.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon EC2 instance-based Docker cluster to handle the dynamic
                                    application load.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) cluster with a Fargate
                                    launch type to handle the dynamic application load.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) cluster with an Amazon EC2
                                    launch type to handle the dynamic application load.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ69">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer69" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A,D
                            </div>

            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_70" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_70" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_70"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 70</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_70" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_70" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is using a third-party vendor to manage its marketplace analytics. The vendor
                            needs limited programmatic access to resources in the company’s account. All the needed
                            policies have been created to grant appropriate access.<br /><br />Which additional
                            component will provide the vendor with the MOST secure access to the account?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an IAM user.</li>
                                <li> Implement a service control policy (SCP)</li>
                                <li> Use a cross-account role with an external ID.</li>
                                <li> Configure a single sign-on (SSO) identity provider.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ70">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer70" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>

                            </div>

<div class="product-info-box questions">
    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_71" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_71" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_71"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 71</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_71" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_71" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an on-premises volume backup solution that has reached its end of life. The
                            company wants to use AWS as part of a new backup solution and wants to maintain local access
                            to all the data while it is backed up on AWS. The company wants to ensure that the data
                            backed up on AWS is automatically and securely transferred.<br /><br />Which solution meets
                            these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use AWS Snowball to migrate data out of the on-premises solution to Amazon S3.
                                    Configure on-premises systems to mount the Snowball S3 endpoint to provide local
                                    access to the data.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS Snowball Edge to migrate data out of the on-premises solution to Amazon S3.
                                    Use the Snowball Edge file interface to provide on-premises systems with local
                                    access to the data.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS Storage Gateway and configure a cached volume gateway. Run the Storage
                                    Gateway software appliance on premises and configure a percentage of data to cache
                                    locally. Mount the gateway storage volumes to provide local access to the data.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS Storage Gateway and configure a stored volume gateway. Run the Storage
                                    Gateway software appliance on premises and map the gateway storage volumes to
                                    on-premises storage. Mount the gateway storage volumes to provide local access to
                                    the data.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ71">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer71" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ71" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_71" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_71" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_72" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_72" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_72"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 72</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_72" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_72" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            The financial application at a company stores monthly reports in an Amazon S3 bucket. The
                            vice president of finance has mandated that all access to these reports be logged and that
                            any modifications to the log files be detected.<br /><br />Which actions can a solutions
                            architect take to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use S3 server access logging on the bucket that houses the reports with the read
                                    and write data events and log file validation options enabled.</li>
                                <li> Use S3 server access logging on the bucket that houses the reports with the read
                                    and write management events and log file validation options enabled.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS CloudTrail to create a new trail. Configure the trail to log read and write
                                    data events on the S3 bucket that houses the reports. Log these events to a new
                                    bucket, and enable log file validation.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS CloudTrail to create a new trail. Configure the trail to log read and write
                                    management events on the S3 bucket that houses the reports. Log these events to a
                                    new bucket, and enable log file validation.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ72">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer72" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/user-guide/enable-cloudtrail-events.html
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_72" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_73" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_73" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_73"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 73</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_73" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_73" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an image processing workload running on Amazon Elastic Container Service
                            (Amazon ECS) in two private subnets. Each private subnet uses a NAT instance for internet
                            access. All images are stored in Amazon S3 buckets. The company is concerned about the data
                            transfer costs between Amazon ECS and Amazon S3.<br /><br />What should a solutions
                            architect do to reduce costs?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure a NAT gateway to replace the NAT instances.</li>
                                <li> Configure a gateway endpoint for traffic destined to Amazon S3.</li>
                                <li> Configure an interface endpoint for traffic destined to Amazon S3.</li>
                                <li> Configure Amazon CloudFront for the S3 bucket storing the images.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ73">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer73" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>

                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_73" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_74" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_74" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_74"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 74</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_74" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_74" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has a build server that is in an Auto Scaling group and often has multiple Linux
                            instances running. The build server requires consistent and mountable shared NFS storage for
                            jobs and configurations. Which storage option should a solutions architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Amazon S3</li>
                                <li> Amazon FSx</li>
                                <li> Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS)</li>
                                <li> Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS)</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ74">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer74" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_75" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_75" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_75"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 75</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_75" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_75" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            Management has decided to deploy all AWS VPCs with IPv6 enabled. After some time, a
                            solutions architect tries to launch a new instance and receives an error stating that there
                            is not enough IP address space available in the subnet.<br /><br />What should the solutions
                            architect do to fix this?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Check to make sure that only IPv6 was used during the VPC creation.</li>
                                <li> Create a new IPv4 subnet with a larger range, and then launch the instance.</li>
                                <li> Create a new IPv6-only subnet with a large range, and then launch the instance.
                                </li>
                                <li> Disable the IPv4 subnet and migrate all instances to IPv6 only. Once that is
                                    complete, launch the instance.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ75">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer75" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ75" role="button">

                        </a>

<div class="product-info-box questions">
    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_76" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_76" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_76"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 76</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_76" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_76" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has a hybrid application hosted on multiple on-premises servers with static IP
                            addresses. There is already a VPN that provides connectivity between the VPC and the
                            on-premises network. The company wants to distribute TCP traffic across the on-premises
                            servers for internet users.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect recommend to
                            provide a highly available and scalable solution?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Launch an internet-facing Network Load Balancer (NLB) and register on-premises IP
                                    addresses with the NLB.</li>
                                <li> Launch an internet-facing Application Load Balancer (ALB) and register on-premises
                                    IP addresses with the AL</li>
                                <li> Launch an Amazon EC2 instance, attach an Elastic IP address, and distribute traffic
                                    to the on-premises servers.</li>
                                <li> Launch an Amazon EC2 instance with public IP addresses in an Auto Scaling group and
                                    distribute traffic to the on-premises servers.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ76">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer76" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ76" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_76" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_76" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_77" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_77" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_77"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 77</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_77" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_77" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company runs a production application on a fleet of Amazon EC2 instances. The application
                            reads the data from an Amazon SQS queue and processes the messages in parallel. The message
                            volume is unpredictable and often has intermittent traffic. This application should
                            continually process messages without any downtime.<br /><br />Which solution meets these
                            requirements MOST cost-effectively?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Spot Instances exclusively to handle the maximum capacity required.</li>
                                <li> Use Reserved Instances exclusively to handle the maximum capacity required.</li>
                                <li> Use Reserved Instances for the baseline capacity and use Spot Instances to handle
                                    additional capacity.</li>
                                <li> Use Reserved Instances for the baseline capacity and use On-Demand Instances to
                                    handle additional capacity.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ77">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer77" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ77" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_77" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_77" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_78" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_78" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_78"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 78</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_78" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_78" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company hosts a training site on a fleet of Amazon EC2 instances. The company anticipates
                            that its new course, which consists of dozens of training videos on the site, will be
                            extremely popular when it is released in 1 week.<br /><br />What should a solutions
                            architect do to minimize the anticipated server load?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Store the videos in Amazon ElastiCache for Redis. Update the web servers to serve
                                    the videos using the ElastiCache API.</li>
                                <li> Store the videos in Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS). Create a user data
                                    script for the web servers to mount the EFS volume.</li>
                                <li> Store the videos in an Amazon S3 bucket. Create an Amazon CloudFront distribution
                                    with an origin access identity (OAI) of that S3 bucket. Restrict Amazon S3 access to
                                    the OAI.</li>
                                <li> Store the videos in an Amazon S3 bucket. Create an AWS Storage Gateway file gateway
                                    to access the S3 bucket. Create a user data script for the web servers to mount the
                                    file gateway.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ78">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer78" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ78" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_78" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_78" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_79" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_79" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_79"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 79</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_79" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_79" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company hosts its static website content from an Amazon S3 bucket in the us-east-1 Region.
                            Content is made available through an Amazon CloudFront origin pointing to that bucket.
                            Cross-Region replication is set to create a second copy of the bucket in the ap-southeast-1
                            Region. Management wants a solution that provides greater availability for the
                            website.<br /><br />Which combination of actions should a solutions architect take to
                            increase availability? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Add both buckets to the CloudFront origin.</li>
                                <li> Configure failover routing in Amazon Route 53.</li>
                                <li> Create a record in Amazon Route 53 pointing to the replica bucket.</li>
                                <li> Create an additional CloudFront origin pointing to the ap-southeast-1 bucket.</li>
                                <li> Set up a CloudFront origin group with the us-east-1 bucket as the primary and the
                                    ap-southeast-1 bucket as the secondary.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ79">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer79" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B,E
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ79" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_79" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_79" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_80" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_80" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_80"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 80</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_80" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_80" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has a live chat application running on its on-premises servers that use
                            WebSockets. The company wants to migrate the application to AWS. Application traffic is
                            inconsistent, and the company expects there to be more traffic with sharp spikes in the
                            future.<br /><br />The company wants a highly scalable solution with no server maintenance
                            nor advanced capacity planning. Which solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon API Gateway and AWS Lambda with an Amazon DynamoDB table as the data
                                    store. Configure the DynamoDB table for provisioned capacity.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon API Gateway and AWS Lambda with an Amazon DynamoDB table as the data
                                    store. Configure the DynamoDB table for on-demand capacity.</li>
                                <li> Run Amazon EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer in an Auto Scaling
                                    group with an Amazon DynamoDB table as the data store. Configure the DynamoDB table
                                    for on-demand capacity.</li>
                                <li> Run Amazon EC2 instances behind a Network Load Balancer in an Auto Scaling group
                                    with an Amazon DynamoDB table as the data store. Configure the DynamoDB table for
                                    provisioned capacity.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ80">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer80" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ80" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_80" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_80" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>

<div class="product-info-box questions">
    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_81" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_81" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_81"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 81</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_81" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_81" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company that hosts its web application on AWS wants to ensure all Amazon EC2 instances,
                            Amazon RDS DB instances, and Amazon Redshift clusters are configured with tags. The company
                            wants to minimize the effort of configuring and operating this check.<br /><br />What should
                            a solutions architect do to accomplish this?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use AWS Config rules to define and detect resources that are not properly tagged.
                                </li>
                                <li> Use Cost Explorer to display resources that are not properly tagged. Tag those
                                    resources manually.</li>
                                <li> Write API calls to check all resources for proper tag allocation. Periodically run
                                    the code on an EC2 instance.</li>
                                <li> Write API calls to check all resources for proper tag allocation. Schedule an AWS
                                    Lambda function through Amazon CloudWatch to periodically run the code.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ81">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer81" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://d1.awsstatic.com/whitepapers/aws-tagging-best-practices.pdf
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ81" role="button">
                        </a>

                                <li> Configure Auto Scaling to automatically adjust the capacity of the website.</li>

                            predictable capacity and uptime requirements. The company wants to use its existing

                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 87</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_87" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_87" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is hosting its static website in an Amazon S3 bucket, which is the origin for
                            Amazon CloudFront. The company has users in the United States, Canada, and Europe and wants
                            to reduce costs.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Adjust the CloudFront caching time to live (TTL) from the default to a longer
                                    timeframe.</li>
                                <li> Implement CloudFront events with Lambda@Edge to run the website’s data processing.
                                </li>
                                <li> Modify the CloudFront price class to include only the locations of the countries
                                    that are served.</li>
                                <li> Implement a CloudFront Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) certificate to push security
                                    closer to the locations of the countries that are served.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ87">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer87" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 88</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_88" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_88" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has a highly dynamic batch processing job that uses many Amazon EC2 instances to
                            complete it. The job is stateless in nature, can be started and stopped at any given time
                            with no negative impact, and typically takes upwards of 60 minutes total to complete. The
                            company has asked a solutions architect to design a scalable and cost-effective solution
                            that meets the requirements of the job.<br /><br />What should the solutions architect
                            recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Implement EC2 Spot Instances.</li>
                                <li> Purchase EC2 Reserved Instances.</li>
                                <li> Implement EC2 On-Demand Instances.</li>
                                <li> Implement the processing on AWS Lambda.</li>
                            </ol>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_89" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_89" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_89"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 89</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_89" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_89" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company runs a static website through its on-premises data center. The company has
                            multiple servers that handle all of its traffic, but on busy days, services are interrupted
                            and the website becomes unavailable. The company wants to expand its presence globally and
                            plans to triple its website traffic.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect recommend
                            to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Migrate the website content to Amazon S3 and host the website on Amazon CloudFront.
                                </li>
                                <li> Migrate the website content to Amazon EC2 instances with public Elastic IP
                                    addresses in multiple AWS Regions.</li>
                                <li> Migrate the website content to Amazon EC2 instances and vertically scale as the
                                    load increases.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Route 53 to distribute the loads across multiple Amazon CloudFront
                                    distributions for each AWS Region that exists globally.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ89">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer89" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_90" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_90" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_90"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 90</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_90" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_90" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect needs to ensure that all Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS)
                            volumes restored from unencrypted EBC snapshots are encrypted.<br /><br />What should the
                            solutions architect do to accomplish this?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Enable EBS encryption by default for the AWS Region.</li>
                                <li> Enable EBS encryption by default for the specific volumes.</li>
                                <li> Create a new volume and specify the symmetric customer master key (CMK) to use for
                                    encryption.</li>
                                <li> Create a new volume and specify the asymmetric customer master key (CMK) to use for
                                    encryption.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ90">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer90" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/EBSEncryption.html#volume-account-off
                                </p>
                            </div>

<div class="product-info-box questions">
    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_91" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_91" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_91"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 91</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_91" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_91" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect is designing a multi-Region disaster recovery solution for an
                            application that will provide public API access. The application will use Amazon EC2
                            instances with a userdata script to load application code and an Amazon RDS for MySQL
                            database. The Recovery Time Objective (RTO) is 3 hours and the Recovery Point Objective
                            (RPO) is 24 hours.<br /><br />Which architecture would meet these requirements at the LOWEST
                            cost?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use an Application Load Balancer for Region failover. Deploy new EC2 instances with
                                    the userdata script. Deploy separate RDS instances in each Region.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Route 53 for Region failover. Deploy new EC2 instances with the userdata
                                    script. Create a read replica of the RDS instance in a backup Region.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon API Gateway for the public APIs and Region failover. Deploy new EC2
                                    instances with the userdata script. Create a MySQL read replica of the RDS instance
                                    in a backup Region.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Route 53 for Region failover. Deploy new EC2 instances with the userdata
                                    script for APIs, and create a snapshot of the RDS instance daily for a backup.
                                    Replicate the snapshot to a backup Region.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ91">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer91" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ91" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_91" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_91" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_92" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_92" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_92"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 92</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_92" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_92" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is backing up on-premises databases to local file server shares using the SMB
                            protocol. The company requires immediate access to 1 week of backup files to meet recovery
                            objectives. Recovery after a week is less likely to occur, and the company can tolerate a
                            delay in accessing those older backup files.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do
                            to meet these requirements with the LEAST operational effort?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Deploy Amazon FSx for Windows File Server to create a file system with exposed file
                                    shares with sufficient storage to hold all the desired backups.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an AWS Storage Gateway file gateway with sufficient storage to hold 1 week
                                    of backups. Point the backups to SMB shares from the file gateway.</li>
                                <li> Deploy Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) to create a file system with exposed
                                    NFS shares with sufficient storage to hold all the desired backups.</li>
                                <li> Continue to back up to the existing file shares. Deploy AWS Database Migration
                                    Service (AWS DMS) and define a copy task to copy backup files older than 1 week to
                                    Amazon S3, and delete the backup files from the local file store.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ92">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer92" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ92" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_92" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_92" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_93" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_93" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_93"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 93</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_93" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_93" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has developed a microservices application. It uses a client-facing API with Amazon
                            API Gateway and multiple internal services hosted on Amazon EC2 instances to process user
                            requests. The API is designed to support unpredictable surges in traffic, but internal
                            services may become overwhelmed and unresponsive for a period of time during surges. A
                            solutions architect needs to design a more reliable solution that reduces errors when
                            internal services become unresponsive or unavailable.<br /> <br />Which solution meets these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use AWS Auto Scaling to scale up internal services when there is a surge in
                                    traffic.</li>
                                <li> Use different Availability Zones to host internal services. Send a notification to
                                    a system administrator when an internal service becomes unresponsive.</li>
                                <li> Use an Elastic Load Balancer to distribute the traffic between internal services.
                                    Configure Amazon CloudWatch metrics to monitor traffic to internal services.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) to store user requests as they arrive.
                                    Change the internal services to retrieve the requests from the queue for processing.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ93">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer93" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ93" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_93" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_93" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_94" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_94" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_94"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 94</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_94" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_94" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is hosting 60 TB of production-level data in an Amazon S3 bucket. A solution
                            architect needs to bring that data on premises for quarterly audit requirements. This export
                            of data must be encrypted while in transit. The company has low network bandwidth in place
                            between AWS and its on-premises data center.<br /><br />What should the solutions architect
                            do to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Deploy AWS Migration Hub with 90-day replication windows for data transfer.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an AWS Storage Gateway volume gateway on AWS. Enable a 90-day replication
                                    window to transfer the data.</li>
                                <li> Deploy Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS), with lifecycle policies enabled, on
                                    AWS. Use it to transfer the data.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an AWS Snowball device in the on-premises data center after completing an
                                    export job request in the AWS Snowball console.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ94">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer94" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ94" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_94" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_94" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_95" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_95" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_95"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 95</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_95" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_95" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company uses Amazon S3 to store its confidential audit documents. The S3 bucket uses
                            bucket policies to restrict access to audit team IAM user credentials according to the
                            principle of least privilege. Company managers are worried about accidental deletion of
                            documents in the S3 bucket and want a more secure solution.<br /><br />What should a
                            solutions architect do to secure the audit documents?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Enable the versioning and MFA Delete features on the S3 bucket.</li>
                                <li> Enable multi-factor authentication (MFA) on the IAM user credentials for each audit
                                    team IAM user account.</li>
                                <li> Add an S3 Lifecycle policy to the audit team’s IAM user accounts to deny the
                                    s3:DeleteObject action during audit dates.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) to encrypt the S3 bucket and restrict
                                    audit team IAN user accounts from accessing the KMS key.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ95">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer95" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/dev/security-best-practices.html
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />

                <div aria-labelledby="heading_96" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_96" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect wants all new users to have specific complexity requirements and
                            mandatory rotation periods for IAM user passwords. What should the solutions architect do to
                            accomplish this?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Set an overall password policy for the entire AWS account</li>
                                <li> Set a password policy for each IAM user in the AWS account.</li>
                                <li> Use third-party vendor software to set password requirements.</li>
                                <li> Attach an Amazon CloudWatch rule to the Create_newuser event to set the password
                                    with the appropriate requirements.</li>
                            </ol>
