            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_124" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_124" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_124"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 124</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_124" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_124" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company serves a multilingual website from a fleet of Amazon EC2 instances behind an
                            Application Load Balancer (ALB). This architecture is currently running in the us-west-1
                            Region but is exhibiting high request latency for users located in other parts of the
                            world.<br /><br />The website needs to serve requests quickly and efficiently regardless of
                            a user’s location. However, the company does not want to recreate the existing architecture
                            across multiple Regions.<br /><br />How should a solutions architect accomplish this?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Replace the existing architecture with a website served from an Amazon S3 bucket.
                                    Configure an Amazon CloudFront distribution with the S3 bucket as the origin.</li>
                                <li> Configure an Amazon CloudFront distribution with the ALB as the origin. Set the
                                    cache behavior settings to only cache based on the Accept-Language request header.
                                </li>
                                <li> Set up Amazon API Gateway with the ALB as an integration. Configure API Gateway to
                                    use an HTTP integration type. Set up an API Gateway stage to enable the API cache.
                                </li>
                                <li> Launch an EC2 instance in each additional Region and configure NGINX to act as a
                                    cache server for that Region. Put all the instances plus the ALB behind an Amazon
                                    Route 53 record set with a geolocation routing policy.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ124">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer124" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ124" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_124" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_124" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_125" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_125" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_125"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 125</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_125" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_125" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has a custom application with embedded credentials that retrieves information from
                            an Amazon RDS MySQL DB instance. Management says the application must be made more secure
                            with the least amount of programming effort.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do
                            to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) customer master keys (CMKs) to create
                                    keys. Configure the application to load the database credentials from AWS KMS.
                                    Enable automatic key rotation.</li>
                                <li> Create credentials on the RDS for MySQL database for the application user and store
                                    the credentials in AWS Secrets Manager. Configure the application to load the
                                    database credentials from Secrets Manager. Create an AWS Lambda function that
                                    rotates the credentials in Secret Manager.</li>
                                <li> Create credentials on the RDS for MySQL database for the application user and store
                                    the credentials in AWS Secrets Manager. Configure the application to load the
                                    database credentials from Secrets Manager. Set up a credentials rotation schedule
                                    for the application user in the RDS for MySQL database using Secrets Manager.</li>
                                <li> Create credentials on the RDS for MySQL database for the application user and store
                                    the credentials in AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store. Configure the application to
                                    load the database credentials from Parameter Store. Set up a credentials rotation
                                    schedule for the application user in the RDS for MySQL database using Parameter
                                    Store.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ125">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer125" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ125" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_125" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_125" role="button">

<div class="product-info-box questions">
    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_126" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_126" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_126"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 126</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_126" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_126" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is running a multi-tier web application on AWS. The application runs its database
                            tier on Amazon Aurora MySQL. The application and database tiers are in the us-east-1 Region.
                            A database administrator who regularly monitors the Aurora DB cluster finds that an
                            intermittent increase in read traffic is creating high CPUutilization on the read replica
                            and causing increased read latency of the application.<br /><br />What should a solutions
                            architect do to improve read scalability?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Reboot the Aurora DB cluster.</li>
                                <li> Create a cross-Region read replica</li>
                                <li> Increase the instance class of the read replica.</li>
                                <li> Configure Aurora Auto Scaling for the read replica.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ126">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer126" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ126" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_126" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_126" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_127" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_127" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_127"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 127</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_127" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_127" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company’s order fulfillment service uses a MySQL database. The database needs to support a
                            large number of concurrent queries and transactions. Developers are spending time patching
                            and tuning the database This is causing delays in releasing new product
                            features.<br /><br />The company wants to use cloud-based services to help address this new
                            challenge. The solution must allow the developers to migrate the database with little or no
                            code changes and must optimize performance.<br /><br />Which service should a solutions
                            architect use to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Amazon Aurora</li>
                                <li> Amazon DynamoDB</li>
                                <li> Amazon ElastiCache</li>
                                <li> MySQL on Amazon EC2</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ127">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer127" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_127" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_128" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_128" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_128"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 128</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_128" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_128" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is planning to migrate a TCP-based application into the company’s VPC. The
                            application is publicly accessible on a nonstandard TCP port through a hardware appliance in
                            the company’s data center. This public endpoint can process up to 3 million requests per
                            second with low latency. The company requires the same level of performance for the new
                            public endpoint in AWS.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect recommend to meet this
                            requirement?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Deploy a Network Load Balancer (NLB). Configure the NLB to be publicly accessible
                                    over the TCP port that the application requires.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an Application Load Balancer (ALB). Configure the ALB to be publicly
                                    accessible over the TCP port that the application requires.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an Amazon CloudFront distribution that listens on the TCP port that the
                                    application requires. Use an Application Load Balancer as the origin.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an Amazon API Gateway API that is configured with the TCP port that the
                                    application requires. Configure AWS Lambda functions with provisioned concurrency to
                                    process the requests.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ128">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer128" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_128" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_129" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_129" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_129"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 129</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_129" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_129" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company operates a two-tier application for image processing. The application uses two
                            Availability Zones, each with one public subnet and one private subnet. An Application Load
                            Balancer (ALB) for the web tier uses the public subnets. Amazon EC2 instances for the
                            application tier use the private subnets.<br /><br />Users report that the application is
                            running more slowly than expected. A security audit of the web server log files shows that
                            the application is receiving millions of illegitimate requests from a small number of IP
                            addresses. A solutions architect needs to resolve the immediate performance problem while
                            the company investigates a more permanent solution.<br /><br />What should the solutions
                            architect recommend to meet this requirement?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Modify the inbound security group for the web tier. Add a deny rule for the IP
                                    addresses that are consuming resources.</li>
                                <li> Modify the network ACL for the web tier subnets. Add an inbound deny rule for the
                                    IP addresses that are consuming resources.</li>
                                <li> Modify the inbound security group for the application tier. Add a deny rule for the
                                    IP addresses that are consuming resources.</li>
                                <li> Modify the network ACL for the application tier subnets. Add an inbound deny rule
                                    for the IP addresses that are consuming resources.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ129">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer129" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ129" role="button">

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_129" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_129" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_130" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_130" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_130"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 130</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_130" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_130" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A media company is using two video conversion tools that run on Amazon EC2 instances. One
                            tool runs on Windows instances, and the other tool runs on Linux instances. Each video file
                            is large in size and must be processed by both tools.<br /><br />The company needs a storage
                            solution that can provide a centralized file system that can be mounted on all the EC2
                            instances that are used in this process.<br /><br />Which solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon FSx for Windows File Server for the Windows instances. Use Amazon
                                    Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) with Max I/O performance mode for the Linux
                                    instances.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon FSx for Windows File Server for the Windows instances. Use Amazon FSx
                                    for Lustre for the Linux instances. Link both Amazon FSx file systems to the same
                                    Amazon S3 bucket.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) with General Purpose performance mode
                                    for the Windows instances and the Linux instances</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon FSx for Windows File Server for the Windows instances and the Linux
                                    instances.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ130">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer130" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_130" role="button">

        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_131" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_131" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_131"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 131</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_131" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_131" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect must provide an automated solution for a company’s compliance policy
                            that states security groups cannot include a rule that allows SSH from 0.0.0.0/0. The
                            company needs to be notified if there is any breach in the policy. A solution is needed as
                            soon as possible.<br /><br />What should the solutions architect do to meet these
                            requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Write an AWS Lambda script that monitors security groups for SSH being open to
                                    0.0.0.0/0 addresses and creates a notification every time it finds one.</li>
                                <li> Enable the restricted-ssh AWS Config managed rule and generate an Amazon Simple
                                    Notification Service (Amazon SNS) notification when a noncompliant rule is created.
                                </li>
                                <li> Create an IAM role with permissions to globally open security groups and network
                                    ACLs. Create an Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS) topic to generate a
                                    notification every time the role is assumed by a user.</li>
                                <li> Configure a service control policy (SCP) that prevents non-administrative users
                                    from creating or editing security groups. Create a notification in the ticketing
                                    system when a user requests a rule that needs administrator permissions.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ131">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer131" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>

                                <p>
                                    https://www.stratoscale.com/blog/compute/aws-security-groups-5-best-practices/
                                </p>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_132" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_132" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_132"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 132</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_132" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_132" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A security team needs to enforce the rotation of all IAM users’ access keys every 90 days.
                            If an access key is found to be older, the key must be made inactive and removed. A
                            solutions architect must create a solution that will check for and remediate any keys older
                            than 90 days.<br /><br />Which solution meets these requirements with the LEAST operational
                            effort?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an AWS Config rule to check for the key age. Configure the AWS Config rule
                                    to run an AWS Batch job to remove the key.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule to check for the key
                                    age. Configure the rule to run an AWS Batch job to remove the key.</li>
                                <li> Create an AWS Config rule to check for the key age. Define an Amazon EventBridge
                                    (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule to schedule an AWS Lambda function to remove the
                                    key.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule to check for the key
                                    age. Define an EventBridge (CloudWatch Events) rule to run an AWS Batch job to
                                    remove the key.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ132">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer132" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_133" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_133" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_133"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 133</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_133" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_133" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company runs its two-tier ecommerce website on AWS. The web tier consists of a load
                            balancer that sends traffic to Amazon EC2 instances. The database tier uses an Amazon RDS DB
                            instance. The EC2 instances and the RDS DB instance should not be exposed to the public
                            internet. The EC2 instances require internet access to complete payment processing of orders
                            through a third-party web service. The application must be highly
                            available.<br /><br />Which combination of configuration options will meet these
                            requirements? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use an Auto Scaling group to launch the EC2 instances in private subnets. Deploy an
                                    RDS Multi-AZ DB instance in private subnets.</li>
                                <li> Configure a VPC with two private subnets and two NAT gateways across two
                                    Availability Zones. Deploy an Application Load Balancer in the private subnets.</li>
                                <li> Use an Auto Scaling group to launch the EC2 instances in public subnets across two
                                    Availability Zones. Deploy an RDS Multi-AZ DB instance in private subnets.</li>
                                <li> Configure a VPC with one public subnet, one private subnet, and two NAT gateways
                                    across two Availability Zones. Deploy an Application Load Balancer in the public
                                    subnet.</li>
                                <li> Configure a VPC with two public subnets, two private subnets, and two NAT gateways
                                    across two Availability Zones. Deploy an Application Load Balancer in the public
                                    subnets.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ133">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer133" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A,B
                            </div>
                            </p>

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_133" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_133" role="button">

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_134" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_134" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_134"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 134</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_134" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_134" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is building an online multiplayer game. The game communicates by using UDP, and
                            low latency between the client and the backend is important. The backend is hosted on Amazon
                            EC2 instances that can be deployed to multiple AWS Regions to meet demand. The company needs
                            the game to be highly available so that users around the world can access the game at all
                            times.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Deploy Amazon CloudFront to support the global traffic. Configure CloudFront with
                                    an origin group to allow access to EC2 instances in multiple Regions.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an Application Load Balancer in one Region to distribute traffic to EC2
                                    instances in each Region that hosts the game’s backend instances.</li>
                                <li> Deploy Amazon CloudFront to support an origin access identity (OAI). Associate the
                                    OAI with EC2 instances in each Region to support global traffic.</li>
                                <li> Deploy a Network Load Balancer in each Region to distribute the traffic. Use AWS
                                    Global Accelerator to route traffic to the correct Regional endpoint.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ134">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer134" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudFront/latest/DeveloperGuide/private-content-restricting-access-to-s3.html
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ134" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_134" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_134" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_135" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_135" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_135"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 135</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_135" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_135" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company recently launched a new service that involves medical images. The company scans
                            the images and sends them from its on-premises data center through an AWS Direct Connect
                            connection to Amazon EC2 instances. After processing is complete, the images are stored in
                            an Amazon S3 bucket.<br /><br />A company requirement states that the EC2 instances cannot
                            be accessible through the internet. The EC2 instances run in a private subnet, which has a
                            default route back to the on-premises data center for outbound internet
                            access.<br /><br />Usage of the new service is increasing rapidly. A solutions architect
                            must recommend a solution that meets the company’s requirements and reduces the Direct
                            Connect charges.<br /><br />Which solution accomplishes these goals MOST cost-effectively?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure a VPC endpoint for Amazon S3. Add an entry to the private subnet’s route
                                    table for the S3 endpoint.</li>
                                <li> Configure a NAT gateway in a public subnet. Configure the private subnet’s route
                                    table to use the NAT gateway.</li>
                                <li> Configure Amazon S3 as a file system mount point on the EC2 instances. Access
                                    Amazon S3 through the mount.</li>
                                <li> Move the EC2 instances into a public subnet. Configure the public subnet route
                                    table to point to an internet gateway.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ135">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer135" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ135" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_135" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_135" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>

<div class="product-info-box questions">
    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_136" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_136" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_136"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 136</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_136" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_136" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is building an application that consists of several microservices. The company has
                            decided to use container technologies to deploy its software on AWS. The company needs a
                            solution that minimizes the amount of ongoing effort for maintenance and scaling. The
                            company cannot manage additional infrastructure.<br /> <br />Which combination of actions
                            should a solutions architect take to meet these requirements? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Deploy an Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) cluster.</li>
                                <li> Deploy the Kubernetes control plane on Amazon EC2 instances that span multiple
                                    Availability Zones.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) service with an Amazon EC2
                                    launch type. Specify a desired task number level of greater than or equal to 2.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) service with a Fargate
                                    launch type. Specify a desired task number level of greater than or equal to 2.</li>
                                <li> Deploy Kubernetes worker nodes on Amazon EC2 instances that span multiple
                                    Availability Zones. Create a deployment that specifies two or more replicas for each
                                    microservice.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ136">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer136" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A,B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ136" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_136" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_136" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_137" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_137" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_137"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 137</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_137" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_137" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company hosts a multi-tier web application that uses an Amazon Aurora MySQL DB cluster for
                            storage. The application tier is hosted on Amazon EC2 instances. The company’s IT security
                            guidelines mandate that the database credentials be encrypted and rotated every 14
                            days.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to meet this requirement with the
                            LEAST operational effort?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create a new AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) encryption key. Use AWS Secrets
                                    Manager to create a new secret that uses the KMS key with the appropriate
                                    credentials. Associate the secret with the Aurora DB cluster. Configure a custom
                                    rotation period of 14 days.</li>
                                <li> Create two parameters in AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store: one for the user name
                                    as a string parameter and one that uses the SecureString type for the password.
                                    Select AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) encryption for the password parameter,
                                    and load these parameters in the application tier. Implement an AWS Lambda function
                                    that rotates the password every 14 days.</li>
                                <li> Store a file that contains the credentials in an AWS Key Management Service (AWS
                                    KMS) encrypted Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) file system. Mount the EFS
                                    file system in all EC2 instances of the application tier. Restrict the access to the
                                    file on the file system so that the application can read the file and that only
                                    super users can modify the file. Implement an AWS Lambda function that rotates the
                                    key in Aurora every 14 days and writes new credentials into the file.</li>
                                <li> Store a file that contains the credentials in an AWS Key Management Service (AWS
                                    KMS) encrypted Amazon S3 bucket that the application uses to load the credentials.
                                    Download the file to the application regularly to ensure that the correct
                                    credentials are used. Implement an AWS Lambda function that rotates the Aurora
                                    credentials every 14 days and uploads these credentials to the file in the S3
                                    bucket.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ137">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer137" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://docs.aws.amazon.com/systems-manager/latest/userguide/systems-manager-parameter-store.html
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ137" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_137" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_137" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_138" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_138" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_138"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 138</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_138" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_138" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company needs to provide its employees with secure access to confidential and sensitive
                            files. The company wants to ensure that the files can be accessed only by authorized users.
                            The files must be downloaded securely to the employees’ devices.<br /><br />The files are
                            stored in an on-premises Windows file server. However, due to an increase in remote usage,
                            the file server is running out of capacity.<br /><br />Which solution will meet these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Migrate the file server to an Amazon EC2 instance in a public subnet. Configure the
                                    security group to limit inbound traffic to the employees’ IP addresses.</li>
                                <li> Migrate the files to an Amazon FSx for Windows File Server file system. Integrate
                                    the Amazon FSx file system with the on-premises Active Directory. Configure AWS
                                    Client VPN.</li>
                                <li> Migrate the files to Amazon S3, and create a private VPC endpoint. Create a signed
                                    URL to allow download.</li>
                                <li> Migrate the files to Amazon S3, and create a public VPC endpoint. Allow employees
                                    to sign on with AWS Single Sign-On.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ138">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer138" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ138" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_138" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_138" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_139" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_139" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_139"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 139</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_139" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_139" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company’s security team requests that network traffic be captured in VPC Flow Logs. The
                            logs will be frequently accessed for 90 days and then accessed
                            intermittently.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to meet these requirements
                            when configuring the logs?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon CloudWatch as the target. Set the CloudWatch log group with an
                                    expiration of 90 days.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Kinesis as the target. Configure the Kinesis stream to always retain the
                                    logs for 90 days.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS CloudTrail as the target. Configure CloudTrail to save to an Amazon S3
                                    bucket, and enable S3 Intelligent-Tiering.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon S3 as the target. Enable an S3 Lifecycle policy to transition the logs
                                    to S3 Standard-Infrequent Access (S3 Standard-IA) after 90 days.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ139">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer139" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ139" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_139" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_139" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_140" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_140" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_140"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 140</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_140" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_140" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is designing a new application that runs in a VPC on Amazon EC2 instances. The
                            application stores data in Amazon S3 and uses Amazon DynamoDB as its database. For
                            compliance reasons, the company prohibits all traffic between the EC2 instances and other
                            AWS services from passing over the public internet.<br /><br />What can a solutions
                            architect do to meet this requirement?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure gateway VPC endpoints to Amazon S3 and DynamoDB.</li>
                                <li> Configure interface VPC endpoints to Amazon S3 and DynamoD</li>
                                <li> Configure a gateway VPC endpoint to Amazon S3. Configure an interface VPC endpoint
                                    to DynamoDB.</li>
                                <li> Configure a gateway VPC endpoint to DynamoDB. Configure an interface VPC endpoint
                                    to Amazon S3.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ140">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer140" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_141" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_141" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_141"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 141</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_141" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_141" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company wants to run its critical applications in containers to meet requirements for
                            scalability and availability. The company prefers to focus on maintenance of the critical
                            applications. The company does not want to be responsible for provisioning and managing the
                            underlying infrastructure that runs the containerized workload.<br /><br />What should a
                            solutions architect do to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon EC2 instances, and install Docker on the instances.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) on Amazon EC2 worker nodes.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) on AWS Fargate.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon EC2 instances from an Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon
                                    ECS)-optimized Amazon Machine Image (AMI).</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ141">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer141" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>

                                <br />
                            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_142" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_142" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_142"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 142</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_142" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_142" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is migrating a large, mission-critical database to AWS. A solutions architect has
                            decided to use an Amazon RDS for MySQL Multi-AZ DB instance that is deployed with 80,000
                            Provisioned IOPS for storage. The solutions architect is using AWS Database Migration
                            Service (AWS DMS) to perform the data migration. The migration is taking longer than
                            expected, and the company wants to speed up the process. The company’s network team has
                            ruled out bandwidth as a limiting factor.<br /><br />Which actions should the solutions
                            architect take to speed up the migration? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Disable Multi-AZ on the target DB instance.</li>
                                <li> Create a new DMS instance that has a larger instance size.</li>
                                <li> Turn off logging on the target DB instance until the initial load is complete.</li>
                                <li> Restart the DMS task on a new DMS instance with transfer acceleration enabled.</li>
                                <li> Change the storage type on the target DB instance to Amazon Elastic Block Store
                                    (Amazon EBS) General Purpose SSD (gp2).</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ142">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer142" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C,D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ142" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_142" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_142" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_143" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_143" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_143"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 143</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_143" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_143" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has deployed a multiplayer game for mobile devices. The game requires live
                            location tracking of players based on latitude and longitude. The data store for the game
                            must support rapid updates and retrieval of locations.<br /><br />The game uses an Amazon
                            RDS for PostgreSQL DB instance with read replicas to store the location data. During peak
                            usage periods, the database is unable to maintain the performance that is needed for reading
                            and writing updates. The game’s user base is increasing rapidly.<br /> <br />What should a
                            solutions architect do to improve the performance of the data tier?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Take a snapshot of the existing DB instance. Restore the snapshot with Multi-AZ
                                    enabled.</li>
                                <li> Migrate from Amazon RDS to Amazon Elasticsearch Service (Amazon ES) with Kibana.
                                </li>
                                <li> Deploy Amazon DynamoDB Accelerator (DAX) in front of the existing DB instance.
                                    Modify the game to use DAX.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an Amazon ElastiCache for Redis cluster in front of the existing DB
                                    instance. Modify the game to use Redis.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ143">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer143" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ143" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_143" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_143" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_144" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_144" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_144"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 144</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_144" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_144" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company with a single AWS account runs its internet-facing containerized web application
                            on an Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS) cluster. The EKS cluster is placed in a
                            private subnet of a VPC. System administrators access the EKS cluster through a bastion host
                            on a public subnet.<br /><br />A new corporate security policy requires the company to avoid
                            the use of bastion hosts. The company also must not allow internet connectivity to the EKS
                            cluster.<br /><br />Which solution meets these requirements MOST cost-effectively?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Set up an AWS Direct Connect connection.</li>
                                <li> Create a transit gateway.</li>
                                <li> Establish a VPN connection.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS Storage Gateway.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ144">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer144" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_145" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_145" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_145"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 145</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_145" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_145" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has a customer relationship management (CRM) application that stores data in an
                            Amazon RDS DB instance that runs Microsoft SQL Server. The company’s IT staff has
                            administrative access to the database. The database contains sensitive data. The company
                            wants to ensure that the data is not accessible to the IT staff and that only authorized
                            personnel can view the data.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to secure the
                            data?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use client-side encryption with an Amazon RDS managed key.</li>
                                <li> Use client-side encryption with an AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) customer
                                    managed key.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon RDS encryption with an AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) default
                                    encryption key.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon RDS encryption with an AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) customer
                                    managed key.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ145">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer145" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>

        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_146" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_146" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_146"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 146</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_146" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_146" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company captures ordered clickstream data from multiple websites and uses batch processing
                            to analyze the data. The company receives 100 million event records, all approximately 1 KB
                            in size, each day. The company loads the data into Amazon Redshift each night, and business
                            analysts consume the data.<br /><br />The company wants to move toward near-real-time data
                            processing for timely insights. The solution should process the streaming data while
                            requiring the least possible operational overhead.<br /><br />Which combination of AWS
                            services will meet these requirements MOST cost-effectively? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Amazon EC2</li>
                                <li> AWS Batch</li>
                                <li> Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS)</li>
                                <li> Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose</li>
                                <li> Amazon Kinesis Data Analytics</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ146">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer146" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C,E
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ146" role="button">
