            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_147" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_147" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_147"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 147</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_147" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_147" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect is designing the architecture for a new web application. The
                            application will run on AWS Fargate containers with an Application Load Balancer (ALB) and
                            an Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL database. The web application will perform primarily read
                            queries against the database.<br /><br />What should the solutions architect do to ensure
                            that the website can scale with increasing traffic? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Enable auto scaling on the ALB to scale the load balancer horizontally.</li>
                                <li> Configure Aurora Auto Scaling to adjust the number of Aurora Replicas in the Aurora
                                    cluster dynamically.</li>
                                <li> Enable cross-zone load balancing on the ALB to distribute the load evenly across
                                    containers in all Availability Zones.</li>
                                <li> Configure an Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) cluster in each
                                    Availability Zone to distribute the load across multiple Availability Zones.</li>
                                <li> Configure Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) Service Auto Scaling with a
                                    target tracking scaling policy that is based on CPU utilization.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ147">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer147" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B,E
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ147" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_147" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_147" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_148" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_148" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_148"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 148</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_148" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_148" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is migrating its applications to AWS. Currently, applications that run on premises
                            generate hundreds of terabytes of data that is stored on a shared file system. The company
                            is running an analytics application in the cloud that runs hourly to generate insights from
                            this data.<br /><br />The company needs a solution to handle the ongoing data transfer
                            between the on-premises shared file system and Amazon S3. The solution also must be able to
                            handle occasional interruptions in internet connectivity.<br /> <br />Which solutions should
                            the company use for the data transfer to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> AWS DataSync</li>
                                <li> AWS Migration Hub</li>
                                <li> AWS Snowball Edge Storage Optimized</li>
                                <li> AWS Transfer for SFTP</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ148">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer148" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://aws.amazon.com/cloud-data-migration/
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ148" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_148" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_148" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_149" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_149" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_149"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 149</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_149" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_149" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company’s database is hosted on an Amazon Aurora MySQL DB cluster in the us-east-1 Region.
                            The database is 4 TB in size. The company needs to expand its disaster recovery strategy to
                            the us-west-2 Region. The company must have the ability to fail over to us-west-2 with a
                            recovery time objective (RTO) of 15 minutes.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect
                            recommend to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create a Multi-Region Aurora MySQL DB cluster in us-east-1 and use-west-2. Use an
                                    Amazon Route 53 health check to monitor us-east-1 and fail over to us-west-2 upon
                                    failure.</li>
                                <li> Take a snapshot of the DB cluster in us-east-1. Configure an Amazon EventBridge
                                    (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule that invokes an AWS Lambda function upon receipt of
                                    resource events. Configure the Lambda function to copy the snapshot to us-west-2 and
                                    restore the snapshot in us-west-2 when failure is detected.</li>
                                <li> Create an AWS CloudFormation script to create another Aurora MySQL DB cluster in
                                    us-west-2 in case of failure. Configure an Amazon EventBridge (Amazon CloudWatch
                                    Events) rule that invokes an AWS Lambda function upon receipt of resource events.
                                    Configure the Lambda function to deploy the AWS CloudFormation stack in us-west-2
                                    when failure is detected.</li>
                                <li> Recreate the database as an Aurora global database with the primary DB cluster in
                                    us-east-1 and a secondary DB cluster in us-west-2. Configure an Amazon EventBridge
                                    (Amazon CloudWatch Events) rule that invokes an AWS Lambda function upon receipt of
                                    resource events. Configure the Lambda function to promote the DB cluster in
                                    us-west-2 when failure is detected.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ149">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer149" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://docs.aws.amazon.com/aws-backup/latest/devguide/eventbridge.html
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ149" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_149" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_149" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_150" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_150" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_150"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 150</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_150" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_150" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect must provide a fully managed replacement for an on-premises solution
                            that allows employees and partners to exchange files. The solution must be easily accessible
                            to employees connecting from on-premises systems, remote employees, and external
                            partners.<br /><br />Which solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use AWS Transfer for SFTP to transfer files into and out of Amazon S3.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS Snowball Edge for local storage and large-scale data transfers.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon FSx to store and transfer files to make them available remotely.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS Storage Gateway to create a volume gateway to store and transfer files to
                                    Amazon S3.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ150">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer150" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>

                            </div>

                                </p>

    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_151" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_151" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_151"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 151</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_151" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_151" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is using Amazon Redshift for analytics and to generate customer reports. The
                            company recently acquired 50 TB of additional customer demographic data. The data is stored
                            in .csv files in Amazon S3. The company needs a solution that joins the data and visualizes
                            the results with the least possible cost and effort.<br /><br />What should a solutions
                            architect recommend to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon Redshift Spectrum to query the data in Amazon S3 directly and join that
                                    data with the existing data in Amazon Redshift. Use Amazon QuickSight to build the
                                    visualizations.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Athena to query the data in Amazon S3. Use Amazon QuickSight to join the
                                    data from Athena with the existing data in Amazon Redshift and to build the
                                    visualizations.</li>
                                <li> Increase the size of the Amazon Redshift cluster, and load the data from Amazon S3.
                                    Use Amazon EMR Notebooks to query the data and build the visualizations in Amazon
                                    Redshift.</li>
                                <li> Export the data from the Amazon Redshift cluster into Apache Parquet files in
                                    Amazon S3. Use Amazon Elasticsearch Service (Amazon ES) to query the data. Use
                                    Kibana to visualize the results.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ151">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer151" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_152" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_152" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_152"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 152</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_152" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_152" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is using AWS Organizations with two AWS accounts: Logistics and Sales. The
                            Logistics account operates an Amazon Redshift cluster. The Sales account includes Amazon EC2
                            instances. The Sales account needs to access the Logistics account’s Amazon Redshift
                            cluster.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect recommend to meet this requirement
                            MOST cost-effectively?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Set up VPC sharing with the Logistics account as the owner and the Sales account as
                                    the participant to transfer the data.</li>
                                <li> Create an AWS Lambda function in the Logistics account to transfer data to the
                                    Amazon EC2 instances in the Sales account.</li>
                                <li> Create a snapshot of the Amazon Redshift cluster, and share the snapshot with the
                                    Sales account. In the Sales account, restore the cluster by using the snapshot ID
                                    that is shared by the Logistics account.</li>
                                <li> Run COPY commands to load data from Amazon Redshift into Amazon S3 buckets in the
                                    Logistics account. Grant permissions to the Sales account to access the S3 buckets
                                    of the Logistics account.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ152">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer152" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://docs.aws.amazon.com/redshift/latest/mgmt/managing-snapshots-console.html
                                </p>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_153" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_153" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_153"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 153</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_153" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_153" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has two VPCs named Management and Production. The Management VPC uses VPNs through
                            a customer gateway to connect to a single device in the data center. The Production VPC uses
                            a virtual private gateway with two attached AWS Direct Connect connections. The Management
                            and Production VPCs both use a single VPC peering connection to allow communication between
                            the applications.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to mitigate any single
                            point of failure in this architecture?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Add a set of VPNs between the Management and Production VPCs.</li>
                                <li> Add a second virtual private gateway and attach it to the Management VPC.</li>
                                <li> Add a second set of VPNs to the Management VPC from a second customer gateway
                                    device.</li>
                                <li> Add a second VPC peering connection between the Management VPC and the Production
                                    VPC.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ153">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer153" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_154" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_154" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_154"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 154</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_154" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_154" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            The following IAM policy is attached to an IAM group. This is the only policy applied to the
                            group. <br /><img id="img48" imageviewer=""
                                src="data:image/png;base64," /><br /><br />What
                            are the effective IAM permissions of this policy for group members?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Group members are permitted any Amazon EC2 action within the us-east-1 Region.
                                    Statements after the Allow permission are not applied.</li>
                                <li> Group members are denied any Amazon EC2 permissions in the us-east-1 Region unless
                                    they are logged in with multi-factor authentication (MFA).</li>
                                <li> Group members are allowed the ec2:StopInstances and ec2:TerminateInstances
                                    permissions for all Regions when logged in with multi-factor authentication (MFA).
                                    Group members are permitted any other Amazon EC2 action.</li>
                                <li> Group members are allowed the ec2:StopInstances and ec2:TerminateInstances
                                    permissions for the us- east-1 Region only when logged in with multi-factor
                                    authentication (MFA). Group members are permitted any other Amazon EC2 action within
                                    the us-east-1 Region.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ154">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer154" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>

                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_154" role="button">

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_155" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_155" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_155"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 155</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_155" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_155" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An ecommerce company is creating an application that requires a connection to a third-party
                            payment service to process payments. The payment service needs to explicitly allow the
                            public IP address of the server that is making the payment request. However, the company’s
                            security policies do not allow any server to be exposed directly to the public
                            internet.<br /><br />Which solution will meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Provision an Elastic IP address. Host the application servers on Amazon EC2
                                    instances in a private subnet. Assign the public IP address to the application
                                    servers.</li>
                                <li> Create a NAT gateway in a public subnet. Host the application servers on Amazon EC2
                                    instances in a private subnet. Route payment requests through the NAT gateway.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an Application Load Balancer (ALB). Host the application servers on Amazon
                                    EC2 instances in a private subnet. Route the payment requests through the ALB.</li>
                                <li> Set up an AWS Client VPN connection to the payment service. Host the application
                                    servers on Amazon EC2 instances in a private subnet. Route the payment requests
                                    through the VPN.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ155">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer155" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ155" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_155" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_155" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>

    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_156" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_156" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_156"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 156</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_156" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_156" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is running an ASP.NET MVC application on a single Amazon EC2 instance. A recent
                            increase in application traffic is causing slow response times for users during lunch hours.
                            The company needs to resolve this concern with the least amount of
                            configuration.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect recommend to meet these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Move the application to AWS Elastic Beanstalk. Configure load-based auto scaling
                                    and time-based scaling to handle scaling during lunch hours.</li>
                                <li> Move the application to Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS). Create an
                                    AWS Lambda function to handle scaling during lunch hours.</li>
                                <li> Move the application to Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS). Configure
                                    scheduled scaling for AWS Application Auto Scaling during lunch hours.</li>
                                <li> Move the application to AWS Elastic Beanstalk. Configure load-based auto scaling,
                                    and create an AWS Lambda function to handle scaling during lunch hours.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ156">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer156" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticbeanstalk/latest/dg/environments-cfg-autoscaling-scheduledactions.html
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ156" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_156" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_156" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_157" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_157" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_157"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 157</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_157" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_157" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An online gaming company is designing a game that is expected to be popular all over the
                            world. A solutions architect needs to define an AWS Cloud architecture that supports
                            near-real-time recording and displaying of current game statistics for each player, along
                            with the names of the top 25 players in the world, at any given time.<br /><br />Which AWS
                            database solution and configuration should the solutions architect use to meet these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon RDS for MySQL as the data store for player activity. Configure the RDS
                                    DB instance for Multi-AZ support.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon DynamoDB as the data store for player activity. Configure DynamoDB
                                    Accelerator (DAX) for the player data.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon DynamoDB as the data store for player activity. Configure global tables
                                    in each required AWS Region for the player data.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon RDS for MySQL as the data store for player activity. Configure
                                    cross-Region read replicas in each required AWS Region based on player proximity.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ157">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer157" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ157" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_157" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_157" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_158" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_158" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_158"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 158</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_158" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_158" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company uses Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL databases for its data tier. The company must
                            implement password rotation for the databases.<br /><br />Which solution meets this
                            requirement with the LEAST operational overhead?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Store the password in AWS Secrets Manager. Enable automatic rotation on the secret.
                                </li>
                                <li> Store the password in AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store. Enable automatic
                                    rotation on the parameter.</li>
                                <li> Store the password in AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store. Write an AWS Lambda
                                    function that rotates the password.</li>
                                <li> Store the password in AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS). Enable automatic
                                    rotation on the customer master key (CMK).</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ158">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer158" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/security/rotate-amazon-rds-database-credentials-automatically-with-aws-secrets-manager/
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ158" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_158" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_158" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_159" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_159" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_159"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 159</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_159" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_159" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect is designing a new hybrid architecture to extend a company's
                            on-premises infrastructure to AWS. The company requires a highly available connection with
                            consistent low latency to an AWS Region. The company needs to minimize costs and is willing
                            to accept slower traffic if the primary connection fails.<br /><br />What should the
                            solutions architect do to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Provision an AWS Direct Connect connection to a Region. Provision a VPN connection
                                    as a backup if the primary Direct Connect connection fails.</li>
                                <li> Provision a VPN tunnel connection to a Region for private connectivity. Provision a
                                    second VPN tunnel for private connectivity and as a backup if the primary VPN
                                    connection fails.</li>
                                <li> Provision an AWS Direct Connect connection to a Region. Provision a second Direct
                                    Connect connection to the same Region as a backup if the primary Direct Connect
                                    connection fails.</li>
                                <li> Provision an AWS Direct Connect connection to a Region. Use the Direct Connect
                                    failover attribute from the AWS CLI to automatically create a backup connection if
                                    the primary Direct Connect connection fails.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ159">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer159" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ159" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_159" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_159" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_160" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_160" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_160"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 160</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_160" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_160" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An online learning company is migrating to the AWS Cloud. The company maintains its student
                            records in a PostgreSQL database. The company needs a solution in which its data is
                            available and online across multiple AWS Regions at all times.<br /><br />Which solution
                            will meet these requirements with the LEAST amount of operational overhead?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Migrate the PostgreSQL database to a PostgreSQL cluster on Amazon EC2 instances.
                                </li>
                                <li> Migrate the PostgreSQL database to an Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL DB instance with
                                    the Multi-AZ feature turned on.</li>
                                <li> Migrate the PostgreSQL database to an Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL DB instance. Create
                                    a read replica in another Region.</li>
                                <li> Migrate the PostgreSQL database to an Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL DB instance. Set up
                                    DB snapshots to be copied to another Region.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ160">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer160" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>

        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_161" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_161" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_161"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 161</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_161" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_161" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is building its web application by using containers on AWS. The company requires
                            three instances of the web application to run at all times. The application must be highly
                            available and must be able to scale to meet increases in demand.<br /><br />Which solution
                            meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use the AWS Fargate launch type to create an Amazon Elastic Container Service
                                    (Amazon ECS) cluster. Create a task definition for the web application. Create an
                                    ECS service that has a desired count of three tasks.</li>
                                <li> Use the Amazon EC2 launch type to create an Amazon Elastic Container Service
                                    (Amazon ECS) cluster that has three container instances in one Availability Zone.
                                    Create a task definition for the web application. Place one task for each container
                                    instance.</li>
                                <li> Use the AWS Fargate launch type to create an Amazon Elastic Container Service
                                    (Amazon ECS) cluster that has three container instances in three different
                                    Availability Zones. Create a task definition for the web application. Create an ECS
                                    service that has a desired count of three tasks.</li>
                                <li> Use the Amazon EC2 launch type to create an Amazon Elastic Container Service
                                    (Amazon ECS) cluster that has one container instance in two different Availability
                                    Zones. Create a task definition for the web application. Place two tasks on one
                                    container instance. Place one task on the remaining container instance.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ161">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer161" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">

                                <p>
                                    https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/task-placement.html<br />https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/containers/amazon-ecs-availability-best-practices/
                                </p>
                            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_162" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_162" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_162"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 162</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_162" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_162" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A gaming company hosts a browser-based application on AWS. The users of the application
                            consume a large number of videos and images that are stored in Amazon S3. This content is
                            the same for all users.<br /><br />The application has increased in popularity, and millions
                            of users worldwide are accessing these media files. The company wants to provide the files
                            to the users while reducing the load on the origin.<br /><br />Which solution meets these
                            requirements MOST cost-effectively?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Deploy an AWS Global Accelerator accelerator in front of the web servers.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an Amazon CloudFront web distribution in front of the S3 bucket.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an Amazon ElastiCache for Redis instance in front of the web servers.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an Amazon ElastiCache for Memcached instance in front of the web servers.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ162">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer162" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://aws.amazon.com/getting-started/hands-on/deliver-content-faster/
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_163" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_163" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_163"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 163</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_163" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_163" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is hosting its website by using Amazon EC2 instances behind an Elastic Load
                            Balancer across multiple Availability Zones. The instances run in an EC2 Auto Scaling group.
                            The website uses Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) volumes to store product manuals
                            for users to download. The company updates the product content often, so new instances
                            launched by the Auto Scaling group often have old data. It can take up to 30 minutes for the
                            new instances to receive all the updates. The updates also require the EBS volumes to be
                            resized during business hours.<br /><br />The company wants to ensure that the product
                            manuals are always up to date on all instances and that the architecture adjusts quickly to
                            increased user demand. A solutions architect needs to meet these requirements without
                            causing the company to update its application code or adjust its website.<br /><br />What
                            should the solutions architect do to accomplish this goal?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Store the product manuals in an EBS volume. Mount that volume to the EC2 instances.
                                </li>
                                <li> Store the product manuals in an Amazon S3 bucket. Redirect the downloads to this
                                    bucket.</li>
                                <li> Store the product manuals in an Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) volume.
                                    Mount that volume to the EC2 instances.</li>
                                <li> Store the product manuals in an Amazon S3 Standard-Infrequent Access (S3
                                    Standard-IA) bucket. Redirect the downloads to this bucket.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ163">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer163" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ163" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_163" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_163" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_164" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_164" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_164"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 164</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_164" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_164" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company runs a fleet of web servers using an Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL DB instance. After
                            a routine compliance check, the company sets a standard that requires a recovery point
                            objective (RPO) of less than 1 second for all its production databases.<br /><br />Which
                            solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Enable a Multi-AZ deployment for the DB instance.</li>
                                <li> Enable auto scaling for the DB instance in one Availability Zone.</li>
                                <li> Configure the DB instance in one Availability Zone, and create multiple read
                                    replicas in a separate Availability Zone.</li>
                                <li> Configure the DB instance in one Availability Zone, and configure AWS Database
                                    Migration Service (AWS DMS) change data capture (CDC) tasks.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ164">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer164" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>

                                <br />
                            </div>

                                </p>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_165" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_165" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_165"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 165</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_165" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_165" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has primary and secondary data centers that are 500 miles (804.7 km) apart and
                            interconnected with high-speed fiber-optic cable. The company needs a highly available and
                            secure network connection between its data centers and a VPC on AWS for a mission-critical
                            workload. A solutions architect must choose a connection solution that provides maximum
                            resiliency.<br /><br />Which solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Two AWS Direct Connect connections from the primary data center terminating at two
                                    Direct Connect locations on two separate devices</li>
                                <li> A single AWS Direct Connect connection from each of the primary and secondary data
                                    centers terminating at one Direct Connect location on the same device</li>
                                <li> Two AWS Direct Connect connections from each of the primary and secondary data
                                    centers terminating at two Direct Connect locations on two separate devices</li>
                                <li> A single AWS Direct Connect connection from each of the primary and secondary data
                                    centers terminating at one Direct Connect location on two separate devices</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ165">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer165" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />

                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

<div class="product-info-box questions">
    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_166" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_166" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_166"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 166</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_166" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_166" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is developing a file-sharing application that will use an Amazon S3 bucket for
                            storage. The company wants to serve all the files through an Amazon CloudFront distribution.
                            The company does not want the files to be accessible through direct navigation to the S3
                            URL.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Write individual policies for each S3 bucket to grant read permission for only
                                    CloudFront access.</li>
                                <li> Create an IAM user. Grant the user read permission to objects in the S3 bucket.
                                    Assign the user to CloudFront.</li>
                                <li> Write an S3 bucket policy that assigns the CloudFront distribution ID as the
                                    Principal and assigns the target S3 bucket as the Amazon Resource Name (ARN).</li>
                                <li> Create an origin access identity (OAI). Assign the OAI to the CloudFront
                                    distribution. Configure the S3 bucket permissions so that only the OAI has read
                                    permission.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ166">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer166" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://aws.amazon.com/premiumsupport/knowledge-center/cloudfront-access-to-amazon-s3/
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ166" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_166" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_166" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_167" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_167" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_167"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 167</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_167" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_167" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company hosts an application on AWS Lambda functions that are invoked by an Amazon API
                            Gateway API. The Lambda functions save customer data to an Amazon Aurora MySQL database.
                            Whenever the company upgrades the database, the Lambda functions fail to establish database
                            connections until the upgrade is complete. The result is that customer data is not recorded
                            for some of the event.<br /><br />A solutions architect needs to design a solution that
                            stores customer data that is created during database upgrades.<br /><br />Which solution
                            will meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Provision an Amazon RDS proxy to sit between the Lambda functions and the database.
                                    Configure the Lambda functions to connect to the RDS proxy.</li>
                                <li> Increase the run time of the Lambda functions to the maximum. Create a retry
                                    mechanism in the code that stores the customer data in the database.</li>
                                <li> Persist the customer data to Lambda local storage. Configure new Lambda functions
                                    to scan the local storage to save the customer data to the database.</li>
                                <li> Store the customer data in an Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) FIFO queue.
                                    Create a new Lambda function that polls the queue and stores the customer data in
                                    the database.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ167">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer167" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ167" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_167" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_167" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_168" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_168" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_168"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 168</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_168" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_168" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company needs to ingest and handle large amounts of streaming data that its application
                            generates. The application runs on Amazon EC2 instances and sends data to Amazon Kinesis
                            Data Streams, which is configured with default settings. Every other day, the application
                            consumes the data and writes the data to an Amazon S3 bucket for business intelligence (BI)
                            processing. The company observes that Amazon S3 is not receiving all the data that the
                            application sends to Kinesis Data Streams.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do
                            to resolve this issue?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Update the Kinesis Data Streams default settings by modifying the data retention
                                    period.</li>
                                <li> Update the application to use the Kinesis Producer Library (KPL) to send the data
                                    to Kinesis Data Streams.</li>
                                <li> Update the number of Kinesis shards to handle the throughput of the data that is
                                    sent to Kinesis Data Streams.</li>
                                <li> Turn on S3 Versioning within the S3 bucket to preserve every version of every
                                    object that is ingested in the S3 bucket.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ168">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer168" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://aws.amazon.com/kinesis/data-firehose/faqs/
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ168" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_168" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_168" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_169" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_169" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_169"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 169</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_169" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_169" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company wants to migrate its accounting system from an on-premises data center to the AWS
                            Cloud in a single AWS Region. Data security and an immutable audit log are the top
                            priorities. The company must monitor all AWS activities for compliance auditing. The company
                            has enabled AWS CloudTrail but wants to make sure it meets these
                            requirements.<br /><br />Which actions should a solutions architect take to protect and
                            secure CloudTrail? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Enable CloudTrail log file validation.</li>
                                <li> Install the CloudTrail Processing Library.</li>
                                <li> Enable logging of Insights events in CloudTrail.</li>
                                <li> Enable custom logging from the on-premises resources.</li>
                                <li> Create an AWS Config rule to monitor whether CloudTrail is configured to use
                                    server-side encryption with AWS KMS managed encryption keys (SSE-KMS).</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ169">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer169" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A,C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ169" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_169" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_169" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_170" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_170" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_170"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 170</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_170" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_170" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An online photo-sharing company stores its photos in an Amazon S3 bucket that exists in the
                            us-west-1 Region. The company needs to store a copy of all existing and new photos in
                            another geographical location.<br /><br />Which solution will meet this requirement with the
                            LEAST operational effort?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create a second S3 bucket in us-east-1. Enable S3 Cross-Region Replication from the
                                    existing S3 bucket to the second S3 bucket.</li>
                                <li> Create a cross-origin resource sharing (CORS) configuration of the existing S3
                                    bucket. Specify us-east-1 in the CORS rule's AllowedOrigin element.</li>
                                <li> Create a second S3 bucket in us-east-1 across multiple Availability Zones. Create
                                    an S3 Lifecycle management rule to save photos into the second S3 bucket.</li>
                                <li> Create a second S3 bucket in us-east-1 to store the replicated photos. Configure S3
                                    event notifications on object creation and update events that invoke an AWS Lambda
                                    function to copy photos from the existing S3 bucket to the second S3 bucket.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ170">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer170" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ170" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_170" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_170" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
