<div class="product-info-box questions">
    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_171" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_171" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_171"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 171</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_171" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_171" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has hired a solutions architect to design a reliable architecture for its
                            application. The application consists of one Amazon RDS DB instance and two manually
                            provisioned Amazon EC2 instances that run web servers. The EC2 instances are located in a
                            single Availability Zone.<br /><br />An employee recently deleted the DB instance, and the
                            application was unavailable for 24 hours as a result. The company is concerned with the
                            overall reliability of its environment.<br /><br />What should the solutions architect do to
                            maximize reliability of the application's infrastructure?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Delete one EC2 instance and enable termination protection on the other EC2
                                    instance. Update the DB instance to be Multi-AZ, and enable deletion protection.
                                </li>
                                <li> Update the DB instance to be Multi-AZ, and enable deletion protection. Place the
                                    EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer, and run them in an EC2 Auto
                                    Scaling group across multiple Availability Zones.</li>
                                <li> Create an additional DB instance along with an Amazon API Gateway and an AWS Lambda
                                    function. Configure the application to invoke the Lambda function through API
                                    Gateway. Have the Lambda function write the data to the two DB instances.</li>
                                <li> Place the EC2 instances in an EC2 Auto Scaling group that has multiple subnets
                                    located in multiple Availability Zones. Use Spot Instances instead of On-Demand
                                    Instances. Set up Amazon CloudWatch alarms to monitor the health of the instances.
                                    Update the DB instance to be Multi-AZ, and enable deletion protection.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ171">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer171" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ171" role="button">

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_171" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_171" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_172" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_172" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_172"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 172</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_172" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_172" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is running a global application. The application’s users submit multiple videos
                            that are then merged into a single video file. The application uses a single Amazon S3
                            bucket in the us-east-1 Region to receive uploads from users. The same S3 bucket provides
                            the download location of the single video file that is produced. The final video file output
                            has an average size of 250 GB.<br /><br />The company needs to develop a solution that
                            delivers faster uploads and downloads of the video files that are stored in Amazon S2. The
                            company will offer the solution as a subscription to users who want to pay for the increased
                            speed.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Enable AWS Global Accelerator for the S3 endpoint. Adjust the application’s upload
                                    and download links to use the Global Accelerator S3 endpoint for users who have a
                                    subscription.</li>
                                <li> Enable S3 Cross-Region Replication to S3 buckets in all other AWS Regions. Use an
                                    Amazon Route 53 geolocation routing policy to route S3 requests based on the
                                    location of users who have a subscription.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon CloudFront distribution and use the S3 bucket in us-east-1 as an
                                    origin. Adjust the application to use the CloudFront URL as the upload and download
                                    links for users who have a subscription.</li>
                                <li> Enable S3 Transfer Acceleration for the S3 bucket in us-east-1. Configure the
                                    application to use the bucket’s S3-accelerate endpoint domain name for the upload
                                    and download links for users who have a subscription.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ172">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer172" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ172" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_172" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_172" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_173" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_173" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_173"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 173</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_173" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_173" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is running a publicly accessible serverless application that uses Amazon API
                            Gateway and AWS Lambda. The application's traffic recently spiked due to fraudulent requests
                            from botnets.<br /><br />Which steps should a solutions architect take to block requests
                            from unauthorized users? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create a usage plan with an API key that is shared with genuine users only.</li>
                                <li> Integrate logic within the Lambda function to ignore the requests from fraudulent
                                    IP addresses.</li>
                                <li> Implement an AWS WAF rule to target malicious requests and trigger actions to
                                    filter them out.</li>
                                <li> Convert the existing public API to a private API. Update the DNS records to
                                    redirect users to the new API endpoint.</li>
                                <li> Create an IAM role for each user attempting to access the API. A user will assume
                                    the role when making the API call.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ173">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer173" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A,E
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://www.google.com/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=&amp;ved=2ahUKEwiR_oHhu5DyAhVvA2MBHWEbDhgQFjAGegQIIhAD&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Faws.amazon.com%2Fblogs%2Fmedia%2Ftag%2Famazon-api-gateway%2Ffeed%2F&amp;usg=AOvVaw2OaNncetRRtgvJ-d60ePyu

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_174" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_174" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_174"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 174</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_174" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_174" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A solutions architect is designing a two-tiered architecture that has separate private
                            subnets for compute resources and the database. An AWS Lambda function that is deployed in
                            the compute subnets needs connectivity to the database.<br /><br />Which solution will
                            provide this connectivity in the MOST secure way?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure the Lambda function to use Amazon RDS Proxy outside the VPC.</li>
                                <li> Associate a security group with the Lambda function. Authorize this security group
                                    in the database's security group.</li>
                                <li> Authorize the compute subnet’s CIDR ranges in the database's security group.</li>
                                <li> During the initialization phase, authorize all IP addresses in the database's
                                    security group temporarily. Remove the rule after the initialization is complete.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ174">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer174" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ174" role="button">

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_174" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_174" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_175" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_175" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_175"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 175</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_175" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_175" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company runs an application in the AWS Cloud and uses Amazon DynamoDB as the database. The
                            company deploys Amazon EC2 instances to a private network to process data from the database.
                            The company uses two NAT instances to provide connectivity to DynamoDB.<br /><br />The
                            company wants to retire the NAT instances. A solutions architect must implement a solution
                            that provides connectivity to DynamoDB and that does not require ongoing
                            management.<br /><br />What is the MOST cost-effective solution that meets these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create a gateway VPC endpoint to provide connectivity to DynamoDB.</li>
                                <li> Configure a managed NAT gateway to provide connectivity to DynamoD</li>
                                <li> Establish an AWS Direct Connect connection between the private network and
                                    DynamoDB.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an AWS PrivateLink endpoint service between the private network and
                                    DynamoDB.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ175">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer175" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>

    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_176" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_176" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_176"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 176</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_176" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_176" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company uses AWS Organizations to manage multiple AWS accounts for different departments.
                            The management account has an Amazon S3 bucket that contains project reports. The company
                            wants to limit access to this S3 bucket to only users of accounts within the organization in
                            AWS Organizations.<br /><br />Which solution meets these requirements with the LEAST amount
                            of operational overhead?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Add the aws:PrincipalOrgID global condition key with a reference to the
                                    organization ID to the S3 bucket policy.</li>
                                <li> Create an organizational unit (OU) for each department. Add the
                                    aws:PrincipalOrgPaths global condition key to the S3 bucket policy.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS CloudTrail to monitor the CreateAccount, InviteAccountToOrganization,
                                    LeaveOrganization, and RemoveAccountFromOrganization events. Update the S3 bucket
                                    policy accordingly.</li>
                                <li> Tag each user that needs access to the S3 bucket. Add the aws:PrincipalTag global
                                    condition key to the S3 bucket policy.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ176">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer176" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_176" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"

                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_177" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_177" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_177"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 177</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_177" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_177" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company wants to build a scalable key management infrastructure to support developers who
                            need to encrypt data in their applications.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do
                            to reduce the operational burden?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use multi-factor authentication (MFA) to protect the encryption keys.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) to protect the encryption keys.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS Certificate Manager (ACM) to create, store, and assign the encryption keys.
                                </li>
                                <li> Use an IAM policy to limit the scope of users who have access permissions to
                                    protect the encryption keys.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ177">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer177" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>

                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://aws.amazon.com/kms/faqs/
                                </p>

            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_178" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_178" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_178"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 178</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_178" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_178" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An entertainment company is using Amazon DynamoDB to store media metadata. The application
                            is read intensive and experiencing delays. The company does not have staff to handle
                            additional operational overhead and needs to improve the performance efficiency of DynamoDB
                            without reconfiguring the application.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect
                            recommend to meet this requirement?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon ElastiCache for Redis.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon DynamoDB Accelerator (DAX).</li>
                                <li> Replicate data by using DynamoDB global tables.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon ElastiCache for Memcached with Auto Discovery enabled.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ178">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer178" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_179" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_179" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_179"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 179</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_179" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_179" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is relocating its data center and wants to securely transfer 50 TB of data to AWS
                            within 2 weeks. The existing data center has a Site-to-Site VPN connection to AWS that is
                            90% utilized.<br /><br />Which AWS service should a solutions architect use to meet these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> AWS DataSync with a VPC endpoint</li>
                                <li> AWS Direct Connect</li>
                                <li> AWS Snowball Edge Storage Optimized</li>
                                <li> AWS Storage Gateway</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ179">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer179" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>

                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ179" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_179" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_179" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_180" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_180" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_180"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 180</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_180" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_180" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company designed a stateless two-tier application that uses Amazon EC2 in a single
                            Availability Zone and an Amazon RDS Multi-AZ DB instance. New company management wants to
                            ensure the application is highly available.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do
                            to meet this requirement?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure the application to use Multi-AZ EC2 Auto Scaling and create an
                                    Application Load Balancer.</li>
                                <li> Configure the application to take snapshots of the EC2 instances and send them to a
                                    different AWS Region.</li>
                                <li> Configure the application to use Amazon Route 53 latency-based routing to feed
                                    requests to the application.</li>
                                <li> Configure Amazon Route 53 rules to handle incoming requests and create a Multi-AZ
                                    Application Load Balancer.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ180">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer180" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ180" role="button">

                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_180" role="button">

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 181</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_181" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_181" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company wants to use a custom distributed application that calculates various profit and
                            loss scenarios. To achieve this goal, the company needs to provide a network connection
                            between its Amazon EC2 instances. The connection must minimize latency and must maximize
                            throughput<br /><br />Which solution will meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Provision the application to use EC2 Dedicated Hosts of the same instance type.
                                </li>
                                <li> Configure a placement group for EC2 instances that have the same instance type.
                                </li>
                                <li> Use multiple AWS elastic network interfaces and link aggregation.</li>
                                <li> Configure AWS PrivateLink for the EC2 instances.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 182</strong>

                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_182" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_182" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company runs a web application that is backed by Amazon RDS. A new database administrator
                            caused data loss by accidentally editing information in a database table. To help recover
                            from this type of incident, the company wants the ability to restore the database to its
                            state from 5 minutes before any change within the last 30 days.<br /><br />Which feature
                            should the solutions architect include in the design to meet this requirement?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Read replicas</li>
                                <li> Manual snapshots</li>
                                <li> Automated backups</li>
                                <li> Multi-AZ deployments</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ182">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer182" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>

                                <br />
                            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_183" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_183" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_183"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 183</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_183" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_183" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is running an application on Amazon EC2 instances. Traffic to the workload
                            increases substantially during business hours and decreases afterward. The CPU utilization
                            of an EC2 instance is a strong indicator of end-user demand on the application. The company
                            has configured an Auto Scaling group to have a minimum group size of 2 EC2 instances and a
                            maximum group size of 10 EC2 instances.<br /><br />The company is concerned that the current
                            scaling policy that is associated with the Auto Scaling group might not be correct. The
                            company must avoid over-provisioning EC2 instances and incurring unnecessary
                            costs.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect recommend to meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Configure Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling to use a scheduled scaling plan and launch an
                                    additional 8 EC2 instances during business hours.</li>
                                <li> Configure AWS Auto Scaling to use a scaling plan that enables predictive scaling.
                                    Configure predictive scaling with a scaling mode of forecast and scale, and to
                                    enforce the maximum capacity setting during scaling.</li>
                                <li> Configure a step scaling policy to add 4 EC2 instances at 50% CPU utilization and
                                    add another 4 EC2 instances at 90% CPU utilization. Configure scale-in policies to
                                    perform the reverse and remove EC2 instances based on the two values.</li>
                                <li> Configure AWS Auto Scaling to have a desired capacity of 5 EC2 instances, and
                                    disable any existing scaling policies. Monitor the CPU utilization metric for 1
                                    week. Then create dynamic scaling policies that are based on the observed values.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ183">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer183" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/as-scaling-simple-step.html
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ183" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_183" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_184" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_184" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_184"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 184</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_184" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_184" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has been running a web application with an Oracle relational database in an
                            on-premises data center for the past 15 years. The company must migrate the database to AWS.
                            The company needs to reduce operational overhead without having to modify the application’s
                            code.<br /><br />Which solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use AWS Database Migration Service (AWS DMS) to migrate the database servers to
                                    Amazon RDS.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon EC2 instances to migrate and operate the database servers.</li>
                                <li> Use AWS Database Migration Service (AWS DMS) to migrate the database servers to
                                    Amazon DynamoDB.</li>
                                <li> Use an AWS Snowball Edge Storage Optimized device to migrate the data from Oracle
                                    to Amazon Aurora.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ184">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer184" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>
                                    https://docs.aws.amazon.com/prescriptive-guidance/latest/patterns/migrate-an-on-premises-oracle-database-to-amazon-rds-for-oracle.html
                                </p>
                            </div>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_185" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_185" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_185"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 185</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_185" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_185" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An Amazon EC2 instance is located in a private subnet in a new VPC. This subnet does not
                            have outbound internet access, but the EC2 instance needs the ability to download monthly
                            security updates from an outside vendor.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to
                            meet these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an internet gateway, and attach it to the VPC. Configure the private subnet
                                    route table to use the internet gateway as the default route.</li>
                                <li> Create a NAT gateway, and place it in a public subnet. Configure the private subnet
                                    route table to use the NAT gateway as the default route.</li>
                                <li> Create a NAT instance, and place it in the same subnet where the EC2 instance is
                                    located. Configure the private subnet route table to use the NAT instance as the
                                    default route.</li>
                                <li> Create an internet gateway, and attach it to the VPC. Create a NAT instance, and
                                    place it in the same subnet where the EC2 instance is located. Configure the private
                                    subnet route table to use the internet gateway as the default route.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ185">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer185" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> A
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>

    <div class="content">
        <div aria-multiselectable="true" class="panel-group" id="accordion" role="tablist">
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_186" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_186" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_186"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 186</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_186" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_186" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company’s facility has badge readers at every entrance throughout the building. When
                            badges are scanned, the readers send a message over HTTPS to indicate who attempted to
                            access that particular entrance.<br /><br />A solutions architect must design a system to
                            process these messages from the sensors. The solution must be highly available, and the
                            results must be made available for the company's security team to analyze.<br /><br />Which
                            system architecture should the solutions architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Launch an Amazon EC2 instance to serve as the HTTPS endpoint and to process the
                                    messages. Configure the EC2 instance to save the results to an Amazon S3 bucket.
                                </li>
                                <li> Create an HTTPS endpoint in Amazon API Gateway. Configure the API Gateway endpoint
                                    to invoke an AWS Lambda function to process the messages and save the results to an
                                    Amazon DynamoDB table.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Route 53 to direct incoming sensor messages to an AWS Lambda function.
                                    Configure the Lambda function to process the messages and save the results to an
                                    Amazon DynamoDB table.</li>
                                <li> Create a gateway VPC endpoint for Amazon S3. Configure a Site-to-Site VPN
                                    connection from the facility network to the VPC so that sensor data can be written
                                    directly to an S3 bucket by way of the VPC endpoint.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ186">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer186" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>

                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ186" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_186" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"

                        </a>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_187" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_187" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_187"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 187</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_187" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_187" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A ride-sharing company stores historical service usage data as structured .csv data files in
                            Amazon S3. A data analyst needs to perform SQL queries on this data. A solutions architect
                            must recommend a solution that optimizes cost-effectiveness for the
                            queries.<br /><br />Which solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Create an Amazon EMR cluster. Load the data. Perform the queries.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Redshift cluster. Import the data. Perform the queries.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL DB cluster. Import the data. Perform the
                                    queries.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Athena database. Associate the data in Amazon S3. Perform the
                                    queries.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ187">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer187" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <div>
                                <br />
                            </div>
                            <div class="bg-light-yellow">
                                <h3><strong>Reference:</strong></h3>
                                <p>

                                </p>

                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_188" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_188" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_188"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 188</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_188" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_188" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is deploying an application that processes streaming data in near-real time. The
                            company plans to use Amazon EC2 instances for the workload. The network architecture must be
                            configurable to provide the lowest possible latency between nodes.<br /><br />Which
                            combination of network solutions will meet these requirements? (Choose two.)
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Enable and configure enhanced networking on each EC2 instance.</li>
                                <li> Group the EC2 instances in separate accounts.</li>
                                <li> Run the EC2 instances in a cluster placement group.</li>
                                <li> Attach multiple elastic network interfaces to each EC2 instance.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) optimized instance types.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ188">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer188" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C,D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ188" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_188" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_188" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_189" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_189" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_189"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 189</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_189" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_189" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has two VPCs that are located in the us-west-2 Region within the same AWS account.
                            The company needs to allow network traffic between these VPCs. Approximately 500 GB of data
                            transfer will occur between the VPCs each month.<br /><br />What is the MOST cost-effective
                            solution to connect these VPCs?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Implement AWS Transit Gateway to connect the VPCs. Update the route tables of each
                                    VPC to use the transit gateway for inter-VPC communication.</li>
                                <li> Implement an AWS Site-to-Site VPN tunnel between the VPCs. Update the route tables
                                    of each VPC to use the VPN tunnel for inter-VPC communication.</li>
                                <li> Set up a VPC peering connection between the VPCs. Update the route tables of each
                                    VPC to use the VPC peering connection for inter-VPC communication.</li>
                                <li> Set up a 1 GB AWS Direct Connect connection between the VPCs. Update the route
                                    tables of each VPC to use the Direct Connect connection for inter-VPC communication.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ189">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer189" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ189" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_189" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_189" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br />
            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_190" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_190" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_190"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 190</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_190" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_190" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company’s HTTP application is behind a Network Load Balancer (NLB). The NLB’s target group
                            is configured to use an Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling group with multiple EC2 instances that run
                            the web service.<br /><br />The company notices that the NLB is not detecting HTTP errors
                            for the application. These errors require a manual restart of the EC2 instances that run the
                            web service. The company needs to improve the application’s availability without writing
                            custom scripts or code.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to meet these
                            requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Enable HTTP health checks on the NLB, supplying the URL of the company’s
                                    application.</li>
                                <li> Add a cron job to the EC2 instances to check the local application’s logs once each
                                    minute. If HTTP errors are detected, the application will restart.</li>
                                <li> Replace the NLB with an Application Load Balancer. Enable HTTP health checks by
                                    supplying the URL of the company’s application. Configure an Auto Scaling action to
                                    replace unhealthy instances.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon CloudWatch alarm that monitors the UnhealthyHostCount metric for
                                    the NLB. Configure an Auto Scaling action to replace unhealthy instances when the
                                    alarm is in the ALARM state.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ190">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer190" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_191" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_191" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_191"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 191</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_191" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_191" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has a mobile game that reads most of its metadata from an Amazon RDS DB instance.
                            As the game increased in popularity developers noticed slowdowns related to the game’s
                            metadata load times.<br />Performance metrics indicate that simply scaling the database will
                            not help. A solutions architect must explore all options that include capabilities for
                            snapshots replication and sub-millisecond response times. What should the solutions
                            architect recommend to solve these issues?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Migrate the database to Amazon Aurora with Aurora Replicas.</li>
                                <li> Migrate the database to Amazon DyramoDB with global tables.</li>
                                <li> Add an Amazon ElastiCache for Redis layer in front of the database.</li>
                                <li> Add an Amazon ElastiCache for Memcached layer in front of the database.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ191">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer191" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 192</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_192" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_192" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is using Site-to-Site VPN connections for secure connectivity to its AWS Cloud
                            resources from on premises. Due to an increase in traffic across the VPN connections to the
                            Amazon EC2 instances, users are experiencing slower VPN connectivity.<br /><br />Which
                            solution will improve the VPN throughput?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Implement multiple customer gateways for the same network to scale the throughput.
                                </li>
                                <li> Use a transit gateway with equal cost multipath routing and add additional VPN
                                    tunnels.</li>
                                <li> Configure a virtual private gateway with equal cost multipath routing and multiple
                                    channels.</li>
                                <li> Increase the number of tunnels in the VPN configuration to scale the throughput
                                    beyond the default limit.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 193</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_193" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_193" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company runs an application that uses multiple Amazon EC2 instances to gather data from
                            its users. The data is then processed and transferred to Amazon S3 for long-term storage. A
                            review of the application shows that there were long periods of time when the EC2 instances
                            were not being used. A solutions architect needs to design a solution that optimizes
                            utilization and reduces costs.<br /> <br />Which solution meets these requirements?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon EC2 in an Auto Scaling group with On-Demand instances.</li>
                                <li> Build the application to use Amazon Lightsail with On-Demand Instances.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon CloudWatch cron job to automatically stop the EC2 instances when
                                    there is no activity.</li>
                                <li> Redesign the application to use an event-driven design with Amazon Simple Queue
                                    Service (Amazon SQS) and AWS Lambda.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ193">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer193" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_194" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_194" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_194"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 194</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_194" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_194" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A media company has an application that tracks user clicks on its websites and performs
                            analytics to provide near-real time recommendations. The application has a Heel of Amazon
                            EC2 instances that receive data from the websites and send the data to an Amazon RDS DB
                            instance. Another fleet of EC2 instances hosts the portion of the application that is
                            continuously checking changes in the database and executing SQL queries to provide
                            recommendations. Management has requested a redesign to decouple the infrastructure. The
                            solution must ensure that data analysts are writing SQL to analyze the data only No data can
                            the lost during the deployment.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect recommend?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Use Amazon Kinesis Data Streams to capture the data from the websites Kinesis Data
                                    Firehose to persist the data on Amazon S3, and Amazon Athena to query the data.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Kinesis Data Streams to capture the data from the websites. Kinesis Data
                                    Analytics to query the data, and Kinesis Data Firehose to persist the data on Amazon
                                    S3.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) to capture the data from the websites,
                                    keep the fleet of EC2 instances, and change to a bigger instance type in the Auto
                                    Scaling group configuration.</li>
                                <li> Use Amazon Simple Notification Service (Amazon SNS) to receive data from the
                                    websites and proxy the messages to AWS Lambda functions that execute the queries and
                                    persist the data. Change Amazon RDS to Amazon Aurora Serverless to persist the data.
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ194">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer194" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>

                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 195</strong>

                <div aria-labelledby="heading_195" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_195" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company has an application running on Amazon EC2 instances in a private subnet. The
                            application needs to store and retrieve data in Amazon S3. To reduce costs, the company
                            wants to configure its AWS resources in a cost-effective manner.<br /><br />How should the
                            company accomplish this?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Deploy a NAT gateway to access the S3 buckets.</li>
                                <li> Deploy AWS Storage Gateway to access the S3 buckets.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an S3 gateway endpoint to access the S3 buckets.</li>
                                <li> Deploy an S3 interface endpoint to access the S3 buckets.</li>
                            </ol>

                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_196" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_196" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_196"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 196</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_196" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_196" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is preparing to migrate its on-premises application to AWS. The application
                            consists of application servers and a Microsoft SQL Server database The database cannot be
                            migrated to a different engine because SQL Server features are used in the application’s NET
                            code. The company wants to attain the greatest availability possible while minimizing
                            operational and management overhead.<br /><br />What should a solutions architect do to
                            accomplish this?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Install SQL Server on Amazon EC2 in a Multi-AZ deployment.</li>
                                <li> Migrate the data to Amazon RDS for SQL Server in a Multi-AZ deployment.</li>
                                <li> Deploy the database on Amazon RDS for SQL Server with Multi-AZ Replicas.</li>
                                <li> Migrate the data to Amazon RDS for SQL Server in a cross-Region Multi-AZ
                                    deployment.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ196">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer196" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> B
                            </div>

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_197" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_197" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_197"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 197</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_197" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_197" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            A company is preparing to store confidential data in Amazon S3. For compliance reasons, the
                            data must be encrypted at rest. Encryption key usage must be logged for auditing purposes.
                            Keys must be rotated every year. Which solution meets these requirements and is the MOST
                            operationally efficient?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Server-side encryption with customer-provided keys (SSE-C)</li>
                                <li> Server-side encryption with Amazon S3 managed keys (SSE-S3)</li>
                                <li> Server-side encryption with AWS KMS (SSE-KMS) customer master keys (CMKs) with
                                    manual rotation</li>
                                <li> Server-side encryption with AWS KMS (SSE-KMS) customer master keys (CMKs) with
                                    automatic rotation</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ197">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer197" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> D
                            </div>
                            </p>

                        <a aria-controls="collapse_197" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_197" role="button">

            <div class="panel panel-default">
                <div class="panel-heading" id="heading_198" role="tab">
                    <a aria-controls="collapse_198" aria-expanded="true" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_198"
                        role="button">
                        <h4 class="panel-title">
                            <strong class="text-uppercase lead">Question: 198</strong>
                            <span class="pull-right"></span>
                        </h4>
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div aria-labelledby="heading_198" class="panel-collapse collapse in" id="collapse_198" role="tabpanel">
                    <div class="panel-body">
                        <p class="lead">
                            An online shopping application accesses an Amazon RDS Multi-AZ DB instance. Database
                            performance is slowing down the application. After upgrading to the next-generation instance
                            type, there was no significant performance improvement.<br /> <br />Analysis shows
                            approximately 700 IOPS are sustained, common queries run for long durations and memory
                            utilization is high.<br /><br />Which application change should a solutions architect
                            recommend to resolve these issues?
                        </p>
                        <div>
                            <ol class="rounded-list" type="A">
                                <li> Migrate the RDS instance to an Amazon Redshift cluster and enable weekly garbage
                                    collection.</li>
                                <li> Separate the long-running queries into a new Multi-AZ RDS database and modify the
                                    application to query whichever database is needed.</li>
                                <li> Deploy a two-node Amazon ElastiCache cluster and modify the application to query
                                    the cluster first and query the database only if needed.</li>
                                <li> Create an Amazon Simple Queue Service (Amazon SQS) FIFO queue for common queries
                                    and query it first and query the database only if needed.</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
                        <div class="collapse" id="answerQ198">
                            <p>
                            <div id="answer198" style="display: none; background: lightblue"> C
                            </div>
                            </p>
                            <br />
                        </div>
                        <a aria-controls="collapseExample" aria-expanded="false" class="btn btn-success"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#answerQ198" role="button">
                        </a>
                        <a aria-controls="collapse_198" aria-expanded="true" class="collapsed btn btn-primary"
                            data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse_198" role="button">
                        </a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
